{"title_page": "Eskimo Nell (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1975 film by Martin Campbell}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Eskimo Nell\n| image_size     =\n| image          = Eskimo Nell FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Martin Campbell]]\n| producer       = [[Stanley Long]]\n| writer         =\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Roy Kinnear]]<br>[[Anna Quayle]]<br>[[Katy Manning]]<br>[[Christopher Timothy]]<br>[[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]]<br>[[Terence Edmond]]<br>[[Rosalind Knight]]<br>[[Diane Langton]]<br>[[Richard Caldicot]]<br>[[Christopher Biggins]]\n| music          = [[Simon Park]]\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = 17 January 1975\n| runtime        =\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n\n'''''Eskimo Nell''''', also known as ''The Ballad of Eskimo Nell'' and as ''The Sexy Saga of Naughty Nell and Big Dick'', is a 1975 [[United Kingdom|British]] film directed by [[Martin Campbell]] and produced by [[Stanley Long]]. Though inspired by \"[[The Ballad of Eskimo Nell]]\", the movie owes little to the original bawdy song.\n\n==Plot==\nBudding film director Dennis Morrison ([[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]]), producer Clive Potter ([[Terence Edmond]]), and screenwriter Harris Tweedle ([[Christopher Timothy]]) are hired by seedy [[erotic film]] producer Benny U. Murdoch ([[Roy Kinnear]]) to make a dirty movie based on the poem \"The Ballad of Eskimo Nell\". However they run into difficulty when each of the production's backers want a completely different style of film made. Then Murdoch makes off with the money and the three have to produce four ''different'' versions of the movie to keep everybody happy - a [[gay]] [[Western (genre)|Western]], a hardcore porno, a [[Kung Fu]]-style musical, and a wholesome family production.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Roy Kinnear]] as Benny U. Murdoch\n* [[Anna Quayle]] as Reverend Mother\n* [[Katy Manning]] as Hermione\n* [[Christopher Timothy]] as Harris Tweedle\n* [[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]] as Dennis Morrison\n* [[Terence Edmond]] as Clive Potter\n* [[Rosalind Knight]] as Lady Longhorn\n* [[Diane Langton]] as Gladys Armitage\n* [[Richard Caldicot]] as Ambrose Cream\n* [[Beth Porter]] as Billie Harris\n* [[Christopher Biggins]] as Jeremy\n* [[Gordon Tanner]] as Big Dick\n* [[Jonathan Adams (British actor)|Jonathan Adams]] as Lord Coltwind\n* [[Lloyd Lamble]] as The Bishop\n* [[Christopher Neil]] as Brendan\n* [[Nicholas Young (actor)|Nicholas Young]] as Deadeye Dick\n* [[Mary Millington]] as Stripping Traffic Warden (uncredited)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Background==\nMany of the film's characters are based on real personalities of the time. Lady Longhorn and Lord Coltwind &mdash; the backers of the wholesome family version &mdash; are thinly veiled caricatures of [[Mary Whitehouse]] and [[Lord Longford]]. Benny U. Murdoch is loosely based on [[Tony Tenser]], head of Tigon films. A more obscure figure the film ridicules is Louis \"Deke\" M. Heyward, the [[London]] representative of AIP ([[American International Pictures]]), who had previously clashed with the film's writer Michael Armstrong in 1969 during the making of Armstrong's directing debut, ''The Haunted House of Horror''. In ''Eskimo Nell'' Heyward is parodied as \"Big Dick\", a crass, foul-mouthed American producer from \"A.W.P Films\", and the backer of the hardcore porno version. A similar character had previously appeared in Armstrong's script for ''[[The Sex Thief]]'' in 1973.  \n\nA pre-fame [[Mary Millington]], then just a jobbing actress and model using her married name Mary Maxted, has a small role in the film as a stripping traffic warden who auditions for a part in the film within a film.  Although Millington appears only fleetingly (with her audition speeded up for comic effect), stills from her scene were used to publicize the film in magazines including ''Titbits''<ref>Titbits (No. 4613, 1\u20137 August 1974, \"Eskimo Nell\"</ref> and ''[[Cinema X]]''.     \n\nThe film is not to be confused with Richard Franklin's 1975 film ''[[The True Story of Eskimo Nell]]'' which was released in the UK as ''Dick Down Under''. Campbell's film was re-titled ''The Sexy Saga of Naughty Nell and Big Dick'' in [[Australia]].\n\n==Home media==\n\n''Eskimo Nell'' was released in a 'special edition' DVD and Blu-ray on 16 February 2015, to celebrate its 40th anniversary (the film was originally released in London in January 1975). The new edition has been digitally re-mastered at [[Pinewood Studios]] and comes with several extra features including the original theatrical trailer (unseen since 1975), an audio commentary by the film's actor-writer [[Michael Armstrong (filmmaker)|Michael Armstrong]] and film historian Simon Sheridan, an 8-page booklet, plus an extensive stills gallery and a newly re-mastered version of Mary Millington's short 1974 film ''Wild Lovers''.\n\n==References==\n<references/> \n*''X-Rated - Adventures of an Exploitation Filmmaker'' by Simon Sheridan (Reynolds & Hearn books) 2008\n*''Keeping the British End Up: Four Decades of Saucy Cinema'' by Simon Sheridan (Titan books) (fourth edition) 2011\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb title|0072953|Eskimo Nell}}\n\n{{Martin Campbell}}\n\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Martin Campbell]]\n[[Category:1975 films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1975 film by Martin Campbell}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Eskimo Nell\n| image_size     =\n| image          = Eskimo Nell FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Martin Campbell]]\n| producer       = [[Stanley Long]]\n| writer         =\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Roy Kinnear]]<br>[[Anna Quayle]]<br>[[Katy Manning]]<br>[[Christopher Timothy]]<br>[[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]]<br>[[Terence Edmond]]<br>[[Rosalind Knight]]<br>[[Diane Langton]]<br>[[Richard Caldicot]]<br>[[Christopher Biggins]]\n| music          = [[Simon Park]]\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = 17 January 1975\n| runtime        =\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n\n'''''Eskimo Nell''''', also known as ''The Ballad of Eskimo Nell'' and as ''The Sexy Saga of Naughty Nell and Big Dick'', is a 1975 [[United Kingdom|British]] film directed by [[Martin Campbell]] and produced by [[Stanley Long]]. Though inspired by \"[[The Ballad of Eskimo Nell]]\", the movie owes little to the original bawdy song.\n\n==Plot==\nBudding film director Dennis Morrison ([[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]]), producer Clive Potter ([[Terence Edmond]]), and screenwriter Harris Tweedle ([[Christopher Timothy]]) are hired by seedy [[erotic film]] producer Benny U. Murdoch ([[Roy Kinnear]]) to make a dirty movie based on the poem \"The Ballad of Eskimo Nell\". However they run into difficulty when each of the production's backers want a completely different style of film made. Then Murdoch makes off with the money and the three have to produce four ''different'' versions of the movie to keep everybody happy - a [[gay]] [[Western (genre)|Western]], a hardcore porno, a [[Kung Fu]]-style musical, and a wholesome family production.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Roy Kinnear]] as Benny U. Murdoch\n* [[Anna Quayle]] as Reverend Mother\n* [[Katy Manning]] as Hermione\n* [[Christopher Timothy]] as Harris Tweedle\n* [[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]] as Dennis Morrison\n* [[Terence Edmond]] as Clive Potter\n* [[Rosalind Knight]] as Lady Longhorn\n* [[Diane Langton]] as Gladys Armitage\n* [[Richard Caldicot]] as Ambrose Cream\n* [[Beth Porter]] as Billie Harris\n* [[Christopher Biggins]] as Jeremy\n* [[Gordon Tanner]] as Big Dick\n* [[Jonathan Adams (British actor)|Jonathan Adams]] as Lord Coltwind\n* [[Lloyd Lamble]] as The Bishop\n* [[Christopher Neil]] as Brendan\n* [[Nicholas Young (actor)|Nicholas Young]] as Deadeye Dick\n* [[Mary Millington]] as Stripping Traffic Warden (uncredited)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Background==\nMany of the film's characters are based on real personalities of the time. Lady Longhorn and Lord Coltwind &mdash; the backers of the wholesome family version &mdash; are thinly veiled caricatures of [[Mary Whitehouse]] and [[Lord Longford]]. Benny U. Murdoch is loosely based on [[Tony Tenser]], head of Tigon films. A more obscure figure the film ridicules is Louis \"Deke\" M. Heyward, the [[London]] representative of AIP ([[American International Pictures]]), who had previously clashed with the film's writer Michael Armstrong in 1969 during the making of Armstrong\u2019s directing debut, ''The Haunted House of Horror''. In ''Eskimo Nell'' Heyward is parodied as \"Big Dick\", a crass, foul-mouthed American producer from \"A.W.P Films\", and the backer of the hardcore porno version. A similar character had previously appeared in Armstrong\u2019s script for ''[[The Sex Thief]]'' in 1973.  \n\nA pre-fame [[Mary Millington]], then just a jobbing actress and model using her married name Mary Maxted, has a small role in the film as a stripping traffic warden who auditions for a part in the film within a film.  Although Millington appears only fleetingly (with her audition speeded up for comic effect), stills from her scene were used to publicize the film in magazines including ''Titbits''<ref>Titbits (No. 4613, 1\u20137 August 1974, \"Eskimo Nell\"</ref> and ''[[Cinema X]]''.     \n\nThe film is not to be confused with Richard Franklin\u2019s 1975 film ''[[The True Story of Eskimo Nell]]'' which was released in the UK as ''Dick Down Under''. Campbell\u2019s film was re-titled ''The Sexy Saga of Naughty Nell and Big Dick'' in [[Australia]].\n\n==Home media==\n\n''Eskimo Nell'' was released in a 'special edition' DVD and Blu-ray on 16 February 2015, to celebrate its 40th anniversary (the film was originally released in London in January 1975). The new edition has been digitally re-mastered at [[Pinewood Studios]] and comes with several extra features including the original theatrical trailer (unseen since 1975), an audio commentary by the film's actor-writer [[Michael Armstrong (filmmaker)|Michael Armstrong]] and film historian Simon Sheridan, an 8-page booklet, plus an extensive stills gallery and a newly re-mastered version of Mary Millington's short 1974 film ''Wild Lovers''.\n\n==References==\n<references/> \n*''X-Rated - Adventures of an Exploitation Filmmaker'' by Simon Sheridan (Reynolds & Hearn books) 2008\n*''Keeping the British End Up: Four Decades of Saucy Cinema'' by Simon Sheridan (Titan books) (fourth edition) 2011\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb title|0072953|Eskimo Nell}}\n\n{{Martin Campbell}}\n\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Martin Campbell]]\n[[Category:1975 films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eskimo_Nell_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Aleksandr Lenderman", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox chess biography\n| name        = Aleksandr Lenderman\n| image       = Lenderman Aleksandr.jpg\n| caption     = Alex Lenderman, Toluca 2011\n| birthname   = \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\n| nickname    = Alex Lenderman\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1989|9|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| title       = [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]]\n| worldchampion = \n| rating      = \n| peakrating  = 2636 (May 2015)\n| FideID      = 2021285\n}}\n'''Aleksandr \"Alex\" Lenderman''' (born September 23, 1989) is an [[United States|American]] [[chess]] [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]]. He won the 2005 [[World Youth Chess Championship#Cadets and Under-16 winners|World Under-16 Championship]] in [[Belfort]] with a score of 9/10 (+8 \u22120 =2),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chessbase.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=2557|title=2005 World Youth Chess Championship|publisher=ChessBase|date=August 4, 2005|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> becoming the first American to win a gold medal at the [[World Youth Chess Championship]] since [[Tal Shaked]] won the [[World Junior Chess Championship|World Junior Championship]] in 1997.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]],<ref>[http://ratings.fide.com/crt/main219026.pdf GM title application] FIDE</ref> he arrived with his family in [[Brooklyn]] when he was four.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/brooklyn-chess-clubs-game-bigger-u-s-champion-gata-kamsky-calling-neighborhood-home-article-1.980139|title=End Zone: Chess is king in King's County|publisher=[[New York Daily News]]|last=Bondy|first=Filip|date=November 19, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He attended [[Edward R. Murrow High School]] in Brooklyn where he played for one of the most successful U.S. high school chess teams of the decade, winning multiple national chess championships.<ref>{{cite book |last=Weinreb |first=Michael |date=2007 |title=The Kings of New York: A Year Among the Geeks, Oddballs and Geniuses Who Make Up America's Top High-School Chess Team |url=https://www.amazon.com/Game-Kings-Oddballs-Geniuses-HighSchool/dp/1592403387 |location=New York |publisher=Avery Publishing |page= |isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>\n\n==Chess career==\nLenderman attended [[Edward R. Murrow High School]] in Brooklyn where, from 2004 to 2007, he was part of the \"dream team\" winning four straight national high school titles for the school, along with now [[International Master]] [[Salvijus Bercys]]. He played an important role in the book ''[[The Kings of New York]]'', written by Michael Weinreb and published by Gotham Press in 2007.\n\nLenderman was first in the 2008 [[USCF Grand Prix]], scoring higher than all the [[grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]]s he competed against by playing and championing in smaller events, including [[World Chess Live|WCL]] [[chess tournament|tournaments]].\n\nIn 2009, he announced after completing his second year at [[Brooklyn College]], he planned to end his studies there and become a professional chess player. He finished first in the 2009 Atlantic Open, in front of several other GMs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://main.uschess.org/content/view/9677/544/|title=Lenderman Takes Atlantic Open|publisher= US Chess Federation|date=August 31, 2009|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also won the 2009 USCF Grand Prix and was a co-champion of the 2009 [[US Open Chess Championship|U.S. Open]]. \nLenderman earned three [[Grandmaster norm]]s in quick succession in the summer of 2009:\n*He earned his first Grandmaster norm at the Copper State International tournament in Mesa AZ, May 29 to June 3, 2009 [http://main.uschess.org/content/view/9434/536].\n*A second GM norm was earned at the Philadelphia International Tournament, June 25\u201329, 2009 [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/05/crosswords/chess/05chess.html?ref=nyregion].\n*He earned his third GM norm on July 5, 2009, at the [[World Open chess tournament|World Open]] in [[Philadelphia]].\n\nIn 2014 he won the 18th Open International Bavarian Chess Championship in [[Bad Wiessee]] on tiebreak over [[Robert Hovhannisyan]] and [[Ante Saric]], after they all tied for first with a score of 7.5/9 points.<ref>{{cite web|title=GM Aleksandr Lenderman is the lucky winner of 18. OIBM Bad Wiessee 2014|url=http://www.chessdom.com/gm-aleksandr-lenderman-is-the-lucky-winner-of-18-oibm-bad-wiessee-2014/|publisher=Chessdom|accessdate=November 1, 2015|date=2014-11-03}}</ref>\n\nLenderman played for USA team in the 2015 [[World Team Chess Championship]] in [[Tsaghkadzor]] and scored 5/7, winning the gold medal on the second board.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chess24.com/en/read/news/china-win-the-world-team-championship|title=China, again. Hello, domination!|publisher=chess24|last=Mart\u00ednez|first=David|date=April 30, 2015|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref>\nHe won the 2015 World Open after beating [[Rauf Mamedov]] in an [[Fast chess|armageddon]] playoff; the two had the best tiebreak among eight players who tied for first place with 7/9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chess.com/news/lenderman-first-on-tiebreak-at-world-open-4392|title=Lenderman 1st on Tiebreak at World Open|publisher=Chess.com|last=Doggers|first=Peter|date=July 7, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Lenderman participated in the [[Chess World Cup 2017|Chess World Cup]] as the No. 104 seed in the field of 128 players. He upset [[Pavel Eljanov]] 2-0 in the first round and [[Aryan Tari]] 1.5-0.5 in the second, before losing on tiebreak in the third round to [[Maxime Vachier-Lagrave]].\n\nLater in the same month, Lenderman played in the Chess.com Isle of Man Open, where he finished with a record of +3-0=6, which included a win against [[Francisco Vallejo Pons]], and a performance rating of 2768. His final score of 6/9 placed him in joint 10th to 18th place.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chess.com Isle of Man Open - Masters|url=http://chess-results.com/tnr303618.aspx?lan=1&art=9&fed=USA&flag=30&wi=821&snr=46|website=Chess-Results.com|accessdate=October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLenderman was born into a Jewish family but converted to Christianity in his 20s.<ref name=Belz2019>{{cite magazine |last=Belz |first=Emily |date=August 31, 2019 |title=Life After Chess |url=https://world.wng.org/2019/08/life_after_chess |magazine=World Magazine |location= |publisher= |access-date=September 10, 2019 }}</ref> He is currently a student at [[Webster University]].<ref name=Belz2019 />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Fide}}\n*[http://www.365chess.com/players/Alex_Lenderman Alex Lenderman] chess games at 365Chess.com\n*{{chessgames player|id=92070}}\n*{{chess.com player|id=AlexanderL}}\n*{{chessclub player|id=manest}}\n\n{{American Chess Masters|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lenderman, Alex}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chess grandmasters]]\n[[Category:American chess players]]\n[[Category:World Youth Chess Champions]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish chess players]]\n[[Category:Edward R. Murrow High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox chess biography\n| name        = Aleksandr Lenderman\n| image       = Lenderman Aleksandr.jpg\n| caption     = Alex Lenderman, Toluca 2011\n| birthname   = \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\n| nickname    = Alex Lenderman\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1989|9|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| title       = [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]]\n| worldchampion = \n| rating      = \n| peakrating  = 2636 (May 2015)\n| FideID      = 2021285\n}}\n'''Aleksandr \"Alex\" Lenderman''' (born September 23, 1989) is an [[United States|American]] [[chess]] [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]]. He won the 2005 [[World Youth Chess Championship#Cadets and Under-16 winners|World Under-16 Championship]] in [[Belfort]] with a score of 9/10 (+8 \u22120 =2),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chessbase.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=2557|title=2005 World Youth Chess Championship|publisher=ChessBase|date=August 4, 2005|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> becoming the first American to win a gold medal at the [[World Youth Chess Championship]] since [[Tal Shaked]] won the [[World Junior Chess Championship|World Junior Championship]] in 1997.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]],<ref>[http://ratings.fide.com/crt/main219026.pdf GM title application] FIDE</ref> he arrived with his family in [[Brooklyn]] when he was four.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/brooklyn-chess-clubs-game-bigger-u-s-champion-gata-kamsky-calling-neighborhood-home-article-1.980139|title=End Zone: Chess is king in King's County|publisher=[[New York Daily News]]|last=Bondy|first=Filip|date=November 19, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He attended [[Edward R. Murrow High School]] in Brooklyn where he played for one of the most successful U.S. high school chess teams of the decade, winning multiple national chess championships.<ref>{{cite book |last=Weinreb |first=Michael |date=2007 |title=The Kings of New York: A Year Among the Geeks, Oddballs and Geniuses Who Make Up America's Top High-School Chess Team |url=https://www.amazon.com/Game-Kings-Oddballs-Geniuses-HighSchool/dp/1592403387 |location=New York |publisher=Avery Publishing |page= |isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>\n\n==Chess career==\nLenderman attended [[Edward R. Murrow High School]] in Brooklyn where, from 2004 to 2007, he was part of the \"dream team\" winning four straight national high school titles for the school, along with now [[International Master]] [[Salvijus Bercys]]. He played an important role in the book ''[[The Kings of New York]]'', written by Michael Weinreb and published by Gotham Press in 2007.\n\nLenderman was first in the 2008 [[USCF Grand Prix]], scoring higher than all the [[grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]]s he competed against by playing and championing in smaller events, including [[World Chess Live|WCL]] [[chess tournament|tournaments]].\n\nIn 2009, he announced after completing his second year at [[Brooklyn College]], he planned to end his studies there and become a professional chess player. He finished first in the 2009 Atlantic Open, in front of several other GMs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://main.uschess.org/content/view/9677/544/|title=Lenderman Takes Atlantic Open|publisher= US Chess Federation|date=August 31, 2009|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also won the 2009 USCF Grand Prix and was a co-champion of the 2009 [[US Open Chess Championship|U.S. Open]]. \nLenderman earned three [[Grandmaster norm]]s in quick succession in the summer of 2009:\n*He earned his first Grandmaster norm at the Copper State International tournament in Mesa AZ, May 29 to June 3, 2009 [http://main.uschess.org/content/view/9434/536].\n*A second GM norm was earned at the Philadelphia International Tournament, June 25\u201329, 2009 [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/05/crosswords/chess/05chess.html?ref=nyregion].\n*He earned his third GM norm on July 5, 2009, at the [[World Open chess tournament|World Open]] in [[Philadelphia]].\n\nIn 2014 he won the 18th Open International Bavarian Chess Championship in [[Bad Wiessee]] on tiebreak over [[Robert Hovhannisyan]] and [[Ante Saric]], after they all tied for first with a score of 7.5/9 points.<ref>{{cite web|title=GM Aleksandr Lenderman is the lucky winner of 18. OIBM Bad Wiessee 2014|url=http://www.chessdom.com/gm-aleksandr-lenderman-is-the-lucky-winner-of-18-oibm-bad-wiessee-2014/|publisher=Chessdom|accessdate=November 1, 2015|date=2014-11-03}}</ref>\n\nLenderman played for USA team in the 2015 [[World Team Chess Championship]] in [[Tsaghkadzor]] and scored 5/7, winning the gold medal on the second board.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chess24.com/en/read/news/china-win-the-world-team-championship|title=China, again. Hello, domination!|publisher=chess24|last=Mart\u00ednez|first=David|date=April 30, 2015|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref>\nHe won the 2015 World Open after beating [[Rauf Mamedov]] in an [[Fast chess|armageddon]] playoff; the two had the best tiebreak among eight players who tied for first place with 7/9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chess.com/news/lenderman-first-on-tiebreak-at-world-open-4392|title=Lenderman 1st on Tiebreak at World Open|publisher=Chess.com|last=Doggers|first=Peter|date=July 7, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Lenderman participated in the [[Chess World Cup 2017|Chess World Cup]] as the No. 104 seed in the field of 128 players. He upset [[Pavel Eljanov]] 2-0 in the first round and [[Aryan Tari]] 1.5-0.5 in the second, before losing on tiebreak in the third round to [[Maxime Vachier-Lagrave]].\n\nLater in the same month, Lenderman played in the Chess.com Isle of Man Open, where he finished with a record of +3-0=6, which included a win against [[Francisco Vallejo Pons]], and a performance rating of 2768. His final score of 6/9 placed him in joint 10th to 18th place.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chess.com Isle of Man Open - Masters|url=http://chess-results.com/tnr303618.aspx?lan=1&art=9&fed=USA&flag=30&wi=821&snr=46|website=Chess-Results.com|accessdate=October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLenderman was born into a Jewish family but converted to Christianity in his 20s.<ref name=Belz2019>{{cite magazine |last=Belz |first=Emily |date=August 31, 2019 |title=Life After Chess |url=https://world.wng.org/2019/08/life_after_chess |magazine=World Magazine |location= |publisher= |access-date=September 10, 2019 }}</ref> He is currently a student at [[Webster University]].<ref name=Belz2019 />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Fide}}\n*[http://www.365chess.com/players/Alex_Lenderman Alex Lenderman] chess games at 365Chess.com\n*{{chessgames player|id=92070}}\n*{{chess.com player|id=AlexanderL}}\n*{{chessclub player|id=manest}}\n\n{{American Chess Masters|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lenderman, Alex}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chess grandmasters]]\n[[Category:American chess players]]\n[[Category:World Youth Chess Champions]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Edward R. Murrow High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "2601:1c0:4500:4220:5019:d5d4:a77f:11f8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aleksandr_Lenderman"}
{"title_page": "The Last American Virgin", "text_new": "{{short description|1982 film by Boaz Davidson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Last American Virgin\n| image          = The Last American Virgin movie poster.jpg\n| caption        = Original film poster\n| director       = [[Boaz Davidson]]\n| producer       = Yoram Globus<br>Menahem Golan<br>David Womark\n| writer         = Boaz Davidson\n| starring = {{plainlist|\n* [[Lawrence Monoson]]\n* [[Diane Franklin]]\n* [[Steve Antin]]\n* [[Joe Rubbo]]\n* [[Louisa Moritz]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Deborah Harry]]<br>Mark Allen\n| cinematography = [[Adam Greenberg (cinematographer)|Adam Greenberg]]\n| editing        = Bruria Davidson\n| distributor    = [[Cannon Film Distributors]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1982|06|26|Japan|1982|07|30|United States}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| gross          = $5.8 million {{small|(North America)}}<ref name=BOM>{{mojo title|lastamericanvirgin|The Last American Virgin}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Last American Virgin''''' is a 1982 American [[sex comedy]] film written and directed by [[Boaz Davidson]]. It is a remake of Davidson's 1978 Israeli film ''[[Eskimo Limon|Eskimo Limon (Lemon Popsicle)]]''.<ref name=NYT3>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Film Society of Lincoln Center Lauds Cannon Films|authorlink=Manohla Dargis|first=Manohla|last=Dargis|date=February 18, 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/19/movies/film-society-of-lincoln-center-lauds-cannon-films.html}}</ref><ref name=\"Maslin\">{{cite web|authorlink=Janet Maslin|last=Maslin |first=Janet |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B04E2DA143BF936A25752C0A965948260 |title=Movie Review - The Last American Virgin - FROLICS IN FLORIDA AND OTHER ANTICS - NYTimes.com |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1983-01-15 |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref>\n\nAfter the success of the original film and its sequels in Israel, Davidson re-teamed with producers [[Golan-Globus]] to attempt to recreate the same success in the United States. Though the film's plot and characters remained largely the same, the setting was updated from 1950s [[Israel]] to then-present day suburban [[Los Angeles]]. The soundtrack, a major facet of both films, was also updated from the original's golden oldies to more contemporary [[New wave music|new wave rock]].\n\n==Plot==\nThe plot closely follows the original Israeli film ''Eskimo Limon'' (''Lemon Popsicle''), and revolves around protagonist Gary, a typical [[high school]] student in early 1980s Los Angeles, and his friends Rick, the slick ladies' man, and David.\n\nMost of the plot involves their numerous attempts to have sex, which are usually successful for Rick and David, but rarely for Gary. Early in the film, the three boys pick up three girls with the promise of [[cocaine]] (instead they use [[Sweet'n Low]]). They go over to Gary's house where he gets stuck with the homely and overweight Millie, a friend of the other two more attractive girls. But their party is interrupted when Gary's parents return home and pandemonium ensues.\n\nA [[love triangle]] develops between Gary, Rick and Karen, a beautiful transfer student to their school who is a virgin that Rick is determined to have sex with.\n\nOne day Gary delivers pizza to Carmela, a woman whose sailor boyfriend is never home, and she tells him she wants more than just pizza. Being too afraid to follow up on it, he goes away and convinces his friends to go along with him. They drop by her home using the pretext they were nearby on a pizza delivery and decided to bring her over some extra pizzas. She lets them in, puts on music and performs a sexy dance routine, to the delight of the boys. She promptly [[fornication|fornicates]] with Rick and David, but her boyfriend Paco returns home just as Gary is about to have his turn, prompting them to flee.\n\nEventually, Rick gets Karen pregnant after they have sex only once, and he leaves her. Gary decides to help Karen pay for her [[abortion]] by selling most of his possessions and borrowing money from his boss. After the abortion, Gary and Karen spend the remainder of the weekend alone together in Gary's grandmother's house. While nursing her back to health, Gary tells Karen that he sincerely loves her. Karen appears to reciprocate and they both share a tender kiss. Karen invites Gary to her 18th birthday party the following week. Gary scrapes up a few more dollars and buys Karen a gold locket for her birthday.\n\nWhen Gary arrives at the party, his dreams of a lasting romance with Karen are shattered when he sees Karen [[making out]] with Rick. Despite what Rick had put Karen through, she apparently decided to take him back. Gary angrily leaves the party without saying a word to either of them, taking Karen's gift with him. Tears streaming down his face, Gary drives home alone, emotionally broken and defeated.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Lawrence Monoson]] as Gary\n* [[Diane Franklin]] as Karen\n* [[Steve Antin]] as Rick\n* [[Joe Rubbo]] as David\n* [[Louisa Moritz]] as Carmela\n* Brian Peck as Victor\n* [[Kimmy Robertson]] as Rose\n* Tessa Richarde as Brenda\n* [[Winifred Freedman]] as Millie\n* Gerri Idol as Roxanne\n* Phil Rubenstein as Gino\n* Roberto Rodriquez as Paco\n* [[Harry Bugin]] as Doctor\n}}\n\n==Home media==\n\n===VHS, CED Videodisc===\nThe film was released on VHS and [[CED Videodisc]] by [[Cannon Films]], November 30, 1983.\n\n===LaserDisc===\nThe film was released by Guild Home Video on LaserDisc with a digital stereo soundtrack in 1984.\n\n===DVD===\nThe Region 1 [[DVD]] was first released in 2002 by [[Cannon Films]]. The only audio option is a 2.0 stereo mix in either English or French. The film was released on blu-ray in 2015 by [[MGM Home Entertainment]]/[[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] & Olive Films.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Last American Virgin\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1982\n| recorded   = 1980\u20131982\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length     = 37:02\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] JS 38279\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Side 1\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| title1          = Teen Angel Eyes\n| extra1          = [[Tommy Tutone]]\n| length1         = 3:30\n| title2          = [[De Do Do Do, De Da Da Da]]\n| extra2          = [[The Police]]\n| length2         = 4:07\n| title3          = [[Whip It (Devo song)|Whip It]]\n| extra3          = [[Devo]]\n| length3         = 2:38\n| title4          = When I Find You\n| extra4          = [[Phil Seymour]]\n| length4         = 5:13\n| title5          = Better Luck Next Time\n| extra5          = [[Oingo Boingo]]\n| length5         = 3:30\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Side 2\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| title6          = Are You Ready for the Sex Girls?\n| extra6          = [[Gleaming Spires]]\n| length6         = 4:00\n| title7          = [[Since You're Gone]]\n| extra7          = [[The Cars]]\n| length7         = 3:30\n| title8          = [[I Know What Boys Like (song)|I Know What Boys Like]]\n| extra8          = [[The Waitresses]]\n| length8         = 3:14\n| title9          = Airwaves\n| extra9          = [[Fortune (band)|The Fortune Band]]\n| length9         = 3:46\n| title10         = [[I Will Follow]]\n| extra10         = [[U2]]\n| length10        = 3:34\n}}\n\nAdditional songs in the film include:\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Oh No (Commodores song)|\"Oh No\"]] - [[The Commodores]]\n* \"[[Open Arms (Journey song)|Open Arms]]\" - [[Journey (band)|Journey]]\n* \"[[Keep on Loving You (song)|Keep on Loving You]]\" - [[REO Speedwagon]]\n* \"[[Just Once]]\" - [[Quincy Jones]] feat. [[James Ingram]]\n* \"[[That's the Way (I Like It)]]\" - [[KC and the Sunshine Band]]\n* \"[[Love Action (I Believe in Love)]]\" - [[The Human League]]\n* \"[[Shake It Up (The Cars song)|Shake It Up]]\" - [[The Cars]]\n* \"[[Besame Mucho]] & Granada\"- Los Fabulosos 3 Paraguayos\n* \"It Aint Easy Comin' Down\" - [[Charlene Marilynn D'Angelo|Charlene]]\n* \"Zero Hour\" - [[The Plimsouls]]\n* \"[[In the Flesh (Blondie song)|In the Flesh]]\" - [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]]\n* \"Espa\u00f1a Cani\" - The Dancing Brass\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Reception==\nResponding to criticism dismissing ''The Last American Virgin'' as distasteful, critic Noel Murray of [[The A.V. Club]] commented \"Really, the film's frankness makes it more honest than its dreamy-eyed descendants; even the shallow treatment of girls captures the point of view of a luckless teenage boy.\"<ref name=\"av\">{{cite web|last=Murray |first=Noel |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-last-american-virgin-dvd,11838/ |title=The Last American Virgin (DVD) &#124; DVD &#124; HomeVideo Review |publisher=The A.V. Club |date=2003-08-19 |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0084234}}\n* {{Amg title|28282}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|last_american_virgin}}\n* [http://www.believermag.com/issues/200605/?read=article_selsberg The Believer article, May 2006]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/lastamericanvirgin Film director Eli Roth conducts Q&A with cast at 25th anniversary screening at the New Beverly Cinema in Hollywood, California. August 8, 2007]\n\n{{Boaz Davidson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Last American Virgin, The}}\n[[Category:1982 films]]\n[[Category:1980s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:1980s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:1980s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:1980s teen romance films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American remakes of foreign films]]\n[[Category:Films about abortion]]\n[[Category:Films about virginity]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Boaz Davidson]]\n[[Category:Golan-Globus films]]\n[[Category:Lemon Popsicle]]\n[[Category:Teenage pregnancy in film]]\n[[Category:Teen sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Teensploitation]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1982 film by Boaz Davidson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Last American Virgin\n| image          = The Last American Virgin movie poster.jpg\n| caption        = Original film poster\n| director       = [[Boaz Davidson]]\n| producer       = Yoram Globus<br>Menahem Golan<br>David Womark\n| writer         = Boaz Davidson\n| starring = {{plainlist|\n* [[Lawrence Monoson]]\n* [[Diane Franklin]]\n* [[Steve Antin]]\n* [[Joe Rubbo]]\n* [[Louisa Moritz]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Deborah Harry]]<br>Mark Allen\n| cinematography = [[Adam Greenberg (cinematographer)|Adam Greenberg]]\n| editing        = Bruria Davidson\n| distributor    = [[Cannon Film Distributors]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1982|06|26|Japan|1982|07|30|United States}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| gross          = $5.8 million {{small|(North America)}}<ref name=BOM>{{mojo title|lastamericanvirgin|The Last American Virgin}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Last American Virgin''''' is a 1982 American [[sex comedy]] film written and directed by [[Boaz Davidson]]. It is a remake of Davidson's 1978 Israeli film ''[[Eskimo Limon|Eskimo Limon (Lemon Popsicle)]]''.<ref name=NYT3>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Film Society of Lincoln Center Lauds Cannon Films|authorlink=Manohla Dargis|first=Manohla|last=Dargis|date=February 18, 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/19/movies/film-society-of-lincoln-center-lauds-cannon-films.html}}</ref><ref name=\"Maslin\">{{cite web|authorlink=Janet Maslin|last=Maslin |first=Janet |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/