/shows/design-and-architecture/peter-loughrey-obit Peter Loughrey, founder of Los Angeles Modern Auctions, leaves us at 52], KCRW, March 19, 2020\n* [https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/peter-loughrey-esteemed-auctioneer-dies Peter Loughrey, Esteemed Auctioneer and Curator, Dies After Battle with Cancer], ''Architectural Digest'', March 18, 2020\n* [https://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/the-irresistible-rise-of-light-and-space/ The irresistible rise of Light and Space], ''The Art Newspaper'', October 20, 2017\n* [https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/18/how-peter-loughrey-went-from-homeless-to-a-millionaire-art-dealer.html How Peter Loughrey Went from Homeless to A Millionaire Art Dealer], CNBC, July 9, 2017\n*[https://www.culturetype.com/2017/03/06/auction-record-alma-thomass-1969-vision-of-spring-flowers-yields-more-than-300k/ Auction Record: Alma Thomas\u2019s 1969 Vision of \u2018Spring Flowers\u2019 Yields More Than $300K], Culture Type, March 6, 2017\n* [https://fortune.com/2016/11/11/los-angeles-modern-auctions-buying-art/ Why It\u2019s a Great Time to Be Buying Collectible Art], ''Fortune'', November 11, 2016\n* [https://issuu.com/surfacemag/docs/surface_february_tadoando_2015_issu/54/ A rare sculpture by 20th-century Italian-American artist Harry Bertoia enters the market], ''Surface'', February 2015\n* [https://www.artmarketmonitor.com/2014/09/17/artelligence-podcast-peter-loughrey-los-angeles-modern-auctions/ Artelligence Podcast: Peter Loughrey, Los Angeles Modern Auctions], September 17, 2014\n* [https://www.latimes.com/home/la-hm-billy-haines-auction-20140517-story.html William Haines\u2019 custom designs from 1960 to be auctioned], ''Los Angeles Times'', May 17, 2014\n* [https://www.artspace.com/magazine/interviews_features/how_i_collect/how_i_collect_peter_loughrey-51956/ L.A. Auctioneer Peter Loughrey on Mixing Art and Design], Artspace, January 7, 2014\n* [https://www.latimes.com/home/la-hm-modern-auctions-photos-photogallery.html/ L.A. Modern Auctions: Record haul for 2011 design sale], ''Los Angeles Times'', 2011\n* [https://issuu.com/cdigital/docs/62/38/ Moving Pictures: The collection of a lifetime is ready for a new home], ''C Magazine'', October 2011\n* [http://nytimes.com/2011/02/25/arts/design/25antiques.html A Sotheby\u2019s Catalog With Some Juicy Details], ''New York Times'', February 24, 2011\n* [https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2009-may-30-hm-scoutauction30-story.html Style and wit], ''Los Angeles Times'', May 30, 2009\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/05/arts/antiques-it-s-modern-no-longer-but-precious.html It's Modern No Longer, But Precious], ''New York Times'', December 5, 2003\n* [https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1999-oct-14-cl-22003-story.html/ Thoroughly Modern Milieu], ''Los Angeles Times'', October 14, 1999\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lamodern.com/ Los Angeles Modern Auctions (LAMA) official website]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* Loughrey, Peter (Spring 2010). [http://www.idealmodern.com/p/current-issue.html Baby, Are You for Real?], Modern Magazine. Retrieved 04-13-2010\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/roadshow/appraisers/peter-loughrey/appraisals Appraisals by Peter Loughrey], Antiques Roadshow. Retrieved 04-15-2010\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110715023552/http://community.ovationtv.com/_Forbes-SOLD-LAMA-Clip/video/374281/16878.html Forbes' SOLD!: LAMA clip], Ovation TV. Retrieved 05-25-2011\n* [http://youhavebeenheresometime.blogspot.com/search/label/peter%20loughrey YHBHS Interview], YHBHS. Retrieved 05-25-2011\n* Heet, Erika (October 2010). [http://www.dwell.com/articles/lamas-50th.html LAMA's 50th], Dwell Magazine. Retrieved 05-25-2011\n\n[[Category:American auction houses]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1992]]\n", "name_user": "Ratbabyjones", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePress:Added one press article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_Angeles_Modern_Auctions"}
{"title_page": "AROCK", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = AROCK\n| image               =\n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = Angel Castillo\n| birth_date          = October 8, 1988\n| birth_place         = [[San Diego]], [[California]]\n| origin              = United States\n| genre               =\n| occupation          = DJ and music producer\n}}\n'''Angel \u201cAROCK\u201d Castillo''' (born July 9, 1987) is an American DJ and music manager. He is well-known as the founder of digital music services BPM Supreme and BPM Latino.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/laurencoleman/2019/09/22/the-new-consumer-gatekeepers-inside-the-hidden-power-of-the-dj-industry-20/ |title=The New Consumer Gatekeepers: Inside the Hidden Power Of The DJ Industry 2.0 |publisher=Forbes |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHe has worked with many notable artists, such as [[Wiz Khalifa]], [[Rob $tone]], [[DJ Nelson]], and [[DJ Kazzanova]], among others.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAROCK grew up in San Diego, California. From an early age, he was a fan of music and disc jockey culture. His father recognized his passion and gifted him DJ equipment at the age of 12<ref>{{cite web| url=https://mixmag.net/feature/key-player-angel-arock-castillo-ceo-of-bpm-supreme |title=BPM Supreme CEO Angel \u2018AROCK\u2019 Castillo: \"We\u2019re always thinking of new ways to keep innovating\" |publisher=MixMag |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> so he could begin learning the art of DJing.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sdvoyager.com/interview/meet-angel-arock-castillo-bpm-supreme-downtown/ |title=Meet Angel \u201cAROCK\u201d Castillo of BPM Supreme in Downtown |publisher=SD Voyager |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nDuring and after high school, AROCK performed as a DJ in local San Diego nightclubs and worked at San Diego\u2019s top radio station, Z90.3 ([[XHITZ-FM]]). AROCK would regularly distribute his DJ mixes to other DJs and stayed on top of the newest trends in music-making, such as digital music software for mixing and producing music.\n\nAROCK graduated from [[Mar Vista High School]] in [[Imperial Beach, California]] in 2005.\n\n==Career==\nAROCK worked at San Diego\u2019s Z90.3 ([[XHITZ-FM]]) from 2006 to 2010. During his time in radio, AROCK was introduced to many artists, including rapper, singer, and songwriter [[Wiz Khalifa]], and his label [[Warner Records]] Inc. (formerly [[Warner Bros. Records]]). AROCK recognized star potential in the single, \"Say Yeah\" and is credited as one of the first DJs to support and break the record on San Diego radio.\n\nThrough AROCK\u2019s various businesses in [[San Diego]], he has helped revive the growing music and DJ cultural scene in the city. Although San Diego was in close proximity to [[Los Angeles]], many artists would typically pass by San Diego during promotional tours. However, with AROCK\u2019s businesses such as BPM Supreme<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.irvinecompanyoffice.com/newsandinsights/news/bpm-supreme-is-rewriting-the-rules-for-the-dj-industry-irvine-company-rewrote-their-lease/ |title=\nBPM Supreme is Rewriting the Rules for the DJ Industry. Irvine Company Rewrote Their Lease. |publisher=Irvine Company Office |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.roland.com/us/company/press_releases/2019/ROLAND-AND-BPM-SUPREME-INTRODUCE-SERATO-X-ROLAND-T/ |title=Roland and BPM Supreme Introduce Serato X Roland TR-Sync 'Ready' Tracks |publisher=Roland |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and BPM Latino, would bring artists and talent to the city, his offices, and local radio stations.<ref name=medium>{{cite web| url=https://medium.com/authority-magazine/rising-star-angel-arock-castillo-just-keep-moving-forward-no-matter-what-kind-of-push-back-you-4c09aae110b0 |title=Rising Star Angel \u201cAROCK\u201d Castillo: \u201cJust keep moving forward no matter what kind of push-back you get or how many people tell you your ideas are crazy\u201d |publisher=Medium |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nLater, AROCK also founded online DJ store BPM Supply, music management agency BPM MGMT Co., and design agency Ensemble Design Co.\n\nAROCK founded BPM MGMT Co. in 2019. The roster of artists currently signed to BPM MGMT Co. include hip hop artists [[Rossi Rock]] and [[Rob $tone]],<ref>{{cite web| url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.53623/title.bpm-supreme-ceo-angel-arock-castillo-is-just-getting-started |title=BPM Supreme CEO Angel 'AROCK' Castillo Is Just Getting Started |publisher=Hip Hop DX |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Latin DJs and record producers [[DJ Nelson]] and [[DJ Kazzanova]], UK-based DJ and renowned turntablist [[DJ Angelo]], and DJ, producer, and vocalist [[Rhiannon Roze]].\n\n===BPM Supreme===\nIn 2006, BPM Supreme originated as a local record pool in San Diego, CA providing physical data discs full of the month\u2019s top music to local DJs. With just two employees, AROCK would begin distributing monthly music and mixes on CDs, building momentum and meeting valuable business partners who would help eventually help his CD distribution turn into a fully functioning digital platform.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://peopleenespanol.com/chica/angel-arock-castillo-interview-bpm-supreme/ |title=Angel Castillo's Success Story |publisher=People en Espa\u00f1ol |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=medium/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://sdvoyager.com/interview/meet-angel-arock-castillo-bpm-supreme-downtown/ |title=Meet Angel \u201cAROCK\u201d Castillo of BPM Supreme in Downtown |publisher=SD Voyager |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, digital DJing had started to gain more popularity, and AROCK realized there was a need in the industry for digital format-focused music/record pools. In 2011, BPM Supreme officially became an online digital music delivery service.\n\nIn 2019, BPM Supreme has more than 40 employees and two locations in [[downtown San Diego]], California and Hollywood, Los Angeles, California. BPM Supreme has signed music licensing agreements with major records labels such as [[Sony Music Entertainment]], [[Universal Music Group]], [[Empire Records]], [[Dim Mak Records]], [[Mad Decent]], and other independent record labels.\n\nNotable DJs who regularly use BPM Supreme include [[DJ Jazzy Jeff]], [[Z-Trip]], [[A-Trak]], [[The Chainsmokers]], [[DJ Snoopadelic]], [[Sky Rompiendo]], [[Deorro]], [[3lau]], and [[DJ Chuckie]].\n\nBPM Supreme has helped break records for many artists, DJs, and producers, and has received a commemorative plaque to recognize the role it had in helping rapper [[Tyga]]\u2019s hit single \u201cTaste\u201d reach 5x platinum in the United States by the RIAA.\n\n==Media==\nAROCK has been featured in print stories found in well-known publications such as ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[People en Espa\u00f1ol]]'', ''[[Mixmag]]'', ''[[DJ Times]]'',<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.decodedmagazine.com/bpm-supreme-launches-bpm-news/ |title=BPM Supreme launches BPM News featuring trusted news channels, DJ times, digital DJ tips, Ableton, and more\u2026 |publisher=Decoded Magazine |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.djtimes.com/2019/01/bpm-supreme-reveals-new-mobile-app-for-djs/ |title=BPM Supreme Reveals New Mobile App for DJs |publisher=DJ Times |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> ''[[Thrive Global]]'', and ''[[Authority Magazine]]''. He has also been featured in San Diego\u2019s prominent local publication, the ''[[San Diego Voyager Magazine]]''.\n\n==Television==\nAROCK was a guest on [[Discovery Family|The Hub]] on [[LATV]]. The program aired on November 12, 2019 in both English and Spanish in 50 markets across the United States.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://arocksworld.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:AROCK}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American DJs]]\n[[Category:American music managers]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego]]\n[[Category:Record producers from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = AROCK\n| image               =\n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = Angel Castillo\n| birth_date          = October 8, 1988\n| birth_place         = [[San Diego]], [[California]]\n| origin              = United States\n| genre               =\n| occupation          = DJ and music producer\n}}\n'''Angel \u201cAROCK\u201d Castillo''' (born July 9, 1987) is an American DJ and music manager. He is well-known as the founder of digital music services BPM Supreme and BPM Latino.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/laurencoleman/2019/09/22/the-new-consumer-gatekeepers-inside-the-hidden-power-of-the-dj-industry-20/ |title=The New Consumer Gatekeepers: Inside the Hidden Power Of The DJ Industry 2.0 |publisher=Forbes |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHe has worked with many notable artists, such as [[Wiz Khalifa]], [[Rob $tone]], [[DJ Nelson]], and [[DJ Kazzanova]], among others.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAROCK grew up in San Diego, California. From an early age, he was a fan of music and disc jockey culture. His father recognized his passion and gifted him DJ equipment at the age of 12<ref>{{cite web| url=https://mixmag.net/feature/key-player-angel-arock-castillo-ceo-of-bpm-supreme |title=BPM Supreme CEO Angel \u2018AROCK\u2019 Castillo: \"We\u2019re always thinking of new ways to keep innovating\" |publisher=MixMag |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> so he could begin learning the art of DJing.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sdvoyager.com/interview/meet-angel-arock-castillo-bpm-supreme-downtown/ |title=Meet Angel \u201cAROCK\u201d Castillo of BPM Supreme in Downtown |publisher=SD Voyager |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nDuring and after high school, AROCK performed as a DJ in local San Diego nightclubs and worked at San Diego\u2019s top radio station, Z90.3 ([[XHITZ-FM]]). AROCK would regularly distribute his DJ mixes to other DJs and stayed on top of the newest trends in music-making, such as digital music software for mixing and producing music.\n\nAROCK graduated from [[Mar Vista High School]] in [[Imperial Beach, California]] in 2005.\n\n==Career==\nAROCK worked at San Diego\u2019s Z90.3 ([[XHITZ-FM]]) from 2006 to 2010. During his time in radio, AROCK was introduced to many artists, including rapper, singer, and songwriter [[Wiz Khalifa]], and his label [[Warner Records]] Inc. (formerly [[Warner Bros. Records]]). AROCK recognized star potential in the single, \"Say Yeah\" and is credited as one of the first DJs to support and break the record on San Diego radio.\n\nThrough AROCK\u2019s various businesses in [[San Diego]], he has helped revive the growing music and DJ cultural scene in the city. Although San Diego was in close proximity to [[Los Angeles]], many artists would typically pass by San Diego during promotional tours. However, with AROCK\u2019s businesses such as BPM Supreme<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.irvinecompanyoffice.com/newsandinsights/news/bpm-supreme-is-rewriting-the-rules-for-the-dj-industry-irvine-company-rewrote-their-lease/ |title=\nBPM Supreme is Rewriting the Rules for the DJ Industry. Irvine Company Rewrote Their Lease. |publisher=Irvine Company Office |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.roland.com/us/company/press_releases/2019/ROLAND-AND-BPM-SUPREME-INTRODUCE-SERATO-X-ROLAND-T/ |title=Roland and BPM Supreme Introduce Serato X Roland TR-Sync 'Ready' Tracks |publisher=Roland |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and BPM Latino, would bring artists and talent to the city, his offices, and local radio stations.<ref name=\"medium\">{{cite web| url=https://medium.com/authority-magazine/rising-star-angel-arock-castillo-just-keep-moving-forward-no-matter-what-kind-of-push-back-you-4c09aae110b0 |title=Rising Star Angel \u201cAROCK\u201d Castillo: \u201cJust keep moving forward no matter what kind of push-back you get or how many people tell you your ideas are crazy\u201d |publisher=Medium |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nLater, AROCK also founded online DJ store BPM Supply, music management agency BPM MGMT Co., and design agency Ensemble Design Co.\n\nAROCK founded BPM MGMT Co. in 2019. The roster of artists currently signed to BPM MGMT Co. include hip hop artists [[Rossi Rock]] and [[Rob $tone]],<ref>{{cite web| url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.53623/title.bpm-supreme-ceo-angel-arock-castillo-is-just-getting-started |title=BPM Supreme CEO Angel 'AROCK' Castillo Is Just Getting Started |publisher=Hip Hop DX |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Latin DJs and record producers [[DJ Nelson]] and [[DJ Kazzanova]], UK-based DJ and renowned turntablist [[DJ Angelo]], and DJ, producer, and vocalist [[Rhiannon Roze]].\n\n===BPM Supreme===\nIn 2006, BPM Supreme originated as a local record pool in San Diego, CA providing physical data discs full of the month\u2019s top music to local DJs. With just two employees, AROCK would begin distributing monthly music and mixes on CDs, building momentum and meeting valuable business partners who would help eventually help his CD distribution turn into a fully functioning digital platform.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://peopleenespanol.com/chica/angel-arock-castillo-interview-bpm-supreme/ |title= |publisher=People en Espa\u00f1ol |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=thrive/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://sdvoyager.com/interview/meet-angel-arock-castillo-bpm-supreme-downtown/ |title= |publisher=SD Voyager |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, digital DJing had started to gain more popularity, and AROCK realized there was a need in the industry for digital format-focused music/record pools. In 2011, BPM Supreme officially became an online digital music delivery service.\n\nIn 2019, BPM Supreme has more than 40 employees and two locations in [[downtown San Diego]], California and Hollywood, Los Angeles, California. BPM Supreme has signed music licensing agreements with major records labels such as [[Sony Music Entertainment]], [[Universal Music Group]], [[Empire Records]], [[Dim Mak Records]], [[Mad Decent]], and other independent record labels.\n\nNotable DJs who regularly use BPM Supreme include [[DJ Jazzy Jeff]], [[Z-Trip]], [[A-Trak]], [[The Chainsmokers]], [[DJ Snoopadelic]], [[Sky Rompiendo]], [[Deorro]], [[3lau]], and [[DJ Chuckie]].\n\nBPM Supreme has helped break records for many artists, DJs, and producers, and has received a commemorative plaque to recognize the role it had in helping rapper [[Tyga]]\u2019s hit single \u201cTaste\u201d reach 5x platinum in the United States by the RIAA.\n\n==Media==\nAROCK has been featured in print stories found in well-known publications such as ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[People en Espa\u00f1ol]]'', ''[[Mixmag]]'', ''[[DJ Times]]'',<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.decodedmagazine.com/bpm-supreme-launches-bpm-news/ |title=BPM Supreme launches BPM News featuring trusted news channels, DJ times, digital DJ tips, Ableton, and more\u2026 |publisher=Decoded Magazine |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.djtimes.com/2019/01/bpm-supreme-reveals-new-mobile-app-for-djs/ |title=BPM Supreme Reveals New Mobile App for DJs |publisher=DJ Times |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> ''[[Thrive Global]]'', and ''[[Authority Magazine]]''. He has also been featured in San Diego\u2019s prominent local publication, the ''[[San Diego Voyager Magazine]]''.\n\n==Television==\nAROCK was a guest on [[Discovery Family|The Hub]] on [[LATV]]. The program aired on November 12, 2019 in both English and Spanish in 50 markets across the United States.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://arocksworld.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:AROCK}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American DJs]]\n[[Category:American music managers]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego]]\n[[Category:Record producers from California]]\n", "name_user": "Yumurtayurt", "label": "