{"title_page": "Quantum of Solace", "text_new": "{{short description|2008 film by Marc Forster}}\n{{about|the film|other uses|Quantum of Solace (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name = Quantum of Solace\n|image = Quantum of Solace - UK cinema poster.jpg\n|alt = Empire Design's poster for ''Quantum of Solace''\n|caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Marc Forster]]\n| producer = \n  {{plainlist|\n*[[Michael G. Wilson]]\n*[[Barbara Broccoli]]\n}}\n| writer = \n  {{plainlist|\n*[[Paul Haggis]]\n*[[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade|Neal Purvis<br>Robert Wade]]}} <!-- DO NOT ADD \"MARC FORSTER\" OR \"DANIEL CRAIG\" HERE, THEY ARE MENTIONED IN PROSE -->\n| based on = {{Based on|[[James Bond (literary character)|James Bond]]|[[Ian Fleming]]}}\n|starring = \n  {{plainlist|\n*[[Daniel Craig]]\n*[[Olga Kurylenko]]\n*[[Mathieu Amalric]]\n*[[Gemma Arterton]]\n*[[Giancarlo Giannini]]\n*[[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]]\n*[[Judi Dench]]\n}}\n| music = [[David Arnold]]\n| cinematography = [[Roberto Schaefer]]\n| editing = \n  {{plainlist |\n*[[Matt Chesse]]\n*[[Richard Pearson (film editor)|Richard Pearson]]\n}}\n| studio = [[Eon Productions]]<br>[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures]]<br>[[Columbia Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/64729?sid=b7c9f0f6-6e18-402f-b725-a18e455f6bfc&sr=3.7816277&cp=1&pos=0|title=AFI-Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com}}</ref>\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|2008|10|29|[[London]]|2008|10|31|United Kingdom|2008|11|14|United States}}<!-- WP:FILMRELEASE -->\n| runtime = 106 minutes\n| country = {{plainlist|\n* United Kingdom<ref name=bfi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8bf92120|title=Quantum of Solace (2008)|work=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=29 May 2016}}</ref>\n* United States<ref name=bfi/>\n* Italy\n}}\n| language = English\n| budget = $230 million<ref name=artfilm/>\n| gross = $589.5 million<ref name=\"bom\">{{cite web|title=Quantum of Solace (2008)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jamesbond22.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Quantum of Solace''''' is a 2008 [[spy film]] and the twenty-second in the [[List of James Bond films|''James Bond'' series]] produced by [[Eon Productions]]. Directed by [[Marc Forster]] and written by [[Paul Haggis]], [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]], it is a direct sequel to [[Casino Royale (2006 film)|''Casino Royale'']], and the second film to star [[Daniel Craig]] as the fictional [[MI6]] agent [[James Bond]]. The film also stars [[Olga Kurylenko]], [[Mathieu Amalric]], [[Gemma Arterton]], [[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]], and [[Judi Dench]].  In the film, Bond seeks revenge for the death of his lover, [[Vesper Lynd]], and is assisted by [[Camille Montes]], who is plotting revenge for the murder of her own family.  The trail eventually leads them to wealthy businessman [[Dominic Greene]], a member of the [[Quantum (James Bond)|Quantum]] organisation<!-- \"Organisation\" is British spelling, and the article uses British spelling -->, which intends to stage a ''[[coup d'\u00e9tat]]'' in Bolivia to [[Water privatization in Bolivia|seize control of their water supply]]. \n\nProducer [[Michael G. Wilson]] developed the film's plot while the previous film in the series, [[Casino Royale (2006 film)|''Casino Royale'']], was being shot.  Purvis, Wade, and Haggis contributed to the script.  Although Craig and Forster wrote some sections themselves during the [[2007\u20132008 Writers Guild of America strike|screenwriter strike]],<ref name=Goldberg /> they received no such credits in the final cut.  The title was chosen from a 1959<!-- The story was first published in November 1959 in ''Modern Woman's Magazine'', q.v. For Your Eyes Only (short story collection) for the citation --> short story in [[Ian Fleming]]'s ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]'', though the film does not contain any elements of that story.  Location filming took place in Mexico, Panama, Chile, Italy, Austria and Wales, while interior sets were built and filmed at [[Pinewood Studios]].  Forster aimed to make a modern film that also featured classic cinema motifs: a vintage [[Douglas DC-3]] was used for a flight sequence, and [[Dennis Gassner]]'s set designs are reminiscent of [[Ken Adam]]'s work on several early ''Bond'' films.  Taking a course away from the usual [[List of James Bond villains|Bond villains]], Forster rejected any grotesque appearance for the character Dominic Greene to emphasise the hidden and secret nature of the film's contemporary villains.\n\nThe film was also marked by its frequent depictions of violence, with a 2012 study by the [[University of Otago]] in New Zealand finding it to be the most violent film in the franchise.  Whereas ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]'' featured 109 \"trivial or severely violent\" acts, ''Quantum of Solace'' had a count of 250\u2014the most depictions of violence in any ''Bond'' film\u2014even more prominent since it was also the shortest film in the franchise.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.meeja.com.au/2012/sean-connery-was-the-girliest-bond/|title=Sean Connery was the girliest Bond|publisher=Meeja|date=10 December 2012|accessdate=6 September 2011|location=Australia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108212058/http://meeja.com.au/2012/sean-connery-was-the-girliest-bond/|archivedate=8 January 2013}}</ref>  ''Quantum of Solace'' premiered at the [[Odeon Leicester Square]] on 29 October 2008, garnering generally polarized reviews, which mainly praised Craig's performance, the darker, grittier and realistic tone and the film's action sequences, but felt that the film was less impressive than the predecessor ''Casino Royale''.  {{As of|2016|September}}, it is the fourth-highest-grossing ''James Bond'' film, without adjusting for inflation, earning $589&nbsp;million worldwide, and becoming the [[2008 in film#Highest-grossing films|seventh highest-grossing film of 2008]].\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please remember to keep it short and around 600 words per WikiProject Films/Style guidelines, and that a spoiler warning is unnecessary per Wikipedia:Spoiler. -->\nMoments after the end of the previous film, James Bond is driving from [[Lake Como]] to [[Siena]], Italy, with the captured [[List of James Bond villains#Casino Royale 2006|Mr. White]] in the [[Trunk (automobile)|boot]] of his [[Aston Martin DBS V12]]. After evading pursuers Bond delivers White to [[M (James Bond)|M]], who interrogates him regarding the then unknown organisation, [[SPECTRE#Rebooted continuity|Quantum]]. M's [[bodyguard]], Craig Mitchell, is a double agent and attacks M, enabling White to escape. Bond chases Mitchell and kills him. Bond and M return to London and search Mitchell's flat, discovering Mitchell had a contact in [[Haiti]], Edmund Slate. Bond learns Slate is a hitman sent to kill [[Camille Montes]] at the behest of her lover, environmentalist entrepreneur [[List of James Bond villains#Quantum of Solace|Dominic Greene]]. Observing her subsequent meeting with Greene, Bond learns Greene is helping exiled Bolivian General Medrano, who murdered Camille's family, to overthrow the government and become the new president, in exchange for a seemingly barren piece of desert.\n\nAfter rescuing Camille from Medrano, Bond follows Greene to a performance of ''[[Tosca]]'' in [[Bregenz]], Austria. Meanwhile, the head of the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]]'s South American section, Gregg Beam, strikes a noninterference deal with Greene for access to putative stocks of Bolivian oil, which the CIA believes to be the reason for Greene's interest in the land. Bond infiltrates Quantum's meeting at the opera, identifying members of Quantum's executive board, and a gunfight ensues. A [[Counter Terrorism Command|Special Branch]] bodyguard working for Quantum member Guy Haines, an advisor to the British [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], is killed by one of Greene's men after Bond throws him off a roof. M assumes Bond killed him, and she has Bond's passports and credit cards revoked. Bond heads to Italy and convinces his old ally [[List of James Bond allies#Ren\u00e9 Mathis|Ren\u00e9 Mathis]] to accompany him to [[Bolivia]]. They are greeted by Strawberry Fields, a consular employee who demands Bond return to the UK immediately. Bond seduces her, and they attend a fundraising party Greene holds that night. At the party, Bond again rescues Camille from Greene. Leaving, Bond and Camille are pulled over by Bolivian police, paid off by Greene and Medrano. They had earlier attacked Mathis and put his body in Bond's car to frame Bond. In the ensuing struggle, Mathis and the policemen are killed.\n\nThe following day, Bond and Camille survey Quantum's intended land acquisition by air; their plane is shot down by a Bolivian fighter aircraft. They skydive into a sinkhole and discover Quantum is damming Bolivia's supply of fresh water to create a [[monopoly]]. Back in La Paz, Bond meets M and learns Quantum killed Fields by drowning her in [[Petroleum|crude oil]]. Bond meets CIA Agent [[Felix Leiter]], who discloses Greene and Medrano will meet in the [[Atacama Desert]] to finalise their agreement. Warned by Leiter, he evades the CIA's [[Special Activities Division]] when they attempt to kill him.\n\nAt an [[eco hotel]] in the desert, Greene tells Medrano that he now controls the majority of Bolivia's water supply, and Medrano must accept a new contract that makes Greene Bolivia's sole provider of water at significantly higher rates; if Medrano refuses, Greene will deprive the country of water until it [[societal collapse|collapses]]. Bond infiltrates the complex, kills the chief of police for betraying Mathis, and single-handedly assaults the hotel. After killing the security detail, he confronts Greene. Meanwhile, Camille kills Medrano, avenging the murders of her family. The struggle leaves the hotel destroyed by fire. Bond captures Greene and interrogates him about Quantum. Bond leaves him stranded in the desert with only a can of engine oil. \n\nBond travels to [[Kazan]], Russia, where he finds [[Vesper Lynd]]'s former lover, Yusef Kabira, a member of Quantum who seduces women with valuable connections and is indirectly responsible for her death. Bond tells Kabira's latest target, Corrine Veneau, a [[Canadian Security Intelligence Service|Canadian Intelligence]] agent, of Kabira's true intentions, thus sparing her Vesper's fate. He allows MI6 to arrest Kabira. Outside, M tells Bond that Greene was found dead in the middle of the desert, shot twice and with engine oil in his stomach. M tells Bond she needs him back; he responds that he never left. Walking away, he drops Vesper's necklace in the snow.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Daniel Craig]] as [[James Bond filmography|James Bond]]. Craig's physical training for his reprise of the role placed extra effort into running and boxing, to spare him the injuries he sustained on his stunts in the first film.<ref>{{cite news |author=Martyn Palmer |title=The man with the golden touch |work=[[The Times]] |date=24 November 2007|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article2900516.ece?token=null&offset=0 |accessdate=25 November 2007 | location=London}}</ref> Craig felt he was fitter, being less bulky than in the first film.<ref name=criminal/> He also practised speedboating and stunt driving. Craig felt ''Casino Royale'' was [physically] \"a walk in the park\" compared to ''Quantum of Solace'',<ref>{{cite web | title = Newswrap | publisher = Official site | format= Flash video | url = http://www.007.com/ | accessdate=1 March 2008}}</ref> which required a different performance from him because ''Quantum of Solace'' is a revenge film, not a love story like ''Casino Royale''.<ref name=criminal/> While filming in Pinewood, he suffered a gash when kicked in his face,<ref name=ew>{{cite news|author=Benjamin Svetkey|title=Bond is back!|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20237005,00.html|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> which required eight stitches, and a fingertip was sliced off. He laughed these off, noting they did not delay filming, and joked his finger wound would enable him to have a criminal career (though it had grown back when he made this comment).<ref name=criminal>{{cite news|author=John Naughton|title=Spy Harder|work=[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]|date=November 2008|pages=278\u2013335}}</ref> He also had minor plastic surgery on his face.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bond actor admits plastic surgery|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=9 October 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7660808.stm|accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref> The actor advised Paul Haggis on the script and helped choose [[Marc Forster]] as the director.<ref>{{cite news |author=Jennifer Vineyard |title=Daniel Craig Says He's Feeling The 'Pressure' Of James Bond Follow-Up |publisher=MTV |date=6 December 2007 |url=http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1575858/20071205/story.jhtml |accessdate=7 December 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Olga Kurylenko]] as [[Camille Montes]], a Bolivian agent with her own vendetta regarding Greene and Medrano. Forster chose her because out of the 400 women who auditioned, she seemed the least nervous.<ref name=premiereset>{{cite news|author=Matt Mueller|title=On the Set of 'Quantum Of Solace': Olga Kurylenko: The Bond Girl|work=[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]|url=http://www.premiere.com/Feature/On-the-Set-of-Quantum-Of-Solace/On-the-Set-of-Quantum-Of-Solace2|accessdate=14 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113010442/http://www.premiere.com/Feature/On-the-Set-of-Quantum-Of-Solace/On-the-Set-of-Quantum-Of-Solace2|archivedate=13 January 2010}}</ref> When she read the script, she was glad she had no love scene with Craig; she felt it would have distracted viewers from her performance.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tim Masters|title=Talking Shop: Olga Kurylenko|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=31 October 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7695332.stm|accessdate=31 October 2008}}</ref> Kurylenko spent three weeks training to fight with weapons, and she learnt a form of indoor skydiving known as body flying.<ref name=guardian/> Kurylenko said she had to do \"training non-stop from the morning to the evening\" for the action scenes, overcoming her fears with the help of Craig and the stunt team.<ref name=chilesoundbite>{{cite web|title = Chile Soundbites videos|publisher = Sony [[Electronic Press Kit]]|url = http://sony.epk.tv/campaign/quantum-of-solace|accessdate=11 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=ignqa/> She was given a DVD box set of Bond films, since the franchise was not easily available to watch in her native Ukraine.<ref name=guardian/> Kurylenko found [[Michelle Yeoh]] in ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'' inspiring \"because she did the fight scenes by herself.\"<ref name=premiereset/> The producers had intended to cast a South American actress in the role<ref name=diary22/>, thus, Kurylenko trained with a [[dialect coach]] to perform with a Spanish accent.<ref name=ignqa>{{cite web|author = Chris Tilly|title = Olga Kurylenko Q&A|website = [[IGN]]|date = 31 January 2008|url = http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/848/848813p1.html|accessdate = 31 January 2008|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080204085248/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/848/848813p1.html|archivedate = 4 February 2008|df = dmy-all}}</ref> She said that the accent was easy for her because she has \"a lot of Hispanic friends, from Latin America and Spain, and it's an accent I've always heard\".<ref>{{cite news|author = Rob Scheer|title = INTERVIEW: Olga Kurylenko on \"Quantum of Solace\"|publisher = [[UGO]]|date = 14 November 2008|url = http://www.cinecon.com/news/1825/interview-olga-kurylenko-quantum-of-solace/|accessdate=6 September 2011}}</ref> When reflecting on her experience as a [[Bond girl]], she stated she was proudest of overcoming her fears in performing stunts.<ref name=glasgowherald>{{cite news|author=David Giammarco|title=From Ukraine, with love|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|url=http://www.theherald.co.uk/features/features/display.var.2446992.0.From_Ukraine_with_love.php|accessdate=18 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903045044/http://www.theherald.co.uk/features/features/display.var.2446992.0.From_Ukraine_with_love.php|archivedate=3 September 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Mathieu Amalric]] as [[List of James Bond villains#Quantum of Solace|Dominic Greene]], the main villain. He is a leading member of Quantum posing as a businessman working in [[reforestation]] and charity funding for environmental science. In the 2015 Bond film ''[[Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre]]'', he is revealed to have been a member of the [[SPECTRE|titular crime syndicate]], of which Quantum is a subsidiary. Amalric acknowledged taking the role was an easy decision because, \"It's impossible to say to your kids that 'I could have been in a Bond film but I refused.'\"<ref name=guardian/> Amalric wanted to wear make-up for the role, but Forster explained that he wanted Greene not to look grotesque, but to symbolise the hidden evils in society.<ref name=ew/> Amalric modelled his performance on \"the smile of [[Tony Blair]] [and] the craziness of [[Nicolas Sarkozy|Sarkozy]],\" the latter of whom he called \"the worst villain we [the French] have ever had \u2026 he walks around thinking he's in a Bond film.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Bond villain spills the beans | work = [[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] | date = 24 January 2008 | url = http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/85747-bond-villain-spills-the-beans | accessdate=31 January 2008}}</ref> He later claimed this was not criticism of either politician, but rather an example of how a politician relies on performance instead of a genuine policy to win power. \"Sarkozy, is just a better actor than [his presidential opponent] [[S\u00e9gol\u00e8ne Royal]]\u2014that's all,\" he explained.<ref name=environment/> Amalric and Forster reconceived the character, who was supposed to have a \"special skill\" in the script, to someone who uses pure animal instinct when fighting Bond in the climax.<ref name=pity>{{cite news|title=Quantum of Solace: Mathieu Amalric on playing James Bond's nemesis|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2 October 2008|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2008/10/23/sm_mathieuamalric.xml|accessdate=23 October 2008|location=London|first=Murphy|last=Williams}}</ref> [[Bruno Ganz]] was also considered for the part,<ref name=diary22>{{cite news |title=Bond 22 Pre-Production Diary (22)|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=30 December 2007 |url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_preprod_diary22.php3?t=&s=articles |accessdate=31 December 2007}}</ref> but Forster decided Amalric gave the character a \"pitiful\" quality.<ref name=pity/>\n* [[Judi Dench]] as [[M (James Bond)|M]]. Forster felt Dench was underused in the previous films and wanted to make her part bigger, having her interact with Bond more because she is \"the only woman Bond doesn't see in a sexual context,\" which Forster finds interesting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fostering change|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=11 October 2008|url=http://www.star-ecentral.com/news/story.asp?file=/2008/10/11/movies/2202154&sec=movies|accessdate=13 October 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Gemma Arterton]] as MI6 agent Strawberry Fields, who works at the British consulate in Bolivia. Fields, who is merely an office worker as described by M, takes herself seriously and tries to overpower Bond when the pair meet. She is later seduced by Bond, infiltrates Greene's fund raiser party with him and ends up paying the ultimate price. Forster found Arterton a witty actress and selected her from a reported 1,500 candidates. One of the casting directors asked her to audition for the role, having seen her portray Rosaline in ''[[Love's Labour's Lost]]'' at the [[Globe Theatre]].<ref name=dianarigg>{{cite web | author = Chris Tilly | title = Gemma Arteron Q&A | website = [[IGN]] | date = 30 January 2008 | url = http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/848/848237p1.html | accessdate = 30 January 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080201171744/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/848/848237p1.html | archivedate = 1 February 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Arterton said Fields was \"not so frolicsome\" as other Bond girls, but is instead \"fresh and young, not \u2026 a [[femme fatale]].\"<ref name=bbctitle/> Arterton described Fields as a homage to the 1960s Bond girls, comparing her red wig to that of [[Diana Rigg]], who played [[Tracy Bond]] in ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (film)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]''. Rigg, alongside [[Honor Blackman]], is one of her favourite Bond girls.<ref name=dianarigg/> Arterton had to film her character's death scene first day on the set, where she was completely covered head to toe in non-toxic black paint. Although she found the experience unpleasant, she believed the scene would be an iconic part of the film.<ref name=Agent>{{cite news |title=SPOILER ALERT - Oilfinger: Exclusive picture shows Gemma Arterton coming to a sticky end in new Bond film|author=Harper, Tom|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=6 October 2008 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1068483/SPOILER-ALERT.html|accessdate=2 May 2009}}</ref> The character's full name, which is a reference to [[the Beatles]] song \"[[Strawberry Fields Forever]]\", is never actually uttered on screen; when Bond asks her for her name, she replies, \"Just Fields.\" Robert A. Caplen suggests that this is a conscious effort to portray a woman \"whose character attributes are neither undermined nor compromised\" by her name, even though her name may have sexual overtones reminiscent of earlier [[Bond girls]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Caplen|first=Robert A.|title=Shaken & Stirred: The Feminism of James Bond|year=2010|page=346|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8p-qpJjPU4C&pg=PA346|isbn=978-1-4535-1282-1}}</ref> In August 2018, Arterton wrote a short story titled ''Woke Bond Woman'', based on the character.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/international-news/article/gemma-arterton-pens-a-short-story-about-her-bond-character/268793|title=Gemma Arterton pens a short story about her Bond character|work=Times Now News|date=13 August 2018|accessdate=10 November 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Giancarlo Giannini]] as [[Ren\u00e9 Mathis]], Bond's ally who was mistakenly believed to be a traitor in ''Casino Royale''. Having been acquitted, he chooses to aid Bond again in his quest to find out who betrayed him.\n* [[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]] as [[Felix Leiter]], Bond's ally at the CIA. Early script drafts gave Leiter a larger role, but his screentime was restricted by on-set rewrites.<ref name=secret>{{cite web|title=The Secrets of Quantum of Solace |website=[[IGN]] |date=5 April 2008 |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/864/864542p1.html |accessdate=5 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410000608/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/864/864542p1.html |archivedate=10 April 2008  }}</ref>\n* [[Anatole Taubman]] as Elvis, Greene's second-in-command. Taubman wanted to make Elvis \"as colourful, as edgy and as interesting as possible\", with one of his suggestions being the [[bowl cut]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Anatole Taubman On Elvis|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=7 November 2008|url=http://mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_qos_capsule_elvis.php3?t=qos&s=qos&id=02075|accessdate=9 November 2008}}</ref> Amalric and Taubman improvised a backstory for Elvis: he is Dominic's cousin and once lived on the streets before being inducted into Quantum. He called Elvis \"a bit of a goofball. He thinks he's all that but he's not really.&nbsp;\u2026 He's not a comic guy. He definitely takes himself very serious, but maybe by his taking himself too serious he may become friendly.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = Elvis Rocks Bond's World | website = [[IGN]] | date = 16 May 2008 | url = http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/874/874700p1.html | accessdate = 16 May 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080521154755/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/874/874700p1.html | archivedate = 21 May 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[David Harbour]] as Gregg Beam, the CIA section chief for South America and a contact of Felix Leiter.\n* [[Joaqu\u00edn Cos\u00edo]] as General Medrano, the exiled general whom Greene is helping to get back into power, in return for support of his organisation. He murdered Camille's entire family when she was a young girl.\n* [[Fernando Guill\u00e9n Cuervo]] as Carlos, the Colonel of Bolivian Police, the chief of all police forces, and the contact of Ren\u00e9 Mathis in Bolivia.\n* [[Jesper Christensen]] as [[Mr. White (James Bond)|Mr. White]], whom Bond captured after he stole the money won at ''Casino Royale'' in Montenegro.\n* [[Rory Kinnear]] as [[Bill Tanner]], M's aide.\n* [[Paul Ritter (actor)|Paul Ritter]] as Guy Haines\n* [[Tim Pigott-Smith]] as the British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]].\n* [[Neil Jackson]] as Edmund Slate, a henchman who fights Bond in Haiti.\n* [[Simon Kassianides]] as Yusef, a member of Quantum who seduces female agents and manipulates them into giving away classified information. He is indirectly responsible for [[Vesper Lynd]]'s death.\n* [[Stana Katic]] as Corrine Veneau, a Canadian agent and Yusef's latest target.\n* Glenn Foster as Craig Mitchell, M's bodyguard and a double agent.\n* [[Oona Chaplin]] as Perla de las Dunas' receptionist, a woman saved by Camille Montes in one of the last sequences.\n* [[Lucrezia Lante della Rovere]] as Gemma, Mathis' girlfriend.\n* [[Elizabeth Arciniega]] as Mr. White's girlfriend.\n\nMarc Forster asked his friends and fellow directors [[Guillermo del Toro]] and [[Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n]] to appear in cameos. Cuar\u00f3n appears as a Bolivian helicopter pilot, while del Toro provides several other voices.<ref>{{cite news|title=Del Toro, Cuaron do voices in new Bond film|agency=Associated Press|date=23 October 2008|url=http://www.hitfix.com/articles/del-toro-cuaron-do-voices-in-new-bond-film|accessdate=23 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n{{quote|If you remember in ''[[Chinatown (1974 film)|Chinatown]]'', if you control the water you control the whole development of the country. I think it's true. Right now it appears to be oil, but there's a lot of other resources that we don't think about too much but are all essential, and they're very limited and every country needs it. Because every country knows that raising the standard of living (and populations are getting bigger) is the way we're all going.|Michael G. Wilson on the plot.<ref name=secret/>}}\n\nIn July 2006, as ''Casino Royale'' entered post-production, Eon Productions announced that the next film would be based on an original idea by producer [[Michael G. Wilson]].<ref>{{cite news |author= Tatiana Siegel and Borys Kit |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002840141 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011120117/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002840141 |archivedate=11 October 2007|title= Roger Michell in Talks for Bond 22 |work= [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date= 17 July 2006 |accessdate=17 July 2006}}</ref> It was decided beforehand the film would be a direct sequel, to exploit Bond's emotions following Vesper's death in the previous film.<ref>{{cite news | author = Liane Bonin | title = 10 Questions With: Daniel Craig | publisher = [[Moviefone]] | url = http://www.moviefone.com/insidemovies/2008/04/14/daniel-craig-interview-for-quantum-of-solace/ | accessdate = 11 April 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080613092700/http://www.moviefone.com/insidemovies/2008/04/14/daniel-craig-interview-for-quantum-of-solace/ | archivedate = 13 June 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Just as ''Casino Royale''{{'s}} theme was terrorism, the sequel focuses on environmentalism.<ref name=environment/> The film was confirmed for a 2 May 2008 release date, with Craig reprising the lead role.<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Columbia Pictures]] |title=22nd James Bond Coming May&nbsp;2,&nbsp;2008! |publisher=[[Superhero Hype!]] |date=20 July 2006 |url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/jamesbondnews.php?id=4521 |accessdate=6 August 2007}}</ref> [[Roger Michell]], who directed Craig in ''[[Enduring Love (film)|Enduring Love]]'' and ''[[The Mother (film)|The Mother]]'', was in negotiations to direct, but opted out because there was no script.<ref>{{cite news |title=They call him Director No|work=[[The Times]]|date=4 July 2007|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/theatre/article1877785.ece|accessdate=27 January 2008 | location=London |first=Greg |last=Hurst}}</ref> Sony Entertainment vice-chairman Jeff Blake admitted a production schedule of 18 months was a very short window, and the release date was pushed back to late 2008.<ref name=superherohype>{{cite news |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=16308 |title=Bond 22 Targeting November&nbsp;7,&nbsp;2008 |publisher= [[Superhero Hype!]] |date=1 September 2006|accessdate=1 September 2006}}</ref> [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]] completed their draft of the script by April 2007,<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Fleming|title='Barbarella' back in action|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=11 April 2007|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117962920.html |accessdate=6 August 2007}}</ref> and [[Paul Haggis]], who polished the ''Casino Royale'' script, began his rewrite the next month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Paul Haggis on board to work on Bond 22 script, but turns down directing role |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=23 May 2007|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=5040&catid=106 |accessdate=23 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, [[Marc Forster]] was confirmed as director.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003600629 |title=Forster back in action with 'Bond 22' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=20 June 2007 |accessdate=19 June 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930183557/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003600629 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref> He was surprised that he was approached for the job, stating he was not a big Bond film fan through the years, and that he would not have accepted the project had he not seen ''Casino Royale'' prior to making his decision: he felt Bond had been humanised in that film, arguing since travelling the world had become less exotic since the series' advent, it made sense to focus more on Bond as a character. Born in Germany and raised in Switzerland, Forster was the first Bond director not to come from the [[British Commonwealth of Nations]], although he noted Bond's mother is Swiss, making him somewhat appropriate to handle the British icon.<ref name=swiss>{{cite news |author=Terrence Rafferty |title=A License to Pursue the Inner Bond |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 December 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/09/movies/09raff.html |accessdate=9 December 2007}}</ref> The director collaborated strongly with [[Barbara Broccoli]] and Michael G. Wilson, noting they only blocked two very expensive ideas he had.<ref name=diary22/> The director found ''Casino Royale''{{'}}s 144-minute running time too long, and wanted his follow-up to be \"tight and fast \u2026 like a bullet.\"<ref name=bullet>{{cite news|author=Alistair Harkness|title=A Quantum leap|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/A-Quantum-leap.4643021.jp|accessdate=30 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Because Bond plays it real, I thought the political circumstances should be real too, even though Bond shouldn't be a political film. I thought the more political I make it, the more real it feels, not just with Bolivia and what's happening in Haiti, but with all these corporations like Shell and Chevron saying they're green because it's so fashionable to be green. During the Cold War, everything was very clear, the good guys and the bad guys. Today there's much overlapping of good and bad. It isn't as morally distinct, because we all have both elements in us.|Marc Forster on the political landscape of the film.<ref name=pain/>}}\n\nHaggis, Forster and Wilson rewrote the story from scratch.<ref name=zetumer/> Haggis said he completed his script two hours before the [[2007\u20132008 Writers Guild of America strike]] officially began.<ref name=swiss/> Forster noted a running theme in his films were emotionally repressed protagonists, and the theme of the picture would be Bond learning to trust after feeling betrayed by Vesper.<ref name=mi6forster/> Forster said he created the Camille character as a strong female counterpart to Bond rather than a casual love interest: she openly shows emotions similar to those which Bond experiences but is unable to express.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/911/911930p1.html|author=Jim Vejvoda|title=007 Responds to IGN Readers|website=[[IGN]]|date=22 September 2008|accessdate=22 September 2008}}</ref> Haggis located his draft's climax in the [[Swiss Alps]],<ref name=empire>{{cite news|author=Ian Nathan|title=Quantum's Leap|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|date=October 2008|pages=82\u201390}}</ref> but Forster wanted the action sequences to be based around the four [[classical element]]s of earth, water, air and fire.<ref name=variety>{{cite news|author=Anne Thompson|title='Solace' offers thinking person's 007|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=23 October 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117994573.html |accessdate=1 November 2008|authorlink=Anne Thompson (film critic)}}</ref> The decision to homage [[Oddjob]]'s murder of Jill Masterson ([[Shirley Eaton]]) in ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'' in Fields's death came about as Forster wanted to show oil had replaced gold as the most precious material.<ref name=pain>{{cite news|first=Ciaran |last=Carty|title='I felt there was pain in Bond'|work=[[Sunday Tribune]]|date=2 November 2008|url=http://tribune.maithu.com/article/2008/nov/02/i-felt-there-was-pain-in-bond/|accessdate=2 November 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206061930/http://www.tribune.ie/arts/films/article/2008/nov/02/i-felt-there-was-pain-in-bond/|archivedate=6 December 2008 }}</ref> The producers rejected Haggis's idea that Vesper Lynd had a child, because \"Bond was an orphan \u2026 Once he finds the kid, Bond can't just leave the kid.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Logan Hill|title=How James Bond Nearly Became a Father|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=3 November 2008|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2008/11/how_james_bond_nearly_became_a.html|accessdate=3 November 2008}}</ref> The [[Water supply and sanitation in Bolivia|water supply issue]] in Bolivia was the main theme of the film, with a story based on the [[Cochabamba]] [[2000 Cochabamba protests|Water Revolt]].<ref>[http://www.filmquarterly.org/2009/06/cinema-for-a-grand-new-game/ Cinema for a Grand New Game], ''[[Film Quarterly]]''</ref>\n\nMichael G. Wilson decided on the film's title ''Quantum of Solace'' only \"a few days\" before its announcement on 24 January 2008.<ref name=bbctitle>{{cite news |title=New Bond film title is confirmed |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=24 January 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7206997.stm |accessdate=24 January 2008}}</ref> It was the name of a short story in [[Ian Fleming]]'s anthology ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]'' (1960).<ref name=confuse/> The film is related to the title in one of its thematic elements: \"when the 'Quantum of Solace' drops to zero, humanity and consideration of one human for another is gone.\" Daniel Craig admitted, \"I was unsure at first. Bond is looking for his quantum of solace and that's what he wants, he wants his closure. Ian Fleming says that if you don't have a quantum of solace in your relationship then the relationship is over. It's that spark of niceness in a relationship that if you don't have you might as well give up.\"<ref name=guardian/> He said that \"Bond doesn't have that because his girlfriend [Vesper Lynd] has been killed,\"<ref name=confuse>{{cite news |title=Daniel: the title is meant to confuse |work=[[Press and Journal (Scotland)|Press and Journal]] |date=24 January 2008}}</ref> and therefore, \"[Bond is] looking for revenge \u2026 to make himself happy with the world again.\"<ref name=bbctitle/> Afterwards, Quantum was made the name of the organisation introduced in ''Casino Royale''.<ref name=quantum/> Craig noted the letter Q itself looks rather odd.<ref name=criminal/> Near the end of the film, the Camille Montes character and Bond have a discussion about their individual quests to avenge the deaths of their loved ones. Montes asks Bond to \"let me know what it feels like\" when he succeeds, the implication of the title being that it will be a small amount of solace compared to his despair. Bond's lack of emotion when he does exact revenge shows this to be the case.\n\nAccording to a December 2011 interview with Craig, \"We had the bare bones of a script and then there was a writers' strike and there was nothing we could do. We couldn't employ a writer to finish it. I say to myself, 'Never again', but who knows? There was me trying to rewrite scenes\u2014and a writer I am not.\"<ref name=Goldberg>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|title=Daniel Craig Talks about the Script Problems on QUANTUM OF SOLACE; Says Why He's Encouraged for SKYFALL|url=http://collider.com/daniel-craig-quantum-of-solace-script-problems/130951/|website=Collider|accessdate=29 August 2012|date=7 December 2011}}</ref> He said that he and Forster \"were the ones allowed to do it. The rules were that you couldn't employ anyone as a writer, but the actor and director could work on scenes together. We were stuffed. We got away with it, but only just. It was never meant to be as much of a sequel as it was, but it ended up being a sequel, starting where the last one finished.\"<ref name=Goldberg/>\n\nDuring filming, after the strike ended, Forster read a [[spec script]] by Joshua Zetumer, which he liked, and hired him to reshape scenes for the later parts of the shoot, which the director was still unsatisfied with.<ref name=zetumer>{{cite web|title=A James Bond Set Visit and Seven Exclusive Quantum of Solace Images! |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=4 April 2008 |url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1719930/a_james_bond_set_visit_and_seven_exclusive_quantum_of_solace_images |accessdate=5 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005195337/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1719930/a_james_bond_set_visit_and_seven_exclusive_quantum_of_solace_images |archivedate= 5 October 2008 }}</ref> Forster had the actors rehearse their scenes, as he liked to film scenes continually.<ref name=environment>{{cite news | author = Karl Rozemeyer | title = Mathieu Amalric on Being the 'Bond 22' Villain | work = [[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]] | date = 18 March 2008 | url = http://www.premiere.com/features/4455/mathieu-amalric-on-being-the-bond-22-villain.html | accessdate=19 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321210654/http://www.premiere.com/features/4455/mathieu-amalric-on-being-the-bond-22-villain.html|archivedate=21 March 2008}}</ref> Zetumer rewrote dialogue depending on the actors' ideas each day.<ref name=environment/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Ingresso della Forra a Tremosine.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''Strada delle Forre'' in [[Tremosine]] ([[Italy]]) where the movie begins.]]\n''Quantum of Solace'' was shot in six countries.<ref name=artfilm>{{cite news|author=Randee Dawn|title='Quantum' is Marc Forster's 007 art film|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=11 November 2008|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ie9098baec9eb95cd02a01aebbd96a968|accessdate=13 November 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113031127/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ie9098baec9eb95cd02a01aebbd96a968|archivedate=13 November 2008}}</ref> [[Second unit]] filming began in Italy at the [[Palio di Siena]] horse race on 16 August 2007,<ref name=paliodisiena>{{cite news|author=Richard Owen|title=Bond has activists on his tail over new film's 'brutal' horse race finale|work=[[The Times]]|date=13 August 2007|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article2246486.ece|accessdate=13 August 2007 | location=London}}</ref> although at that point Forster was unsure how it would fit into the film.<ref name=variety/> Some scenes were filmed also in [[Maratea]] and [[Craco]], two small distinctive towns in [[Basilicata]] in southern Italy.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=imdb.com|title=Filming locations for Quantum of Solace|date=11 November 2008|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0830515/locations|accessdate=2 June 2009}}</ref> Other places used for location shooting were [[Madrid]] in August 2007;<ref>{{cite news |title=Bond 22 filming takes place in Madrid, Spain during last week of August|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=31 August 2007|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=5327 |accessdate=25 March 2008}}</ref> [[Baja California]], Mexico in early 2008, for shots of the aerial battle;<ref name=dogfight>{{cite news|title=Newswrap No. 2 video |publisher=[[ReelzChannel]] |date=20 March 2008 |url=http://www.reelzchannel.com/movie/233698/quantum-of-solace?clipid=32934 |accessdate=20 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080322172830/http://www.reelzchannel.com/movie/233698/quantum-of-solace?clipid=32934 |archivedate=22 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=David Allen|title=A bond with Chino|publisher=[[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]]|date=28 February 2008|url=http://www.dailybulletin.com/ci_8399719|accessdate=2 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603232620/http://www.dailybulletin.com/ci_8399719|archivedate=3 June 2008 }}</ref> [[Malcesine]], [[Limone sul Garda]] and [[Tremosine]] in Italy during March,<ref name=siena>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (16) | publisher= [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 17 March 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary16.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=20 March 2008}}</ref> and at [[Talamone]] during the end of April.<ref name=fountain>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (19) | publisher= [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 27 March 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary19.php3?t=&s= | accessdate=28 March 2008}}</ref> The main unit began on 3 January 2008<ref name=diary22/> at [[Pinewood Studios]]. The [[007 Stage]] was used for the fight in the art gallery,<ref name=guardian>{{cite news |author=Mark Brown|title=Everything changes but Bond |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=24 January 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/jan/24/features|accessdate=24 January 2008 | location=London}}</ref> and an MI6 safehouse hidden within the city's [[cistern]]s,<ref name=bbcbts>{{cite news |author=Tim Marsters |title=Behind the scenes on the Bond set |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=25 January 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7208410.stm |accessdate=25 January 2008}}</ref> while other stages housed Bond's Bolivian hotel suite,<ref name=modernism/> and the MI6 headquarters.<ref name=bbcbts/> Interior and exterior airport scenes were filmed at [[Farnborough Airfield]] and the snowy closing scenes were filmed at the Bruneval Barracks in [[Aldershot]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/2038353_barracks_and_airport_provide_location_for_bond_film|title = Barracks and airport provide location for Bond film|accessdate=18 November 2008|author=Rebecca Connop Price|date=30 October 2008|publisher=Get Hampshire|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110913050519/http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/2038353_barracks_and_airport_provide_location_for_bond_film|archivedate=13 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nShooting in [[Panama City]] began on 7 February 2008 at [[Howard Air Force Base]]. The country doubled for Haiti and Bolivia, with the National Institute of Culture of Panama standing in for a hotel in the latter country. A sequence requiring several hundred [[extra (actor)|extras]] was also shot at nearby [[Col\u00f3n, Panama|Col\u00f3n]].<ref name=andeanhotel>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (11) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 9 February 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary11.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=9 February 2008}}</ref> Shooting in Panama was also carried out at [[Fort Sherman]], a former US military base on the Col\u00f3n coast. Forster was disappointed he could only shoot the boat chase in that harbour, as he had a more spectacular vision for the scene.<ref name=comingsoon>{{cite news|author=Edward Douglas|title=Marc Forster Finds His Quantum of Solace|publisher=ComingSoon.net|date=10 November 2008|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=50314|accessdate=10 November 2008}}</ref> Officials in the country worked with the locals to \"minimise inconvenience\" for the cast and crew, and in return hoped the city's exposure in the film would increase tourism.<ref name=proddiarynine>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (9) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 2 February 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary09.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=8 February 2008}}</ref> The crew was going to move to [[Cusco]], Peru for ten days of filming on 2 March,<ref name=andeanhotel/> but the location was cancelled for budget reasons.<ref name=artfilm/> Twelve days of filming in Chile began on 24 March at [[Antofagasta]]. There was shooting in [[Cobija, Chile|Cobija]], the [[Paranal Observatory]], and other locations in the [[Atacama Desert]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (17) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 19 March 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary17.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=20 March 2008}}</ref> Forster chose the desert and the observatory's [[ESO Hotel]] to represent Bond's rigid emotions, and being on the verge of committing a vengeful act as he confronts Greene in the film's climax.<ref name=quantum>{{cite news | title = Seeking Solace on the Bond set |work=[[USA Today]] | date = 3 April 2008 | url = https://www.usatoday.com/life/flash.htm?gid=459 | accessdate=4 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=water/>\n[[File:Paranal camp.jpg|thumb|left|Marc Forster chose the [[Atacama Desert]] to represent Bond's vengefulness in the climax.|alt=A scientific facility in a desert]]\nDuring filming in [[Sierra Gorda, Chile]], the local mayor, Carlos Lopez, staged a protest because he was angry at the filmmakers' portrayal of the [[Antofagasta Region]] as part of Bolivia. He was arrested, detained briefly, and put on trial two days later. Eon dismissed his claim that they needed his permission to film in the area.<ref>{{cite news | author = Simon Gardner | title = James Bond has new nemesis: irate Chilean mayor | agency=Reuters | date = 2 April 2008 | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUKN0237294620080402 | accessdate=13 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = 'Mayor' protests on Chile 007 set |work=[[BBC News Online]] | date = 2 April 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7326582.stm | accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref> Michael G. Wilson explained that Bolivia was appropriate to the plot, because of the country's history of water problems,<ref name=water>{{cite news |author=Anthony Breznican |title=James Bond series takes a 'Quantum' leap |work=USA Today |date=4 April 2008|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2008-04-03-bond-quantum_N.htm |accessdate=4 April 2008}}</ref> and was surprised the two countries disliked each other a century after the [[War of the Pacific]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (22) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 7 April 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary22.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=10 April 2008}}</ref> In a poll by Chilean daily newspaper ''[[La Segunda]]'', 75% of its readers disagreed with Lopez's actions, due to the negative image of Chile they felt it presented, and the controversy's potential to put off productions looking to film in the country in the future.<ref>{{cite news | title = \u00bfApoya Ud. las protestas del alcalde de Sierra Gorda por la filmaci\u00f3n de James Bond en su comuna? | work = [[La Segunda]] | date = 2 March 2008 | url = http://www.lasegunda.com/edicionOnline/interaccion/encuestas/resultado.asp?idencuesta=2512&idclasificacion=3&fg= | archive-url = https://archive.today/20080405174454/http://www.lasegunda.com/edicionOnline/interaccion/encuestas/resultado.asp?idencuesta=2512&idclasificacion=3&fg= | url-status = dead | archive-date = 5 April 2008 | language=Spanish | accessdate=2 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nFrom 4\u201312 April the main unit shot on Sienese rooftops.<ref name=fountain/> Shooting on the real rooftops turned out to be less expensive than building them at Pinewood.<ref name=artfilm/> The next four weeks were scheduled for filming the car chase at [[Lake Garda]] and [[Carrara]].<ref name=fountain/> On 19 April, an [[Aston Martin]] employee driving a [[Aston Martin DBS V12|DBS]] to the set crashed into the lake. He survived, and was fined \u00a3400 for reckless driving.<ref>{{cite news | author = Nick Pisa | title = Driver of James Bond's Aston Martin cheated death in dramatic crash |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date = 22 April 2008}}</ref> Another accident occurred on 21 April, and two days later, two stuntmen were seriously injured, with one, Greek stuntman Aris Comninos, having to be put in intensive care. Filming of the scenes was temporarily halted so that Italian police could investigate the causes of the accidents.<ref>{{cite news | author = Paul Bompard | title = James Bond production halted amid fears of a curse |work=[[The Times]] | date = 24 April 2008 | url =http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article3810782.ece | accessdate=24 April 2008 | location=London}}</ref> Stunt co-ordinator Gary Powell said the accidents were a testament to the realism of the action.<ref name=empire/> Rumours of a \"curse\" spread among tabloid media, something which deeply offended Craig, who disliked that they compared Comninos' accident to something like his minor finger injury later on the shoot (also part of the \"curse\"). Comninos recovered safely from his injury.<ref name=criminal/>\n\nFor the role Craig trained to be less bulky than in ''Casino Royale'' and told ''[[Men's Fitness]]'' magazine \"In fact, I was much fitter for this film compared to ''Casino Royale''\u2014I really had to be\u2014and I was running a hell of a lot more in training, just so I could do these scenes, whereas last time I spent far more time pumping heavy weights to bulk up so I could look big.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mattpomroy.com/2008/12/01/quantum-physique/|title=Quantum Physique|date=1 December 2008|website=Matt Pomroy|access-date=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nFilming took place at the [[Bregenzer Festspiele|floating opera stage]] at [[Bregenz]], Austria, from 28 April \u2013 9 May 2008. The sequence in which Bond stalks the villains during a performance of ''[[Tosca]]'' required 1,500 extras.<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (10) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 8 February 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary10.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=9 February 2008}}</ref> The production used a large model of an eye, which Forster felt fitted in the Bond style, and the opera itself has parallels to the film.<ref name=lake>{{cite news|title='Quantum of Solace' set visit: filming in Austria; Craig's next Bond moves; 007's new foes; rumors laid to rest|publisher=[[MSN]]|date=8 May 2008|url=http://movies.msn.com/movies/hitlist/05-13-08|accessdate=16 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010045516/http://movies.msn.com/movies/hitlist/05-13-08/|archivedate=10 October 2009}}</ref> A short driving sequence was filmed at the nearby [[Feldkirch, Vorarlberg]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Production Diary (1) |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=3 January 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary01.php3?t=&s=articles |accessdate=8 January 2008}}</ref> The crew returned to Italy from 13\u201317 May to shoot a (planned) car crash at the marble quarry in Carrara,<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (32) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 16 May 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary32.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=16 May 2008}}</ref> and a recreation of the Palio di Siena at the [[Piazza del Campo]] in Siena. 1,000 extras were hired for a scene where Bond emerges from the ''Fonte Gaia''. Originally, he would have emerged from the city's cisterns at [[Siena Cathedral]], but this was thought disrespectful.<ref name=fountain/> By June the crew returned to Pinewood for four weeks,<ref name=lake/> where new sets (including the interior of the hotel in the climax) were built.<ref name=zetumer/><ref name=modernism/> The [[wrap (filmmaking)|wrap]] party was held on 21 June.<ref>{{cite news | title = 'Quantum of Solace' wrap party held on Saturday night, David Arnold confirms | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 22 June 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=6394 | accessdate=22 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Design===\nProduction designer [[Peter Lamont]], a crew member on 18 previous Bond films, retired after ''Casino Royale''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Peter Lamont bows out from Bond 22, Dennis Gassner to be Production Designer |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=23 July 2007|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=5206 |accessdate=23 July 2007}}</ref> Forster hired [[Dennis Gassner]] in his stead, having admired his work on ''[[The Truman Show]]'' and the films of the [[Coen brothers]].<ref name=mi6forster>{{cite web|url=http://mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_qos_capsule_forster.php3?t=qos&s=qos&id=02080|title=Marc Forster on directing 007|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=11 November 2008|accessdate=13 November 2008}}</ref> Craig said the film would have \"a touch of [[Ken Adam]],\"<ref name=kenadam>{{cite news |author=Olly Richards |title=Daniel Craig Talks Quantum of Solace |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=24 January 2008 |url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=21855 |accessdate=24 January 2008}}</ref> while Michael G. Wilson also called Gassner's designs \"a [[postmodern]] look at [[modernism]].\"<ref name=modernism>{{cite news|title=Quantum of Solace \u2013 Production Diary (7)|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=26 January 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary07.php3?t=&s=|accessdate=26 January 2008}}</ref> Forster said he felt the early Bond films' design \"were ahead of their time,\"<ref name=mi6forster/> and enjoyed the clashing of an older style with his own because it created a unique look unto itself.<ref name=aicnqa/> Gassner wanted his sets to emphasize Craig's \"great angular, textured face and wonderful blue eyes,\" and totally redesigned the MI6 headquarters because he felt Judi Dench \"was a bit tired in the last film, so I thought, let's bring her into a new world.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=James Bond: licence to redesign|work=[[Maclean's]]|date=17 November 2008|url=http://blog.macleans.ca/2008/11/17/james-bond-licence-to-redesign/|accessdate=18 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nLouise Frogley replaced [[Lindy Hemming]] as [[costume design]]er, though Hemming remained as supervisor. Hemming hired [[Brioni (fashion)|Brioni]] for Bond's suits since her tenure on the series began with 1995's ''[[GoldenEye]]'', but Lindsay Pugh, another supervisor, explained their suits were \"too relaxed.\" [[Tom Ford]] was hired to tailor \"sharper\" suits for Craig. Pugh said the costumes aimed towards the 1960s feel, especially for Bond and Fields. [[Prada]] provided the dresses for both Bond girls. [[Jasper Conran]] designed Camille's ginger bandeau, bronze skirt and gold fish necklace,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasperconran.com/collections/womenswear/archive/james-bond,116,ART.html |title=Jasper Conran Spring Summer 2008 Collection |publisher=Jasperconran.com |accessdate=12 September 2010}}</ref> while [[Chrome Hearts]] designed gothic jewelry for Amalric's character, which the actor liked enough to keep after filming.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jessica Fellowes|title=James Bond week: 007 and his girls are back with a crisp new look|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 October 2008|url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG3365681/James-Bond-week-007-and-his-girls-are-back-with-a-crisp-new-look.html|accessdate=25 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref> Sophie Harley, who created [[Vesper Lynd]]'s earrings and Algerian loveknot necklace in ''Casino Royale'', was called upon to create another version of the necklace.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jessica Fellowes|title=Necklace with a starring role|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 October 2008|url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG3365680/Necklace-with-a-starring-role.html|accessdate=25 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe film returns to the traditional [[James Bond gun barrel sequence|gun barrel opening shot]], which was altered into part of the story for ''Casino Royale'' where it was moved to the beginning of the title sequence. In this film the gun barrel sequence was moved to the end of the movie, which Wilson explained was done for a surprise,<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Caro|title=15 James Bond facts you need to know|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=9 November 2008|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-11-09/news/0811070249_1_casino-royale-daniel-craig-olga-kurylenko|accessdate=8 November 2008}}</ref> and to signify the conclusion of the story begun in the previous film. The opening credits sequence was created by [[MK12]]. Having worked on Forster's ''[[Stranger than Fiction (2006 film)|Stranger than Fiction]]'' and ''[[The Kite Runner (film)|The Kite Runner]]'', MK12 spontaneously began developing the sequence early on in production, and had a good idea of its appearance which meant it did not have to be redone when the [[#Music|title singer]] was changed. MK12 selected various twilight colours to represent Bond's mood and focused on a dot motif based on the gunbarrel shot. MK12 also worked on scenes with [[graphical user interface]]s, including the electronic table MI6 uses,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://vfxworld.com/index.php?atype=articles&id=3881 |author=Bill Desowitz |title=MK12 Has a Blast with Quantum Main Titles |publisher=VFXWorld |date=16 January 2009 |accessdate=26 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607045355/http://vfxworld.com/index.php?atype=articles&id=3881 |archivedate= 7 June 2009 }}</ref> and the [[Port-au-Prince]], Haiti title cards.<ref>{{cite news|author=Yves Peters|title=MK12 Create Custom Type for Quantum of Solace Title Sequence|publisher=[[FontShop]]|date=19 December 2008|url=http://fontfeed.com/archives/mk12-quantum-of-solace-title-sequence/|accessdate=22 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222234148/http://fontfeed.com/archives/mk12-quantum-of-solace-title-sequence/|archivedate=22 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Effects===\n[[File:AstonMartinDBSCC08.jpg|thumb|right|[[Aston Martin DBS V12]] on display at the 2008 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]|alt=A black car in an exhibition.]]\n''Quantum of Solace'' was the last in [[Ford Motor Company|Ford Motor]]'s three-film deal that began with 2002's ''[[Die Another Day]]''. Although Ford sold over 90% of the [[Aston Martin]] company in 2007, the [[Aston Martin DBS V12]] returned for the film's car chase around Lake Garda;<ref>{{cite news |title=Aston Martin DBS to star in new James Bond film |publisher=[[Aston Martin]] |year=2007 |url=http://www.astonmartin.com/thecompany/news?a=14d34f22-1324-4ca5-acbb-764f80c7d7f2 |accessdate=11 December 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523032827/http://www.astonmartin.com/thecompany/news?a=14d34f22-1324-4ca5-acbb-764f80c7d7f2|archivedate=23 May 2009}}</ref> [[Dan Bradley]] was hired as [[second unit]] director because of his work on the second and third [[Bourne (film series)|''Bourne'' films]], so the film would continue the gritty action style begun in ''Casino Royale''.<ref>{{cite news |author=Borys Kit |title=Bradley tapped to aid Bond stunts |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=4 September 2007 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i61cdc71247ef46a7ec4bddbba9463397 |accessdate=10 January 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070913085544/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i61cdc71247ef46a7ec4bddbba9463397 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 13 September 2007}}</ref> He had intended to use [[Ford GT]]s for the opening chase,<ref>{{cite web|title=Dan Bradley interview |publisher=Bourne Stunt Simulator |url=http://www.bournestuntsimulator.com/danbradley/ |accessdate=16 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128143935/http://www.bournestuntsimulator.com/danbradley/ |archivedate=28 January 2008 }}</ref> but it was replaced by the [[Alfa Romeo 159]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1902288/James-Bond-filming-suspended-after-third-accident-leaves-stuntman-in-coma.html|title=James Bond filming suspended after third accident leaves stuntman in coma|accessdate=28 April 2008|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=28 April 2008 | location=London | first=Malcolm | last=Moore}}</ref> After location filming in Italy, further close-ups of Craig, the cars and the truck were shot at Pinewood against a blue screen.<ref name=vfxworld>{{cite news|author=Bill Desowitz|title=A Quantum of VFX for James Bond|publisher=VFX World|date=3 December 2008|url=http://vfxworld.com/?atype=articles&id=3844&page=1#|accessdate=4 December 2008}}</ref> Originally three Alfa Romeos were in the sequence: but Forster felt the scene was running too long and re-edited the scene so it only looked like two Alfas were chasing Bond.<ref name=fxguide/> Ten cars were supplied by Aston Martin. Six 'hero' cars, needed for close-ups and promotional work, all survived filming unharmed with four more cars used for special effects and stunts.<ref>https://astonmartins.com/car/dbs-v12-for-007-q/</ref>\n\nFourteen cameras were used to film the [[Palio di Siena]] footage, which was later edited into the main sequence. Aerial shots using helicopters were banned, and the crew were also forbidden from showing any violence \"involving either people or animals.\"<ref name=paliodisiena/> To shoot the foot chase in [[Siena]] in April 2008 four camera cranes were built in the town, and a [[Skycam|cable camera]] was also used.<ref name=siena/> [[Framestore]] worked on the Siena chase, duplicating the 1,000 extras during principal photography to match shots of the 40,000-strong audience at the real Palio, removing wires that held Craig and the stuntmen in the rooftop segment of the chase, and digital expansion of the floor and skylight in the art gallery Bond and Mitchell fall into.<ref name=vfxworld/> The art gallery fight was intended to be simple, but during filming Craig's stunt double accidentally fell from the construction scaffolding. Forster preferred the idea of Bond hanging from ropes reaching for his gun to kill Mitchell, rather than having both men run out of the building to continue their chase as specified in the script, and the number of effects shots increased.<ref name=vfxworld/>\n\nTo film the aerial dogfight, a \"Snakehead\" camera was built and placed on the nose and tail of a [[Piper Aerostar]] 700. [[SolidWorks]], who provided the software used to design the camera, stated \"pilots for the first time can fly as aggressively as they dare without sacrificing the drama of the shot.\" The camera could turn 360 degrees and was shaped like a [[periscope]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Chris Reidy | title = \"Snakehead\" films James Bond dogfight footage |work=[[The Boston Globe]] | date = 12 May 2008 | url = http://www.boston.com/business/ticker/2008/05/_the_concord_of.html | accessdate=12 May 2008}}</ref> The crew also mounted SpaceCams on helicopters, and placed cameras with 1600mm lenses underground, to cover the action.<ref name=dogfight/> Forster wanted to film the plane fight as a homage to [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[North by Northwest]]'', and chose planes like the [[Douglas DC-3]] to suit that.<ref name=aicnqa>{{cite news|title=Capone talks with James Bond himself, Daniel Craig, and Quantum of Solace director Marc Forster in London!!!|publisher=[[Ain't It Cool News]]|date=21 September 2008|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/38427|accessdate=22 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For Your Eyes Only: RT in Austria with James Bond |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=9 May 2008 |url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1727255/2/for_your_eyes_only_rt_in_austria_with_james_bond |accessdate=16 May 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208092012/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1727255/2/for_your_eyes_only_rt_in_austria_with_james_bond |archivedate= 8 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[free-fall]] scene involved its own set of challenges; Director Marc Forster didn't want to shoot the scene against a green screen.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.budgettravel.com/article/quantum-of-solace-we-interview-the-director-plus-a-video-clip-of-bond-in-action_10236|title=Quantum of Solace--We interview the director--Plus a\u2026|last=Travel|first=Budget|date=3 October 2012|website=Budget Travel|language=en|access-date=31 January 2019}}</ref> The scene was shot in an air tunnel at Bodyflight, which offers the same effects as skydiving.<ref name=\":0\" />  Daniel Craig and Olga Kurylenko did their own stunts for this scene.<ref name=\":0\" /> While a great solution for the actors' performances, the technique presented enormous VFX challenges: relighting shots captured in a tall white tube to match the sky over the Bolivian desert; and the impossibility of filming medium to wide shots of the actors. An array of eight [[Dalsa Origin]] cameras (supported by seven HD cameras and a 35mm hand-held camera, all running in sync) was used to create a [[virtual camera]] with which to shoot the actors floating in the simulator. [[Ged Wright]] and his team at [[Double Negative (VFX)|Double Negative]]<ref name=fxguide/> developed a method to use the data from these cameras that allowed these real performances to be placed in a synthetic environment as seen by a synthetic camera.\nDuring the shooting in the wind tunnel Craig and Kurylenko wore wind-resistant contact lenses that enabled them to open their eyes as they fell. For safety and comfort, they only shot for 30 seconds at a time.<ref name=ugoqa>{{cite news|url=http://movieblog.ugo.com/index.php/movieblog/more/your_quantum_of_solace_questions_answered/ |title=Your Quantum of Solace Questions Answered! |publisher=[[UGO Networks]] |date=21 September 2008 |accessdate=22 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924230111/http://movieblog.ugo.com/index.php/movieblog/more/your_quantum_of_solace_questions_answered/ |archivedate=24 September 2008 }}</ref> Forster wished he had had more time to work on the free-fall scene.<ref name=vfxworld/>\n\nThe [[Moving Picture Company]] created the climactic hotel sequence. The fire effects were supervised by [[Chris Corbould]], and post-production MPC had to enhance the sequence by making the smoke look closer to the actors, so it would look more dangerous.<ref name=vfxworld/> A full-scale replica of the building's exterior was used for the exploding part Bond and Camille escape from.\nThe boat chase was another scene that required very little CGI. Machine FX worked on replacing a few shots of visible stuntmen with a digital version of Craig's head,<ref name=fxguide/> and recreated the boats Bond jumps over on his motorcycle to make it look more dangerous.<ref name=vfxworld/> Crowd creation was done for the ''[[Tosca]]'' scene by Machine FX, to make the performance look like it had sold out.<ref name=fxguide>{{cite news|title=Back into Bondage|date=16 November 2008|author=Bill Dawes|publisher=[[fxguide]]|url=http://www.fxguide.com/featured/back_into_bondage/|accessdate=22 November 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310150233/http://www.fxguide.com/featured/back_into_bondage/|archive-date=10 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Forster edited the opera scene to resemble ''[[The Man Who Knew Too Much (1956 film)|The Man Who Knew Too Much]]''.<ref name=comingsoon/> In total, there are 900+ visual effects shots in ''Quantum of Solace''.<ref name=vfxworld/>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|Quantum of Solace (soundtrack)}}\n[[David Arnold]], who composed the scores for the previous four Bond films, returned for ''Quantum of Solace''. He said that Forster likes to work very closely with his composers and that, in comparison to the accelerated schedule he was tied to on ''Casino Royale'', the intention was to spend a long time scoring the film to \"really work it out.\" He also said he would be \"taking a different approach\" with the score.<ref>{{cite video | people=Tommy Pearson, [[David Arnold]] | date=November 2007 | title=Interview with David Arnold | url=http://www.stageandscreenonline.com/_Media/DavidArnoldPart3.mp3 | format=mp3 | medium=Audio interview | publisher=Stage and Screen Online | accessdate=25 April 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080911055431/http://www.stageandscreenonline.com/_Media/DavidArnoldPart3.mp3 | archivedate=11 September 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Arnold composed the music based on impressions from reading the script, and Forster edited those into the film.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Beaumont|title=The Midas touch of David Arnold and his influence on Bond|work=[[The Times]]|date=18 October 2008|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article4948366.ece|accessdate=18 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref> As with ''Casino Royale'', Arnold kept use of the \"[[James Bond Theme]]\" to a minimum.<ref name=variety/> Arnold collaborated with [[Kieran Hebden]] for \"Crawl, End Crawl,\" a remix of the score played during the end credits.<ref>{{cite news|title='Crawl, End Crawl' track from 'Quantum of Solace' now on iTunes|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=9 December 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=7146&t=mi6&s=news|accessdate=9 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Jack White (musician)|Jack White]] of [[The White Stripes]] and [[Alicia Keys]] collaborated on \"[[Another Way to Die]],\" the first Bond music duet.<ref>{{cite news | title = Alicia Keys, Jack White Team For Bond Theme |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date = 29 July 2008 | url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044639/alicia-keys-jack-white-team-for-bond-theme | accessdate=29 July 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Quantum of Solace \u2013 News \u2013 Alicia Keys, Jack White Team For \"Quantum of Solace\" Theme Song (Press Release) | publisher = [[Columbia Pictures]] | date = 29 July 2008 | url = http://www.007.com/download/ThemeSong_QOS_PressRelease.pdf | accessdate=2 August 2008|format=PDF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327100324/http://www.007.com/download/ThemeSong_QOS_PressRelease.pdf|archivedate=27 March 2009}}</ref> They had wanted to work together for two years beforehand.<ref name=memphishorns/> The song was recorded in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]; White played the drums while Keys performed on the piano.<ref name=newduo>{{cite news|author=Brian Hiatt|title=Jack White and Alicia Keys: Bond's New Duo|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=2 October 2008|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/23064110/jack_white_and_alicia_keys_bonds_new_duo|accessdate=16 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215192816/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/23064110/jack_white_and_alicia_keys_bonds_new_duo|archivedate=15 February 2009}}</ref> [[The Memphis Horns]] also contributed to the track.<ref name=memphishorns>{{cite web|title=Jack White Talks Bond|website=[[IGN]]|date=21 August 2008|url=http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/901/901612p1.html|accessdate=21 August 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005114947/http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/901/901612p1.html|archivedate=5 October 2008}}</ref> White's favourite Bond theme is [[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]]'s instrumental piece for ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (soundtrack)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]'', and he watched various opening credit sequences from the series for inspiration while mixing the track.<ref name=newduo/> [[Mark Ronson]] and [[Amy Winehouse]] had recorded a [[demo (music)|demo]] track for the film,<ref>{{cite news | title = Winehouse working on 'Bond theme' |work=[[BBC News Online]] | date = 28 April 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7371949.stm | accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> but Ronson explained Winehouse's well-publicised legal issues in the preceding weeks made her \"not ready to record any music\" at that time.<ref>{{cite news | title = Troubled Winehouse 'not ready' for Bond theme | publisher = [[CNN]]/[[Associated Press|AP]] | date =3 May 2008 | accessdate=3 May 2008 | url = http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/03/winehouse.bond.ap/index.html |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080506020030/http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/03/winehouse.bond.ap/index.html |archivedate = 6 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered at the [[Odeon Leicester Square]] on 29 October 2008. Princes [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|William]] and [[Prince Harry|Harry]] attended, and proceeds from the screening were donated to the charities [[Help for Heroes]] and [[the Royal British Legion]].<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Quantum of Solace\" World Premiere Announced|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=5 August 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_premiere_announced.php3?t=qos&s=qos&id=01974|accessdate=6 August 2008}}</ref> The film was originally scheduled to be released in the UK and North America on 7 November; however, Eon pushed forward the British date to 31 October during filming,<ref>{{cite news | author = Olly Richards | title = Quantum of Solace Gets Earlier Release | work = [[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] | date = 19 March 2008 | url = http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=22223 | accessdate=19 March 2008}}</ref> while the American date was pushed back in August to 14 November, after ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' had been moved to 2009, thereby allowing the distributors to market the film over the autumn blockbuster [[Thanksgiving]] holiday weekend.<ref>{{cite news|author=Columbia Pictures|title=Quantum of Solace Moved Back a Week|publisher=ComingSoon.net|date=21 August 2008|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=48142|accessdate=21 August 2008}}</ref> In Australia, the film was moved a week to 19 November, after [[20th Century Fox]] chose to release ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' on ''Quantum of Solace''{{'}}s original date of 26 November.<ref>{{cite news|author=Garry Maddox|title=Bond blinks first in battle of blockbusters|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=6 September 2008|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/film/bond-blinks-first-in-battle-of-the-blockbusters/2008/09/05/1220121520755.html|accessdate=6 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nReturning [[product placement]] partners from ''Casino Royale'' included [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], [[Heineken]], [[Smirnoff]], [[Omega SA]], [[Virgin Atlantic]] and [[Sony Mobile Communications|Sony Ericsson]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Marc Graser|title=Brands line up for Bond sequel|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=14 August 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117990584.html |accessdate=15 August 2008}}</ref> A reported \u00a350&nbsp;million was earned in product placement, which tops the Bond films' record of \u00a344&nbsp;million for ''Die Another Day''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve McGinty|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/Does-this-mean-Bond39s-past.4630875.jp|title=Does this mean Bond's past his sell-by date?|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=27 October 2008|accessdate=15 November 2008}}</ref> The 2009 [[Ford Ka]] is driven by Camille in the film.<ref>\"[http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=6802&catid=106&t=mi6&s=news Bond girl Olga Kurylenko introduces Ford Ka at Paris Motor Show (video)],\" [[MI6-HQ.com]] (10 March 2008). Retrieved 8 November 2008.</ref> [[Avon Products|Avon]] created a fragrance called Bond Girl 007 with [[Gemma Arterton]] as the \"face\" of the product.<ref>{{cite news|title=Avon to introduce Bond Girl 007 fragrance with Gemma Arterton|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=23 May 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=6273|accessdate=12 August 2008}}</ref> [[Coca-Cola]] became a promotional partner, rebranding [[Coke Zero]] as \"Coke Zero Zero 7.\" A tie-in advert featured the orchestral element of \"Another Way to Die.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/video/2008/sep/11/advertising.jamesbond|title=Coca-Cola launches ad featuring Jack White's Quantum of Solace music|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Mark Sweney|date=11 September 2008|accessdate=18 September 2008 | location=London}}</ref> In the film, Coca-Cola was briefly seen being served at Dominic Greene's party. Sony held a competition, \"Mission for a Million,\" enabling registered players to use their products to complete certain tasks. Each completed \"mission\" gave consumers a chance to win $1&nbsp;million and a trip to a top-secret location.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission for a Million|publisher=[[Sony]]|url=http://www.sonymissionmillion.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928070031/http://www.sonymissionmillion.com/|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 September 2008|accessdate=4 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Merchandise====\n[[Corgi International Limited]] made 5-inch action figures and gadgets (such as a voice-activated briefcase), as well as its traditional [[die-cast toy]] vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |title=New 007 Toys & Gadgets 2008 |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=13 February 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_corgi_2008_toyfair3.php3 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Corgi Cars 2008 |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=3 February 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_corgi_2008_toyfair2.php3 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref> It also created 7-inch figures of characters from the previous films.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Corgi Action Figures|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=24 February 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_corgi_2008_toyfair1.php3 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref> [[Scalextric]] released four racing sets to coincide with the film.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scalextric 007 Racing Sets Unveiled |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=24 February 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_scalextric_2008_toyfair.php3?t=&s= |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref> [[Activision]] released its first James Bond game, also titled ''[[Quantum of Solace (video game)|Quantum of Solace]]'', which is based on both ''Casino Royale'' and ''Quantum of Solace''. It is the first [[James Bond (games)|Bond game]] to feature Craig's likeness and the first [[History of video game consoles (seventh generation)|seventh-generation console]] game in the series. [[Swatch]] designed a series of wrist watches, each of them inspired by a Bond villain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swatch Launch 007 Villains Watches|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=9 September 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_swatch_2008_launch.php3?t=&s=&id=02007|accessdate=14 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nThough the screenplay did not get made into a novel despite its original storyline, [[Penguin Books]] published a compilation of Fleming's short stories entitled ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)#Quantum of Solace|Quantum of Solace: The Complete James Bond Short Stories]]'', with a UK release date of 29 May 2008<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/0141189622 Amazon.co.uk listing]. Retrieved 28 June 2008.</ref> and a North American release date of 26 August 2008.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0143114581 Amazon.com listing]. Retrieved 24 May 2008</ref> The book combines the contents of Fleming's two short story collections, ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]''\u2014including the original \"Quantum of Solace\" short story\u2014and ''[[Octopussy and The Living Daylights]]''.\n\n===Home media===\n''Quantum of Solace'' was released on DVD and [[Blu-ray]] by [[MGM]] via [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] in Australia, the UK and North America from 18 to 24 March 2009. On the DVD sales chart the film opened at No. 3, grossing $21,894,957 from 1.21m DVD units sold.<ref name=\"the-numbers1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2008/JB22-DVD.php |title=Quantum of Solace \u2013 DVD Sales |publisher=The Numbers |accessdate=1 November 2009}}</ref> {{As of|2009|November|1}}, 2,643,250 DVD units were sold, generating $44,110,750 in sales revenue.<ref name=\"the-numbers1\"/> These figures do not include Blu-ray sales or DVD rentals. The DVDs were released in both a standard one-disc set and a deluxe two-disc special edition. There are no audio commentaries or deleted scenes on these editions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quantum of Solace Hits DVD & Blu-ray in March|publisher=ComingSoon.net|date=13 January 2009|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=51899|accessdate=13 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nUpon its opening in the UK, the film grossed \u00a34.9&nbsp;million ($8&nbsp;million), breaking the record for the largest Friday opening (31 October 2008) in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|author=Archie Thomas|title='Solace' makes quantum leap in U.K.|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1 November 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995122.html |accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> The film then broke the UK opening-weekend record, taking \u00a315.5&nbsp;million ($25&nbsp;million) in its first weekend, surpassing the previous record of \u00a314.9&nbsp;million held by ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]''. It earned a further \u00a314&nbsp;million in France and Sweden\u2014where it opened on the same day. The weekend gross of the equivalent of $10.6&nbsp;million in France was a record for the series, surpassing what ''Casino Royale'' made in five days by 16%. The $2.7&nbsp;million gross in Sweden was the fourth-highest opening for a film there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bond film smashes weekend records|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=3 November 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7705631.stm|accessdate=3 November 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Dave McNary|title=James Bond finds overseas 'Solace'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2 November 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995151.html |accessdate=3 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe following week, the film was playing in sixty countries. It grossed the equivalent of $39.3&nbsp;million in the UK, $16.5&nbsp;million in France and $7.7&nbsp;million in Germany on 7 November 2008.<ref>{{cite news|author=Pamela McClintock|title='Quantum' leap in overseas box office|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=8 November 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995539.html |accessdate=9 November 2008}}</ref> The film broke records in Switzerland, Finland, United Arab Emirates, Nigeria, Romania and Slovenia. Its Chinese and Indian openings were the second-largest ever for foreign-language films.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dave McNary|title='Quantum' rules foreign box office|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=9 November 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995548.html |accessdate=10 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe film grossed $27&nbsp;million on its opening day in 3,451 cinemas in Canada and the United States, where it was the number one film for the weekend, with $67.5&nbsp;million and $19,568 average per cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2008&wknd=46&p=.htm | title=Weekend Box Office Results from 11/14 \u2013 11/16 | website=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=14 November 2008}}</ref> It was the highest-grossing opening weekend ''Bond'' film in the US,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=jamesbond.htm | title=James Bond Movies | website=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=14 November 2008}}</ref> and tied with ''[[The Incredibles]]'' for the biggest November opening outside of the ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]'' series. The film earned a B- from [[CinemaScore]]'s audience surveys.<ref>{{cite news|author=Joshua Rich|title='Quantum of Solace' Stirs up a Win|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=16 November 2008|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20240780,00.html|accessdate=17 November 2008}}</ref> From the British opening on 31 October, through to the US opening weekend on 14 November, the film had grossed a total $319,128,882 worldwide. As of 10 February 2010, it had grossed the equivalent of $417,722,300 in countries other than Canada and the US, where it grossed $168,368,427, to give a total of $586,090,727.<ref name=\"bom\" />\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an [[approval rating]] of 65% based on 288 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 6.2/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Brutal and breathless, ''Quantum Of Solace'' delivers tender emotions along with frenetic action, but coming on the heels of ''Casino Royale'', it's still a bit of a disappointment.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/|title=Quantum of Solace (2008)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a weighted average score of 58 out of 100 based on 48 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/quantum-of-solace|title=Quantum of Solace Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> Critics generally preferred ''Casino Royale'', but continued to praise  Daniel Craig's depiction of Bond, and agree that the film is still an enjoyable addition to the series. The action sequences and pacing were praised, but criticism grew over the realism and serious but gritty feel that the film carried over.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Butler |title=UK Tomatometer Preview: Quantum Of Solace \u2013 Is the New Bond Shaken or Stirred? |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=31 October 2008 |url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1777726/uk_tomatometer_preview_quantum_of_solace_is_the_new_bond_shaken_or_stirred |accessdate=1 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081106152925/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1777726/uk_tomatometer_preview_quantum_of_solace_is_the_new_bond_shaken_or_stirred |archivedate= 6 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Moore]], the third actor to play Bond in the films, said that Daniel Craig was a \"damn good Bond but the film as a whole, there was a bit too much flash cutting [and] it was just like a commercial of the action. There didn't seem to be any geography and you were wondering what the hell was going on.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Roger Moore weighs in on 'Quantum of Solace'|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=16 March 2009|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=7432&t=mi6&s=news|accessdate=17 March 2009}}</ref> [[Kim Newman]] of ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' gave it 4/5, remarking it was not \"bigger and better than ''Casino Royale'', [which is] perhaps a smart move in that there's still a sense at the finish that Bond's mission has barely begun.\" However, he expressed nostalgia for the more humorous Bond films.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Kim Newman]]|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=134523|title=''Quantum of Solace'' (12A)|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=22 October 2008}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' review noted that \"following ''Casino Royale'' was never going to be easy, but the director Marc Forster has brought the brand's successful relaunch crashing back to earth\u2014with a yawn\"; the screenplay \"is at times incomprehensible\" and the casting \"is a mess.\" The review concludes that \"Bond has been stripped of his iconic status. He no longer represents anything particularly British, or even modern. In place of glamour, we get a spurious grit; instead of style, we get [[product placement]]; in place of fantasy, we get a redundant and silly realism.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Cosmo Landesman]]|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/film_reviews/article5001623.ece|title=Quantum of Solace \u2013 The Sunday Times review|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=26 October 2008|accessdate=28 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave a more positive review, rating it as 4 stars, and was particularly fond of  Daniel Craig's performance, saying he \"made the part his own, every inch the coolly ruthless agent-killer, nursing a broken heart and coldly suppressed rage\" and calling the film \"a crash-bang Bond, high on action, low on quips, long on location glamour, short on product placement\"; it concludes \"''Quantum of Solace'' isn't as good as ''Casino Royale'': the smart elegance off Daniel  Craig's Bond debut has been toned down in favour of conventional action. But the man himself powers this movie; he carries the film: it's an indefinably difficult task for an actor. Craig measures up.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Peter Bradshaw]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/oct/18/jamesbond1|title=Quantum of Solace|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=18 October 2008|accessdate=28 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n''[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]'' says, \"Notices will focus\u2014rightly\u2014on Craig's magnetism as the steely, sexy, murderous MI6 agent, but two other factors weigh in and freshen up proceedings: Forster's new technical team, led by cinematographer Roberto Schaefer and production designer Dennis Gassner. And the ongoing shift of M, as played by Judi Dench, to front and centre: the Bond girls fade into insignificance as she becomes his moral counterpoint and theirs is the only real relationship on screen.\" The review continues, \"Bond is, as has been previously noted, practically the [[Martin Scorsese]] of the [[BAFTA]]s: 22 films later, with grosses probably close to the [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] of one of the small nations it depicts, it's still waiting for that [[BAFTA Award for Best British Film|Alexander Korda award]]. The best ''Casino Royale'' could achieve was a gong for sound. Will this be the year that changes its fortunes?\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Quantum of Solace|publisher=Screen Daily|date=20 October 2008|url=http://www.screendaily.com/ScreenDailyArticle.aspx?intStoryID=41477|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', who praised the previous film, disliked ''Quantum of Solace''. He wrote that the plot was mediocre, characters weak, and that Bond lacked his usual personality, despite his praise for Daniel Craig's interpretation of the role. Throughout his review, he emphasised that \"James Bond is not an action hero.\"<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081111/REVIEWS/811129989 Review] by Roger Ebert, ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', 12 November 2008</ref> [[Kate Muir]] wrote in ''[[The Times]]'' that \"The ''Bond'' franchise is 50 years old this year, and the scriptless mess of ''Quantum of Solace'' may be considered its mid-life crisis\", before she went on to praise the film's successor ''[[Skyfall]]'' as a \"resurrection\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Muir|first=Kate|title=Bond's resurrection is one to die for|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=13 October 2012|authorlink=Kate Muir|location=London|page=4}}</ref> Some writers criticised the choice of ''Quantum of Solace'' as a title. \"Yes, it's a bad title,\" wrote Marni Weisz, the editor of ''Famous'', a Canadian film publication distributed in cinemas in that country, in an editorial entitled \"At least it's not ''[[Octopussy (film)|Octopussy]]''.\"<ref>Marni Weisz, \"At least it's not Octopussy,\" ''Famous'', October 2008, p. 6</ref>\n\nNot all the reviews were as critical. Tim Robey of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', in a reflective review of the film in 2013, was positive. He praised the film's shorter runtime, claiming that many other ''Bond'' films run out of steam before the end, and included ''Casino Royale'' in this category. Describing the film as having a \"rock-solid dramatic idea and the intelligence to run with it\", he gave the film four stars out of five.<ref>{{cite news|last=Robey|first=Tim|title=James Bond: Quantum of Solace, Review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/10540055/James-Bond-Quantum-of-Solace-review.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=30 December 2013|location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe film was nominated for Best Original Score, Best Original Song, Visual Effects, Film and Sound Editing at the 2008 [[Satellite Awards]], winning Best Song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2008.shtml|title=2008 13th Annual SATELLITE Awards|publisher=[[International Press Academy]]|accessdate=15 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209100353/http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2008.shtml <!-- Added by H3llBot -->|archivedate=9 December 2008}}</ref> It was nominated for Best Action Movie at the 2009 [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards|Critics' Choice Awards]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997072.html |author=Dade Hayes|title=Critics Choice favors 'Milk,' 'Button'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=9 December 2008|accessdate=9 December 2008}}</ref> and at the [[Empire Awards]], which is voted for by the public, it was shortlisted for Best Actor, Best Actress, Best Newcomer, Best Thriller and Best Soundtrack.<ref>{{cite news|title=Empire Awards nominate 'Quantum of Solace' five times, vote now online|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=2 March 2009|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=7396&t=mi6&s=news|accessdate=3 March 2009}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Saturn Award]] for Best Action/Adventure/Thriller Film, while Kurylenko and Dench were both nominated for the Best Supporting Actress award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saturnawards.org/nominations.html |title=Nominations for the 35th Annual Saturn Awards |publisher=[[Saturn Award|Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy & Horror Films]] |accessdate=17 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221234527/http://www.saturnawards.org/nominations.html |archivedate=21 February 2012  }}</ref> It was nominated by the [[7th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]] for \"Outstanding Compositing in a Feature Motion Picture.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.visualeffectssociety.com/ayear/7th-annual-ves-awards|title=7th Annual VES Awards|work=visual effects society|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nMovie critic Gilbert Cruz listed the film's pre-titles sequence as the eighth-greatest car chase in film history.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gilbert Cruz|title=The 15 Greatest Movie Car Chases of All Time|work=[[Time (magazine) | Time]]|date=1 May 2011|url=https://entertainment.time.com/2011/05/05/the-15-greatest-movie-car-chases-of-all-time/slide/quantum-of-solace-2008|accessdate=1 February 2020 | location=New York}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n* [[Eco-terrorism in fiction]]\n* [[Outline of James Bond]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* ''Bond on Set: Filming Quantum of Solace'', Greg Williams, DK ADULT (20 October 2008), {{ISBN|0-7566-4120-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Quantum of Solace}}\n{{commons category|Quantum of Solace (film)}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.007.com}}\n*{{IMDb title|0830515}}\n*{{Allmovie title|356351}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|quantum_of_solace}}\n*{{mojo title|jamesbond22}}\n\n{{James Bond films}}\n{{Quantum of Solace}}\n{{Marc Forster}}\n{{Paul Haggis}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Thriller}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:2000s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2000s adventure films]]\n[[Category:2000s spy films]]\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American adventure films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Best Thriller Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British adventure films]]\n[[Category:British sequel films]]\n[[Category:Central Intelligence Agency in fiction]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Eco-terrorism in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Environmental films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by David Arnold]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:British films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Marc Forster]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael G. Wilson]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Barbara Broccoli]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2006]]\n[[Category:Films set in Austria]]\n[[Category:Films set in Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Films set in Haiti]]\n[[Category:Films set in Italy]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in Russia]]\n[[Category:Films set in South America]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Austria]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Chile]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Italy]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Madrid]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Panama]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Wales]]\n[[Category:James Bond films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Pinewood Studios]]\n[[Category:Quantum of Solace]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Paul Haggis]]\n[[Category:Water scarcity in fiction]]\n[[Category:Eon Productions films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2008 film by Marc Forster}}\n{{about|the film|other uses|Quantum of Solace (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name = Quantum of Solace\n|image = Quantum of Solace - UK cinema poster.jpg\n|alt = Empire Design's poster for ''Quantum of Solace''\n|caption = UK theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Marc Forster]]\n| producer = \n  {{plainlist|\n*[[Michael G. Wilson]]\n*[[Barbara Broccoli]]\n}}\n| writer = \n  {{plainlist|\n*[[Paul Haggis]]\n*[[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade|Neal Purvis<br>Robert Wade]]}} <!-- DO NOT ADD \"MARC FORSTER\" OR \"DANIEL CRAIG\" HERE, THEY ARE MENTIONED IN PROSE -->\n| based on = {{Based on|[[James Bond (literary character)|James Bond]]|[[Ian Fleming]]}}\n|starring = \n  {{plainlist|\n*[[Daniel Craig]]\n*[[Olga Kurylenko]]\n*[[Mathieu Amalric]]\n*[[Gemma Arterton]]\n*[[Giancarlo Giannini]]\n*[[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]]\n*[[Judi Dench]]\n}}\n| music = [[David Arnold]]\n| cinematography = [[Roberto Schaefer]]\n| editing = \n  {{plainlist |\n*[[Matt Chesse]]\n*[[Richard Pearson (film editor)|Richard Pearson]]\n}}\n| studio = [[Eon Productions]]<br>[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures]]<br>[[Columbia Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/64729?sid=b7c9f0f6-6e18-402f-b725-a18e455f6bfc&sr=3.7816277&cp=1&pos=0|title=AFI-Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com}}</ref>\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|2008|10|29|[[London]]|2008|10|31|United Kingdom|2008|11|14|United States}}<!-- WP:FILMRELEASE -->\n| runtime = 106 minutes\n| country = {{plainlist|\n* United Kingdom<ref name=bfi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8bf92120|title=Quantum of Solace (2008)|work=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=29 May 2016}}</ref>\n* United States<ref name=bfi/>\n* Italy\n}}\n| language = English\n| budget = $230 million<ref name=artfilm/>\n| gross = $589.5 million<ref name=\"bom\">{{cite web|title=Quantum of Solace (2008)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jamesbond22.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Quantum of Solace''''' is a 2008 [[spy film]] and the twenty-second in the [[List of James Bond films|''James Bond'' series]] produced by [[Eon Productions]]. Directed by [[Marc Forster]] and written by [[Paul Haggis]], [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]], it is a direct sequel to [[Casino Royale (2006 film)|''Casino Royale'']], and the second film to star [[Daniel Craig]] as the fictional [[MI6]] agent [[James Bond]]. The film also stars [[Olga Kurylenko]], [[Mathieu Amalric]], [[Gemma Arterton]], [[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]], and [[Judi Dench]].  In the film, Bond seeks revenge for the death of his lover, [[Vesper Lynd]], and is assisted by [[Camille Montes]], who is plotting revenge for the murder of her own family.  The trail eventually leads them to wealthy businessman [[Dominic Greene]], a member of the [[Quantum (James Bond)|Quantum]] organisation<!-- \"Organisation\" is British spelling, and the article uses British spelling -->, which intends to stage a ''[[coup d'\u00e9tat]]'' in Bolivia to [[Water privatization in Bolivia|seize control of their water supply]]. \n\nProducer [[Michael G. Wilson]] developed the film's plot while the previous film in the series, [[Casino Royale (2006 film)|''Casino Royale'']], was being shot.  Purvis, Wade, and Haggis contributed to the script.  Although Craig and Forster wrote some sections themselves during the [[2007\u20132008 Writers Guild of America strike|screenwriter strike]],<ref name=Goldberg /> they received no such credits in the final cut.  The title was chosen from a 1959<!-- The story was first published in November 1959 in ''Modern Woman's Magazine'', q.v. For Your Eyes Only (short story collection) for the citation --> short story in [[Ian Fleming]]'s ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]'', though the film does not contain any elements of that story.  Location filming took place in Mexico, Panama, Chile, Italy, Austria and Wales, while interior sets were built and filmed at [[Pinewood Studios]].  Forster aimed to make a modern film that also featured classic cinema motifs: a vintage [[Douglas DC-3]] was used for a flight sequence, and [[Dennis Gassner]]'s set designs are reminiscent of [[Ken Adam]]'s work on several early ''Bond'' films.  Taking a course away from the usual [[List of James Bond villains|Bond villains]], Forster rejected any grotesque appearance for the character Dominic Greene to emphasise the hidden and secret nature of the film's contemporary villains.\n\nThe film was also marked by its frequent depictions of violence, with a 2012 study by the [[University of Otago]] in New Zealand finding it to be the most violent film in the franchise.  Whereas ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]'' featured 109 \"trivial or severely violent\" acts, ''Quantum of Solace'' had a count of 250\u2014the most depictions of violence in any ''Bond'' film\u2014even more prominent since it was also the shortest film in the franchise.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.meeja.com.au/2012/sean-connery-was-the-girliest-bond/|title=Sean Connery was the girliest Bond|publisher=Meeja|date=10 December 2012|accessdate=6 September 2011|location=Australia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108212058/http://meeja.com.au/2012/sean-connery-was-the-girliest-bond/|archivedate=8 January 2013}}</ref>  ''Quantum of Solace'' premiered at the [[Odeon Leicester Square]] on 29 October 2008, garnering generally polarized reviews, which mainly praised Craig's performance, the darker, grittier and realistic tone and the film's action sequences, but felt that the film was less impressive than the predecessor ''Casino Royale''.  {{As of|2016|September}}, it is the fourth-highest-grossing ''James Bond'' film, without adjusting for inflation, earning $589&nbsp;million worldwide, and becoming the [[2008 in film#Highest-grossing films|seventh highest-grossing film of 2008]].\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please remember to keep it short and around 600 words per WikiProject Films/Style guidelines, and that a spoiler warning is unnecessary per Wikipedia:Spoiler. -->\nMoments after the end of the previous film, James Bond is driving from [[Lake Como]] to [[Siena]], Italy, with the captured [[List of James Bond villains#Casino Royale 2006|Mr. White]] in the [[Trunk (automobile)|boot]] of his [[Aston Martin DBS V12]]. After evading pursuers Bond delivers White to [[M (James Bond)|M]], who interrogates him regarding the then unknown organisation, [[SPECTRE#Rebooted continuity|Quantum]]. M's [[bodyguard]], Craig Mitchell, is a double agent and attacks M, enabling White to escape. Bond chases Mitchell and kills him. Bond and M return to London and search Mitchell's flat, discovering Mitchell had a contact in [[Haiti]], Edmund Slate. Bond learns Slate is a hitman sent to kill [[Camille Montes]] at the behest of her lover, environmentalist entrepreneur [[List of James Bond villains#Quantum of Solace|Dominic Greene]]. Observing her subsequent meeting with Greene, Bond learns Greene is helping exiled Bolivian General Medrano, who murdered Camille's family, to overthrow the government and become the new president, in exchange for a seemingly barren piece of desert.\n\nAfter rescuing Camille from Medrano, Bond follows Greene to a performance of ''[[Tosca]]'' in [[Bregenz]], Austria. Meanwhile, the head of the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]]'s South American section, Gregg Beam, strikes a noninterference deal with Greene for access to putative stocks of Bolivian oil, which the CIA believes to be the reason for Greene's interest in the land. Bond infiltrates Quantum's meeting at the opera, identifying members of Quantum's executive board, and a gunfight ensues. A [[Counter Terrorism Command|Special Branch]] bodyguard working for Quantum member Guy Haines, an advisor to the British [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], is killed by one of Greene's men after Bond throws him off a roof. M assumes Bond killed him, and she has Bond's passports and credit cards revoked. Bond heads to Italy and convinces his old ally [[List of James Bond allies#Ren\u00e9 Mathis|Ren\u00e9 Mathis]] to accompany him to [[Bolivia]]. They are greeted by Strawberry Fields, a consular employee who demands Bond return to the UK immediately. Bond seduces her, and they attend a fundraising party Greene holds that night. At the party, Bond again rescues Camille from Greene. Leaving, Bond and Camille are pulled over by Bolivian police, paid off by Greene and Medrano. They had earlier attacked Mathis and put his body in Bond's car to frame Bond. In the ensuing struggle, Mathis and the policemen are killed.\n\nThe following day, Bond and Camille survey Quantum's intended land acquisition by air; their plane is shot down by a Bolivian fighter aircraft. They skydive into a sinkhole and discover Quantum is damming Bolivia's supply of fresh water to create a [[monopoly]]. Back in La Paz, Bond meets M and learns Quantum killed Fields by drowning her in [[Petroleum|crude oil]]. Bond meets CIA Agent [[Felix Leiter]], who discloses Greene and Medrano will meet in the [[Atacama Desert]] to finalise their agreement. Warned by Leiter, he evades the CIA's [[Special Activities Division]] when they attempt to kill him.\n\nAt an [[eco hotel]] in the desert, Greene tells Medrano that he now controls the majority of Bolivia's water supply, and Medrano must accept a new contract that makes Greene Bolivia's sole provider of water at significantly higher rates; if Medrano refuses, Greene will deprive the country of water until it [[societal collapse|collapses]]. Bond infiltrates the complex, kills the chief of police for betraying Mathis, and single-handedly assaults the hotel. After killing the security detail, he confronts Greene. Meanwhile, Camille kills Medrano, avenging the murders of her family. The struggle leaves the hotel destroyed by fire. Bond captures Greene and interrogates him about Quantum. Bond leaves him stranded in the desert with only a can of engine oil. \n\nBond travels to [[Kazan]], Russia, where he finds [[Vesper Lynd]]'s former lover, Yusef Kabira, a member of Quantum who seduces women with valuable connections and is indirectly responsible for her death. Bond tells Kabira's latest target, Corrine Veneau, a [[Canadian Security Intelligence Service|Canadian Intelligence]] agent, of Kabira's true intentions, thus sparing her Vesper's fate. He allows MI6 to arrest Kabira. Outside, M tells Bond that Greene was found dead in the middle of the desert, shot twice and with engine oil in his stomach. M tells Bond she needs him back; he responds that he never left. Walking away, he drops Vesper's necklace in the snow.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Daniel Craig]] as [[James Bond filmography|James Bond]]. Craig's physical training for his reprise of the role placed extra effort into running and boxing, to spare him the injuries he sustained on his stunts in the first film.<ref>{{cite news |author=Martyn Palmer |title=The man with the golden touch |work=[[The Times]] |date=24 November 2007|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article2900516.ece?token=null&offset=0 |accessdate=25 November 2007 | location=London}}</ref> Craig felt he was fitter, being less bulky than in the first film.<ref name=criminal/> He also practised speedboating and stunt driving. Craig felt ''Casino Royale'' was [physically] \"a walk in the park\" compared to ''Quantum of Solace'',<ref>{{cite web | title = Newswrap | publisher = Official site | format= Flash video | url = http://www.007.com/ | accessdate=1 March 2008}}</ref> which required a different performance from him because ''Quantum of Solace'' is a revenge film, not a love story like ''Casino Royale''.<ref name=criminal/> While filming in Pinewood, he suffered a gash when kicked in his face,<ref name=ew>{{cite news|author=Benjamin Svetkey|title=Bond is back!|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20237005,00.html|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> which required eight stitches, and a fingertip was sliced off. He laughed these off, noting they did not delay filming, and joked his finger wound would enable him to have a criminal career (though it had grown back when he made this comment).<ref name=criminal>{{cite news|author=John Naughton|title=Spy Harder|work=[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]|date=November 2008|pages=278\u2013335}}</ref> He also had minor plastic surgery on his face.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bond actor admits plastic surgery|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=9 October 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7660808.stm|accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref> The actor advised Paul Haggis on the script and helped choose [[Marc Forster]] as the director.<ref>{{cite news |author=Jennifer Vineyard |title=Daniel Craig Says He's Feeling The 'Pressure' Of James Bond Follow-Up |publisher=MTV |date=6 December 2007 |url=http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1575858/20071205/story.jhtml |accessdate=7 December 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Olga Kurylenko]] as [[Camille Montes]], a Bolivian agent with her own vendetta regarding Greene and Medrano. Forster chose her because out of the 400 women who auditioned, she seemed the least nervous.<ref name=premiereset>{{cite news|author=Matt Mueller|title=On the Set of 'Quantum Of Solace': Olga Kurylenko: The Bond Girl|work=[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]|url=http://www.premiere.com/Feature/On-the-Set-of-Quantum-Of-Solace/On-the-Set-of-Quantum-Of-Solace2|accessdate=14 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113010442/http://www.premiere.com/Feature/On-the-Set-of-Quantum-Of-Solace/On-the-Set-of-Quantum-Of-Solace2|archivedate=13 January 2010}}</ref> When she read the script, she was glad she had no love scene with Craig; she felt it would have distracted viewers from her performance.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tim Masters|title=Talking Shop: Olga Kurylenko|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=31 October 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7695332.stm|accessdate=31 October 2008}}</ref> Kurylenko spent three weeks training to fight with weapons, and she learnt a form of indoor skydiving known as body flying.<ref name=guardian/> Kurylenko said she had to do \"training non-stop from the morning to the evening\" for the action scenes, overcoming her fears with the help of Craig and the stunt team.<ref name=chilesoundbite>{{cite web|title = Chile Soundbites videos|publisher = Sony [[Electronic Press Kit]]|url = http://sony.epk.tv/campaign/quantum-of-solace|accessdate=11 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=ignqa/> She was given a DVD box set of Bond films, since the franchise was not easily available to watch in her native Ukraine.<ref name=guardian/> Kurylenko found [[Michelle Yeoh]] in ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'' inspiring \"because she did the fight scenes by herself.\"<ref name=premiereset/> The producers had intended to cast a South American actress in the role<ref name=diary22/>, thus, Kurylenko trained with a [[dialect coach]] to perform with a Spanish accent.<ref name=ignqa>{{cite web|author = Chris Tilly|title = Olga Kurylenko Q&A|website = [[IGN]]|date = 31 January 2008|url = http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/848/848813p1.html|accessdate = 31 January 2008|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080204085248/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/848/848813p1.html|archivedate = 4 February 2008|df = dmy-all}}</ref> She said that the accent was easy for her because she has \"a lot of Hispanic friends, from Latin America and Spain, and it's an accent I've always heard\".<ref>{{cite news|author = Rob Scheer|title = INTERVIEW: Olga Kurylenko on \"Quantum of Solace\"|publisher = [[UGO]]|date = 14 November 2008|url = http://www.cinecon.com/news/1825/interview-olga-kurylenko-quantum-of-solace/|accessdate=6 September 2011}}</ref> When reflecting on her experience as a [[Bond girl]], she stated she was proudest of overcoming her fears in performing stunts.<ref name=glasgowherald>{{cite news|author=David Giammarco|title=From Ukraine, with love|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|url=http://www.theherald.co.uk/features/features/display.var.2446992.0.From_Ukraine_with_love.php|accessdate=18 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903045044/http://www.theherald.co.uk/features/features/display.var.2446992.0.From_Ukraine_with_love.php|archivedate=3 September 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Mathieu Amalric]] as [[List of James Bond villains#Quantum of Solace|Dominic Greene]], the main villain. He is a leading member of Quantum posing as a businessman working in [[reforestation]] and charity funding for environmental science. In the 2015 Bond film ''[[Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre]]'', he is revealed to have been a member of the [[SPECTRE|titular crime syndicate]], of which Quantum is a subsidiary. Amalric acknowledged taking the role was an easy decision because, \"It's impossible to say to your kids that 'I could have been in a Bond film but I refused.'\"<ref name=guardian/> Amalric wanted to wear make-up for the role, but Forster explained that he wanted Greene not to look grotesque, but to symbolise the hidden evils in society.<ref name=ew/> Amalric modelled his performance on \"the smile of [[Tony Blair]] [and] the craziness of [[Nicolas Sarkozy|Sarkozy]],\" the latter of whom he called \"the worst villain we [the French] have ever had \u2026 he walks around thinking he's in a Bond film.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Bond villain spills the beans | work = [[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] | date = 24 January 2008 | url = http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/85747-bond-villain-spills-the-beans | accessdate=31 January 2008}}</ref> He later claimed this was not criticism of either politician, but rather an example of how a politician relies on performance instead of a genuine policy to win power. \"Sarkozy, is just a better actor than [his presidential opponent] [[S\u00e9gol\u00e8ne Royal]]\u2014that's all,\" he explained.<ref name=environment/> Amalric and Forster reconceived the character, who was supposed to have a \"special skill\" in the script, to someone who uses pure animal instinct when fighting Bond in the climax.<ref name=pity>{{cite news|title=Quantum of Solace: Mathieu Amalric on playing James Bond's nemesis|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2 October 2008|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2008/10/23/sm_mathieuamalric.xml|accessdate=23 October 2008|location=London|first=Murphy|last=Williams}}</ref> [[Bruno Ganz]] was also considered for the part,<ref name=diary22>{{cite news |title=Bond 22 Pre-Production Diary (22)|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=30 December 2007 |url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_preprod_diary22.php3?t=&s=articles |accessdate=31 December 2007}}</ref> but Forster decided Amalric gave the character a \"pitiful\" quality.<ref name=pity/>\n* [[Judi Dench]] as [[M (James Bond)|M]]. Forster felt Dench was underused in the previous films and wanted to make her part bigger, having her interact with Bond more because she is \"the only woman Bond doesn't see in a sexual context,\" which Forster finds interesting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fostering change|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=11 October 2008|url=http://www.star-ecentral.com/news/story.asp?file=/2008/10/11/movies/2202154&sec=movies|accessdate=13 October 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Gemma Arterton]] as MI6 agent Strawberry Fields, who works at the British consulate in Bolivia. Fields, who is merely an office worker as described by M, takes herself seriously and tries to overpower Bond when the pair meet. She is later seduced by Bond, infiltrates Greene's fund raiser party with him and ends up paying the ultimate price. Forster found Arterton a witty actress and selected her from a reported 1,500 candidates. One of the casting directors asked her to audition for the role, having seen her portray Rosaline in ''[[Love's Labour's Lost]]'' at the [[Globe Theatre]].<ref name=dianarigg>{{cite web | author = Chris Tilly | title = Gemma Arteron Q&A | website = [[IGN]] | date = 30 January 2008 | url = http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/848/848237p1.html | accessdate = 30 January 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080201171744/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/848/848237p1.html | archivedate = 1 February 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Arterton said Fields was \"not so frolicsome\" as other Bond girls, but is instead \"fresh and young, not \u2026 a [[femme fatale]].\"<ref name=bbctitle/> Arterton described Fields as a homage to the 1960s Bond girls, comparing her red wig to that of [[Diana Rigg]], who played [[Tracy Bond]] in ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (film)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]''. Rigg, alongside [[Honor Blackman]], is one of her favourite Bond girls.<ref name=dianarigg/> Arterton had to film her character's death scene first day on the set, where she was completely covered head to toe in non-toxic black paint. Although she found the experience unpleasant, she believed the scene would be an iconic part of the film.<ref name=Agent>{{cite news |title=SPOILER ALERT - Oilfinger: Exclusive picture shows Gemma Arterton coming to a sticky end in new Bond film|author=Harper, Tom|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=6 October 2008 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1068483/SPOILER-ALERT.html|accessdate=2 May 2009}}</ref> The character's full name, which is a reference to [[the Beatles]] song \"[[Strawberry Fields Forever]]\", is never actually uttered on screen; when Bond asks her for her name, she replies, \"Just Fields.\" Robert A. Caplen suggests that this is a conscious effort to portray a woman \"whose character attributes are neither undermined nor compromised\" by her name, even though her name may have sexual overtones reminiscent of earlier [[Bond girls]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Caplen|first=Robert A.|title=Shaken & Stirred: The Feminism of James Bond|year=2010|page=346|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8p-qpJjPU4C&pg=PA346|isbn=978-1-4535-1282-1}}</ref> In August 2018, Arterton wrote a short story titled ''Woke Bond Woman'', based on the character.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/international-news/article/gemma-arterton-pens-a-short-story-about-her-bond-character/268793|title=Gemma Arterton pens a short story about her Bond character|work=Times Now News|date=13 August 2018|accessdate=10 November 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Giancarlo Giannini]] as [[Ren\u00e9 Mathis]], Bond's ally who was mistakenly believed to be a traitor in ''Casino Royale''. Having been acquitted, he chooses to aid Bond again in his quest to find out who betrayed him.\n* [[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]] as [[Felix Leiter]], Bond's ally at the CIA. Early script drafts gave Leiter a larger role, but his screentime was restricted by on-set rewrites.<ref name=secret>{{cite web|title=The Secrets of Quantum of Solace |website=[[IGN]] |date=5 April 2008 |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/864/864542p1.html |accessdate=5 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410000608/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/864/864542p1.html |archivedate=10 April 2008  }}</ref>\n* [[Anatole Taubman]] as Elvis, Greene's second-in-command. Taubman wanted to make Elvis \"as colourful, as edgy and as interesting as possible\", with one of his suggestions being the [[bowl cut]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Anatole Taubman On Elvis|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=7 November 2008|url=http://mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_qos_capsule_elvis.php3?t=qos&s=qos&id=02075|accessdate=9 November 2008}}</ref> Amalric and Taubman improvised a backstory for Elvis: he is Dominic's cousin and once lived on the streets before being inducted into Quantum. He called Elvis \"a bit of a goofball. He thinks he's all that but he's not really.&nbsp;\u2026 He's not a comic guy. He definitely takes himself very serious, but maybe by his taking himself too serious he may become friendly.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = Elvis Rocks Bond's World | website = [[IGN]] | date = 16 May 2008 | url = http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/874/874700p1.html | accessdate = 16 May 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080521154755/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/874/874700p1.html | archivedate = 21 May 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[David Harbour]] as Gregg Beam, the CIA section chief for South America and a contact of Felix Leiter.\n* [[Joaqu\u00edn Cos\u00edo]] as General Medrano, the exiled general whom Greene is helping to get back into power, in return for support of his organisation. He murdered Camille's entire family when she was a young girl.\n* [[Fernando Guill\u00e9n Cuervo]] as Carlos, the Colonel of Bolivian Police, the chief of all police forces, and the contact of Ren\u00e9 Mathis in Bolivia.\n* [[Jesper Christensen]] as [[Mr. White (James Bond)|Mr. White]], whom Bond captured after he stole the money won at ''Casino Royale'' in Montenegro.\n* [[Rory Kinnear]] as [[Bill Tanner]], M's aide.\n* [[Paul Ritter (actor)|Paul Ritter]] as Guy Haines\n* [[Tim Pigott-Smith]] as the British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]].\n* [[Neil Jackson]] as Edmund Slate, a henchman who fights Bond in Haiti.\n* [[Simon Kassianides]] as Yusef, a member of Quantum who seduces female agents and manipulates them into giving away classified information. He is indirectly responsible for [[Vesper Lynd]]'s death.\n* [[Stana Katic]] as Corrine Veneau, a Canadian agent and Yusef's latest target.\n* Glenn Foster as Craig Mitchell, M's bodyguard and a double agent.\n* [[Oona Chaplin]] as Perla de las Dunas' receptionist, a woman saved by Camille Montes in one of the last sequences.\n* [[Lucrezia Lante della Rovere]] as Gemma, Mathis' girlfriend.\n* [[Elizabeth Arciniega]] as Mr. White's girlfriend.\n\nMarc Forster asked his friends and fellow directors [[Guillermo del Toro]] and [[Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n]] to appear in cameos. Cuar\u00f3n appears as a Bolivian helicopter pilot, while del Toro provides several other voices.<ref>{{cite news|title=Del Toro, Cuaron do voices in new Bond film|agency=Associated Press|date=23 October 2008|url=http://www.hitfix.com/articles/del-toro-cuaron-do-voices-in-new-bond-film|accessdate=23 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n{{quote|If you remember in ''[[Chinatown (1974 film)|Chinatown]]'', if you control the water you control the whole development of the country. I think it's true. Right now it appears to be oil, but there's a lot of other resources that we don't think about too much but are all essential, and they're very limited and every country needs it. Because every country knows that raising the standard of living (and populations are getting bigger) is the way we're all going.|Michael G. Wilson on the plot.<ref name=secret/>}}\n\nIn July 2006, as ''Casino Royale'' entered post-production, Eon Productions announced that the next film would be based on an original idea by producer [[Michael G. Wilson]].<ref>{{cite news |author= Tatiana Siegel and Borys Kit |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002840141 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011120117/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002840141 |archivedate=11 October 2007|title= Roger Michell in Talks for Bond 22 |work= [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date= 17 July 2006 |accessdate=17 July 2006}}</ref> It was decided beforehand the film would be a direct sequel, to exploit Bond's emotions following Vesper's death in the previous film.<ref>{{cite news | author = Liane Bonin | title = 10 Questions With: Daniel Craig | publisher = [[Moviefone]] | url = http://www.moviefone.com/insidemovies/2008/04/14/daniel-craig-interview-for-quantum-of-solace/ | accessdate = 11 April 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080613092700/http://www.moviefone.com/insidemovies/2008/04/14/daniel-craig-interview-for-quantum-of-solace/ | archivedate = 13 June 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Just as ''Casino Royale''{{'s}} theme was terrorism, the sequel focuses on environmentalism.<ref name=environment/> The film was confirmed for a 2 May 2008 release date, with Craig reprising the lead role.<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Columbia Pictures]] |title=22nd James Bond Coming May&nbsp;2,&nbsp;2008! |publisher=[[Superhero Hype!]] |date=20 July 2006 |url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/jamesbondnews.php?id=4521 |accessdate=6 August 2007}}</ref> [[Roger Michell]], who directed Craig in ''[[Enduring Love (film)|Enduring Love]]'' and ''[[The Mother (film)|The Mother]]'', was in negotiations to direct, but opted out because there was no script.<ref>{{cite news |title=They call him Director No|work=[[The Times]]|date=4 July 2007|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/theatre/article1877785.ece|accessdate=27 January 2008 | location=London |first=Greg |last=Hurst}}</ref> Sony Entertainment vice-chairman Jeff Blake admitted a production schedule of 18 months was a very short window, and the release date was pushed back to late 2008.<ref name=superherohype>{{cite news |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=16308 |title=Bond 22 Targeting November&nbsp;7,&nbsp;2008 |publisher= [[Superhero Hype!]] |date=1 September 2006|accessdate=1 September 2006}}</ref> [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]] completed their draft of the script by April 2007,<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Fleming|title='Barbarella' back in action|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=11 April 2007|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117962920.html |accessdate=6 August 2007}}</ref> and [[Paul Haggis]], who polished the ''Casino Royale'' script, began his rewrite the next month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Paul Haggis on board to work on Bond 22 script, but turns down directing role |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=23 May 2007|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=5040&catid=106 |accessdate=23 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, [[Marc Forster]] was confirmed as director.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003600629 |title=Forster back in action with 'Bond 22' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=20 June 2007 |accessdate=19 June 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930183557/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003600629 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref> He was surprised that he was approached for the job, stating he was not a big Bond film fan through the years, and that he would not have accepted the project had he not seen ''Casino Royale'' prior to making his decision: he felt Bond had been humanised in that film, arguing since travelling the world had become less exotic since the series' advent, it made sense to focus more on Bond as a character. Born in Germany and raised in Switzerland, Forster was the first Bond director not to come from the [[British Commonwealth of Nations]], although he noted Bond's mother is Swiss, making him somewhat appropriate to handle the British icon.<ref name=swiss>{{cite news |author=Terrence Rafferty |title=A License to Pursue the Inner Bond |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 December 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/09/movies/09raff.html |accessdate=9 December 2007}}</ref> The director collaborated strongly with [[Barbara Broccoli]] and Michael G. Wilson, noting they only blocked two very expensive ideas he had.<ref name=diary22/> The director found ''Casino Royale''{{'}}s 144-minute running time too long, and wanted his follow-up to be \"tight and fast \u2026 like a bullet.\"<ref name=bullet>{{cite news|author=Alistair Harkness|title=A Quantum leap|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/A-Quantum-leap.4643021.jp|accessdate=30 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Because Bond plays it real, I thought the political circumstances should be real too, even though Bond shouldn't be a political film. I thought the more political I make it, the more real it feels, not just with Bolivia and what's happening in Haiti, but with all these corporations like Shell and Chevron saying they're green because it's so fashionable to be green. During the Cold War, everything was very clear, the good guys and the bad guys. Today there's much overlapping of good and bad. It isn't as morally distinct, because we all have both elements in us.|Marc Forster on the political landscape of the film.<ref name=pain/>}}\n\nHaggis, Forster and Wilson rewrote the story from scratch.<ref name=zetumer/> Haggis said he completed his script two hours before the [[2007\u20132008 Writers Guild of America strike]] officially began.<ref name=swiss/> Forster noted a running theme in his films were emotionally repressed protagonists, and the theme of the picture would be Bond learning to trust after feeling betrayed by Vesper.<ref name=mi6forster/> Forster said he created the Camille character as a strong female counterpart to Bond rather than a casual love interest: she openly shows emotions similar to those which Bond experiences but is unable to express.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/911/911930p1.html|author=Jim Vejvoda|title=007 Responds to IGN Readers|website=[[IGN]]|date=22 September 2008|accessdate=22 September 2008}}</ref> Haggis located his draft's climax in the [[Swiss Alps]],<ref name=empire>{{cite news|author=Ian Nathan|title=Quantum's Leap|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|date=October 2008|pages=82\u201390}}</ref> but Forster wanted the action sequences to be based around the four [[classical element]]s of earth, water, air and fire.<ref name=variety>{{cite news|author=Anne Thompson|title='Solace' offers thinking person's 007|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=23 October 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117994573.html |accessdate=1 November 2008|authorlink=Anne Thompson (film critic)}}</ref> The decision to homage [[Oddjob]]'s murder of Jill Masterson ([[Shirley Eaton]]) in ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'' in Fields's death came about as Forster wanted to show oil had replaced gold as the most precious material.<ref name=pain>{{cite news|first=Ciaran |last=Carty|title='I felt there was pain in Bond'|work=[[Sunday Tribune]]|date=2 November 2008|url=http://tribune.maithu.com/article/2008/nov/02/i-felt-there-was-pain-in-bond/|accessdate=2 November 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206061930/http://www.tribune.ie/arts/films/article/2008/nov/02/i-felt-there-was-pain-in-bond/|archivedate=6 December 2008 }}</ref> The producers rejected Haggis's idea that Vesper Lynd had a child, because \"Bond was an orphan \u2026 Once he finds the kid, Bond can't just leave the kid.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Logan Hill|title=How James Bond Nearly Became a Father|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=3 November 2008|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2008/11/how_james_bond_nearly_became_a.html|accessdate=3 November 2008}}</ref> The [[Water supply and sanitation in Bolivia|water supply issue]] in Bolivia was the main theme of the film, with a story based on the [[Cochabamba]] [[2000 Cochabamba protests|Water Revolt]].<ref>[http://www.filmquarterly.org/2009/06/cinema-for-a-grand-new-game/ Cinema for a Grand New Game], ''[[Film Quarterly]]''</ref>\n\nMichael G. Wilson decided on the film's title ''Quantum of Solace'' only \"a few days\" before its announcement on 24 January 2008.<ref name=bbctitle>{{cite news |title=New Bond film title is confirmed |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=24 January 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7206997.stm |accessdate=24 January 2008}}</ref> It was the name of a short story in [[Ian Fleming]]'s anthology ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]'' (1960).<ref name=confuse/> The film is related to the title in one of its thematic elements: \"when the 'Quantum of Solace' drops to zero, humanity and consideration of one human for another is gone.\" Daniel Craig admitted, \"I was unsure at first. Bond is looking for his quantum of solace and that's what he wants, he wants his closure. Ian Fleming says that if you don't have a quantum of solace in your relationship then the relationship is over. It's that spark of niceness in a relationship that if you don't have you might as well give up.\"<ref name=guardian/> He said that \"Bond doesn't have that because his girlfriend [Vesper Lynd] has been killed,\"<ref name=confuse>{{cite news |title=Daniel: the title is meant to confuse |work=[[Press and Journal (Scotland)|Press and Journal]] |date=24 January 2008}}</ref> and therefore, \"[Bond is] looking for revenge \u2026 to make himself happy with the world again.\"<ref name=bbctitle/> Afterwards, Quantum was made the name of the organisation introduced in ''Casino Royale''.<ref name=quantum/> Craig noted the letter Q itself looks rather odd.<ref name=criminal/> Near the end of the film, the Camille Montes character and Bond have a discussion about their individual quests to avenge the deaths of their loved ones. Montes asks Bond to \"let me know what it feels like\" when he succeeds, the implication of the title being that it will be a small amount of solace compared to his despair. Bond's lack of emotion when he does exact revenge shows this to be the case.\n\nAccording to a December 2011 interview with Craig, \"We had the bare bones of a script and then there was a writers' strike and there was nothing we could do. We couldn't employ a writer to finish it. I say to myself, 'Never again', but who knows? There was me trying to rewrite scenes\u2014and a writer I am not.\"<ref name=Goldberg>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|title=Daniel Craig Talks about the Script Problems on QUANTUM OF SOLACE; Says Why He's Encouraged for SKYFALL|url=http://collider.com/daniel-craig-quantum-of-solace-script-problems/130951/|website=Collider|accessdate=29 August 2012|date=7 December 2011}}</ref> He said that he and Forster \"were the ones allowed to do it. The rules were that you couldn't employ anyone as a writer, but the actor and director could work on scenes together. We were stuffed. We got away with it, but only just. It was never meant to be as much of a sequel as it was, but it ended up being a sequel, starting where the last one finished.\"<ref name=Goldberg/>\n\nDuring filming, after the strike ended, Forster read a [[spec script]] by Joshua Zetumer, which he liked, and hired him to reshape scenes for the later parts of the shoot, which the director was still unsatisfied with.<ref name=zetumer>{{cite web|title=A James Bond Set Visit and Seven Exclusive Quantum of Solace Images! |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=4 April 2008 |url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1719930/a_james_bond_set_visit_and_seven_exclusive_quantum_of_solace_images |accessdate=5 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005195337/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1719930/a_james_bond_set_visit_and_seven_exclusive_quantum_of_solace_images |archivedate= 5 October 2008 }}</ref> Forster had the actors rehearse their scenes, as he liked to film scenes continually.<ref name=environment>{{cite news | author = Karl Rozemeyer | title = Mathieu Amalric on Being the 'Bond 22' Villain | work = [[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]] | date = 18 March 2008 | url = http://www.premiere.com/features/4455/mathieu-amalric-on-being-the-bond-22-villain.html | accessdate=19 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321210654/http://www.premiere.com/features/4455/mathieu-amalric-on-being-the-bond-22-villain.html|archivedate=21 March 2008}}</ref> Zetumer rewrote dialogue depending on the actors' ideas each day.<ref name=environment/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Ingresso della Forra a Tremosine.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''Strada delle Forre'' in [[Tremosine]] ([[Italy]]) where the movie begins.]]\n''Quantum of Solace'' was shot in six countries.<ref name=artfilm>{{cite news|author=Randee Dawn|title='Quantum' is Marc Forster's 007 art film|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=11 November 2008|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ie9098baec9eb95cd02a01aebbd96a968|accessdate=13 November 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113031127/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ie9098baec9eb95cd02a01aebbd96a968|archivedate=13 November 2008}}</ref> [[Second unit]] filming began in Italy at the [[Palio di Siena]] horse race on 16 August 2007,<ref name=paliodisiena>{{cite news|author=Richard Owen|title=Bond has activists on his tail over new film's 'brutal' horse race finale|work=[[The Times]]|date=13 August 2007|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article2246486.ece|accessdate=13 August 2007 | location=London}}</ref> although at that point Forster was unsure how it would fit into the film.<ref name=variety/> Some scenes were filmed also in [[Maratea]] and [[Craco]], two small distinctive towns in [[Basilicata]] in southern Italy.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=imdb.com|title=Filming locations for Quantum of Solace|date=11 November 2008|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0830515/locations|accessdate=2 June 2009}}</ref> Other places used for location shooting were [[Madrid]] in August 2007;<ref>{{cite news |title=Bond 22 filming takes place in Madrid, Spain during last week of August|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=31 August 2007|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=5327 |accessdate=25 March 2008}}</ref> [[Baja California]], Mexico in early 2008, for shots of the aerial battle;<ref name=dogfight>{{cite news|title=Newswrap No. 2 video |publisher=[[ReelzChannel]] |date=20 March 2008 |url=http://www.reelzchannel.com/movie/233698/quantum-of-solace?clipid=32934 |accessdate=20 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080322172830/http://www.reelzchannel.com/movie/233698/quantum-of-solace?clipid=32934 |archivedate=22 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=David Allen|title=A bond with Chino|publisher=[[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]]|date=28 February 2008|url=http://www.dailybulletin.com/ci_8399719|accessdate=2 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603232620/http://www.dailybulletin.com/ci_8399719|archivedate=3 June 2008 }}</ref> [[Malcesine]], [[Limone sul Garda]] and [[Tremosine]] in Italy during March,<ref name=siena>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (16) | publisher= [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 17 March 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary16.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=20 March 2008}}</ref> and at [[Talamone]] during the end of April.<ref name=fountain>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (19) | publisher= [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 27 March 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary19.php3?t=&s= | accessdate=28 March 2008}}</ref> The main unit began on 3 January 2008<ref name=diary22/> at [[Pinewood Studios]]. The [[007 Stage]] was used for the fight in the art gallery,<ref name=guardian>{{cite news |author=Mark Brown|title=Everything changes but Bond |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=24 January 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/jan/24/features|accessdate=24 January 2008 | location=London}}</ref> and an MI6 safehouse hidden within the city's [[cistern]]s,<ref name=bbcbts>{{cite news |author=Tim Marsters |title=Behind the scenes on the Bond set |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=25 January 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7208410.stm |accessdate=25 January 2008}}</ref> while other stages housed Bond's Bolivian hotel suite,<ref name=modernism/> and the MI6 headquarters.<ref name=bbcbts/> Interior and exterior airport scenes were filmed at [[Farnborough Airfield]] and the snowy closing scenes were filmed at the Bruneval Barracks in [[Aldershot]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/2038353_barracks_and_airport_provide_location_for_bond_film|title = Barracks and airport provide location for Bond film|accessdate=18 November 2008|author=Rebecca Connop Price|date=30 October 2008|publisher=Get Hampshire|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110913050519/http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/2038353_barracks_and_airport_provide_location_for_bond_film|archivedate=13 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nShooting in [[Panama City]] began on 7 February 2008 at [[Howard Air Force Base]]. The country doubled for Haiti and Bolivia, with the National Institute of Culture of Panama standing in for a hotel in the latter country. A sequence requiring several hundred [[extra (actor)|extras]] was also shot at nearby [[Col\u00f3n, Panama|Col\u00f3n]].<ref name=andeanhotel>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (11) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 9 February 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary11.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=9 February 2008}}</ref> Shooting in Panama was also carried out at [[Fort Sherman]], a former US military base on the Col\u00f3n coast. Forster was disappointed he could only shoot the boat chase in that harbour, as he had a more spectacular vision for the scene.<ref name=comingsoon>{{cite news|author=Edward Douglas|title=Marc Forster Finds His Quantum of Solace|publisher=ComingSoon.net|date=10 November 2008|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=50314|accessdate=10 November 2008}}</ref> Officials in the country worked with the locals to \"minimise inconvenience\" for the cast and crew, and in return hoped the city's exposure in the film would increase tourism.<ref name=proddiarynine>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (9) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 2 February 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary09.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=8 February 2008}}</ref> The crew was going to move to [[Cusco]], Peru for ten days of filming on 2 March,<ref name=andeanhotel/> but the location was cancelled for budget reasons.<ref name=artfilm/> Twelve days of filming in Chile began on 24 March at [[Antofagasta]]. There was shooting in [[Cobija, Chile|Cobija]], the [[Paranal Observatory]], and other locations in the [[Atacama Desert]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (17) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 19 March 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary17.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=20 March 2008}}</ref> Forster chose the desert and the observatory's [[ESO Hotel]] to represent Bond's rigid emotions, and being on the verge of committing a vengeful act as he confronts Greene in the film's climax.<ref name=quantum>{{cite news | title = Seeking Solace on the Bond set |work=[[USA Today]] | date = 3 April 2008 | url = https://www.usatoday.com/life/flash.htm?gid=459 | accessdate=4 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=water/>\n[[File:Paranal camp.jpg|thumb|left|Marc Forster chose the [[Atacama Desert]] to represent Bond's vengefulness in the climax.|alt=A scientific facility in a desert]]\nDuring filming in [[Sierra Gorda, Chile]], the local mayor, Carlos Lopez, staged a protest because he was angry at the filmmakers' portrayal of the [[Antofagasta Region]] as part of Bolivia. He was arrested, detained briefly, and put on trial two days later. Eon dismissed his claim that they needed his permission to film in the area.<ref>{{cite news | author = Simon Gardner | title = James Bond has new nemesis: irate Chilean mayor | agency=Reuters | date = 2 April 2008 | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUKN0237294620080402 | accessdate=13 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = 'Mayor' protests on Chile 007 set |work=[[BBC News Online]] | date = 2 April 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7326582.stm | accessdate=3 April 2008}}</ref> Michael G. Wilson explained that Bolivia was appropriate to the plot, because of the country's history of water problems,<ref name=water>{{cite news |author=Anthony Breznican |title=James Bond series takes a 'Quantum' leap |work=USA Today |date=4 April 2008|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2008-04-03-bond-quantum_N.htm |accessdate=4 April 2008}}</ref> and was surprised the two countries disliked each other a century after the [[War of the Pacific]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (22) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 7 April 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary22.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=10 April 2008}}</ref> In a poll by Chilean daily newspaper ''[[La Segunda]]'', 75% of its readers disagreed with Lopez's actions, due to the negative image of Chile they felt it presented, and the controversy's potential to put off productions looking to film in the country in the future.<ref>{{cite news | title = \u00bfApoya Ud. las protestas del alcalde de Sierra Gorda por la filmaci\u00f3n de James Bond en su comuna? | work = [[La Segunda]] | date = 2 March 2008 | url = http://www.lasegunda.com/edicionOnline/interaccion/encuestas/resultado.asp?idencuesta=2512&idclasificacion=3&fg= | archive-url = https://archive.today/20080405174454/http://www.lasegunda.com/edicionOnline/interaccion/encuestas/resultado.asp?idencuesta=2512&idclasificacion=3&fg= | url-status = dead | archive-date = 5 April 2008 | language=Spanish | accessdate=2 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nFrom 4\u201312 April the main unit shot on Sienese rooftops.<ref name=fountain/> Shooting on the real rooftops turned out to be less expensive than building them at Pinewood.<ref name=artfilm/> The next four weeks were scheduled for filming the car chase at [[Lake Garda]] and [[Carrara]].<ref name=fountain/> On 19 April, an [[Aston Martin]] employee driving a [[Aston Martin DBS V12|DBS]] to the set crashed into the lake. He survived, and was fined \u00a3400 for reckless driving.<ref>{{cite news | author = Nick Pisa | title = Driver of James Bond's Aston Martin cheated death in dramatic crash |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date = 22 April 2008}}</ref> Another accident occurred on 21 April, and two days later, two stuntmen were seriously injured, with one, Greek stuntman Aris Comninos, having to be put in intensive care. Filming of the scenes was temporarily halted so that Italian police could investigate the causes of the accidents.<ref>{{cite news | author = Paul Bompard | title = James Bond production halted amid fears of a curse |work=[[The Times]] | date = 24 April 2008 | url =http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article3810782.ece | accessdate=24 April 2008 | location=London}}</ref> Stunt co-ordinator Gary Powell said the accidents were a testament to the realism of the action.<ref name=empire/> Rumours of a \"curse\" spread among tabloid media, something which deeply offended Craig, who disliked that they compared Comninos' accident to something like his minor finger injury later on the shoot (also part of the \"curse\"). Comninos recovered safely from his injury.<ref name=criminal/>\n\nFor the role Craig trained to be less bulky than in ''Casino Royale'' and told ''[[Men's Fitness]]'' magazine \"In fact, I was much fitter for this film compared to ''Casino Royale''\u2014I really had to be\u2014and I was running a hell of a lot more in training, just so I could do these scenes, whereas last time I spent far more time pumping heavy weights to bulk up so I could look big.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mattpomroy.com/2008/12/01/quantum-physique/|title=Quantum Physique|date=1 December 2008|website=Matt Pomroy|access-date=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nFilming took place at the [[Bregenzer Festspiele|floating opera stage]] at [[Bregenz]], Austria, from 28 April \u2013 9 May 2008. The sequence in which Bond stalks the villains during a performance of ''[[Tosca]]'' required 1,500 extras.<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (10) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 8 February 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary10.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=9 February 2008}}</ref> The production used a large model of an eye, which Forster felt fitted in the Bond style, and the opera itself has parallels to the film.<ref name=lake>{{cite news|title='Quantum of Solace' set visit: filming in Austria; Craig's next Bond moves; 007's new foes; rumors laid to rest|publisher=[[MSN]]|date=8 May 2008|url=http://movies.msn.com/movies/hitlist/05-13-08|accessdate=16 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010045516/http://movies.msn.com/movies/hitlist/05-13-08/|archivedate=10 October 2009}}</ref> A short driving sequence was filmed at the nearby [[Feldkirch, Vorarlberg]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Production Diary (1) |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=3 January 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary01.php3?t=&s=articles |accessdate=8 January 2008}}</ref> The crew returned to Italy from 13\u201317 May to shoot a (planned) car crash at the marble quarry in Carrara,<ref>{{cite news | title = Production Diary (32) | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 16 May 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary32.php3?t=qos&s=qos | accessdate=16 May 2008}}</ref> and a recreation of the Palio di Siena at the [[Piazza del Campo]] in Siena. 1,000 extras were hired for a scene where Bond emerges from the ''Fonte Gaia''. Originally, he would have emerged from the city's cisterns at [[Siena Cathedral]], but this was thought disrespectful.<ref name=fountain/> By June the crew returned to Pinewood for four weeks,<ref name=lake/> where new sets (including the interior of the hotel in the climax) were built.<ref name=zetumer/><ref name=modernism/> The [[wrap (filmmaking)|wrap]] party was held on 21 June.<ref>{{cite news | title = 'Quantum of Solace' wrap party held on Saturday night, David Arnold confirms | publisher = [[MI6-HQ.com]] | date = 22 June 2008 | url = http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=6394 | accessdate=22 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Design===\nProduction designer [[Peter Lamont]], a crew member on 18 previous Bond films, retired after ''Casino Royale''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Peter Lamont bows out from Bond 22, Dennis Gassner to be Production Designer |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=23 July 2007|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=5206 |accessdate=23 July 2007}}</ref> Forster hired [[Dennis Gassner]] in his stead, having admired his work on ''[[The Truman Show]]'' and the films of the [[Coen brothers]].<ref name=mi6forster>{{cite web|url=http://mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_qos_capsule_forster.php3?t=qos&s=qos&id=02080|title=Marc Forster on directing 007|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=11 November 2008|accessdate=13 November 2008}}</ref> Craig said the film would have \"a touch of [[Ken Adam]],\"<ref name=kenadam>{{cite news |author=Olly Richards |title=Daniel Craig Talks Quantum of Solace |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=24 January 2008 |url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=21855 |accessdate=24 January 2008}}</ref> while Michael G. Wilson also called Gassner's designs \"a [[postmodern]] look at [[modernism]].\"<ref name=modernism>{{cite news|title=Quantum of Solace \u2013 Production Diary (7)|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=26 January 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_prod_diary07.php3?t=&s=|accessdate=26 January 2008}}</ref> Forster said he felt the early Bond films' design \"were ahead of their time,\"<ref name=mi6forster/> and enjoyed the clashing of an older style with his own because it created a unique look unto itself.<ref name=aicnqa/> Gassner wanted his sets to emphasize Craig's \"great angular, textured face and wonderful blue eyes,\" and totally redesigned the MI6 headquarters because he felt Judi Dench \"was a bit tired in the last film, so I thought, let's bring her into a new world.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=James Bond: licence to redesign|work=[[Maclean's]]|date=17 November 2008|url=http://blog.macleans.ca/2008/11/17/james-bond-licence-to-redesign/|accessdate=18 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nLouise Frogley replaced [[Lindy Hemming]] as [[costume design]]er, though Hemming remained as supervisor. Hemming hired [[Brioni (fashion)|Brioni]] for Bond's suits since her tenure on the series began with 1995's ''[[GoldenEye]]'', but Lindsay Pugh, another supervisor, explained their suits were \"too relaxed.\" [[Tom Ford]] was hired to tailor \"sharper\" suits for Craig. Pugh said the costumes aimed towards the 1960s feel, especially for Bond and Fields. [[Prada]] provided the dresses for both Bond girls. [[Jasper Conran]] designed Camille's ginger bandeau, bronze skirt and gold fish necklace,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasperconran.com/collections/womenswear/archive/james-bond,116,ART.html |title=Jasper Conran Spring Summer 2008 Collection |publisher=Jasperconran.com |accessdate=12 September 2010}}</ref> while [[Chrome Hearts]] designed gothic jewelry for Amalric's character, which the actor liked enough to keep after filming.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jessica Fellowes|title=James Bond week: 007 and his girls are back with a crisp new look|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 October 2008|url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG3365681/James-Bond-week-007-and-his-girls-are-back-with-a-crisp-new-look.html|accessdate=25 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref> Sophie Harley, who created [[Vesper Lynd]]'s earrings and Algerian loveknot necklace in ''Casino Royale'', was called upon to create another version of the necklace.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jessica Fellowes|title=Necklace with a starring role|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 October 2008|url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG3365680/Necklace-with-a-starring-role.html|accessdate=25 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe film returns to the traditional [[James Bond gun barrel sequence|gun barrel opening shot]], which was altered into part of the story for ''Casino Royale'' where it was moved to the beginning of the title sequence. In this film the gun barrel sequence was moved to the end of the movie, which Wilson explained was done for a surprise,<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Caro|title=15 James Bond facts you need to know|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=9 November 2008|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-11-09/news/0811070249_1_casino-royale-daniel-craig-olga-kurylenko|accessdate=8 November 2008}}</ref> and to signify the conclusion of the story begun in the previous film. The opening credits sequence was created by [[MK12]]. Having worked on Forster's ''[[Stranger than Fiction (2006 film)|Stranger than Fiction]]'' and ''[[The Kite Runner (film)|The Kite Runner]]'', MK12 spontaneously began developing the sequence early on in production, and had a good idea of its appearance which meant it did not have to be redone when the [[#Music|title singer]] was changed. MK12 selected various twilight colours to represent Bond's mood and focused on a dot motif based on the gunbarrel shot. MK12 also worked on scenes with [[graphical user interface]]s, including the electronic table MI6 uses,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://vfxworld.com/index.php?atype=articles&id=3881 |author=Bill Desowitz |title=MK12 Has a Blast with Quantum Main Titles |publisher=VFXWorld |date=16 January 2009 |accessdate=26 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607045355/http://vfxworld.com/index.php?atype=articles&id=3881 |archivedate= 7 June 2009 }}</ref> and the [[Port-au-Prince]], Haiti title cards.<ref>{{cite news|author=Yves Peters|title=MK12 Create Custom Type for Quantum of Solace Title Sequence|publisher=[[FontShop]]|date=19 December 2008|url=http://fontfeed.com/archives/mk12-quantum-of-solace-title-sequence/|accessdate=22 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222234148/http://fontfeed.com/archives/mk12-quantum-of-solace-title-sequence/|archivedate=22 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Effects===\n[[File:AstonMartinDBSCC08.jpg|thumb|right|[[Aston Martin DBS V12]] on display at the 2008 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]|alt=A black car in an exhibition.]]\n''Quantum of Solace'' was the last in [[Ford Motor Company|Ford Motor]]'s three-film deal that began with 2002's ''[[Die Another Day]]''. Although Ford sold over 90% of the [[Aston Martin]] company in 2007, the [[Aston Martin DBS V12]] returned for the film's car chase around Lake Garda;<ref>{{cite news |title=Aston Martin DBS to star in new James Bond film |publisher=[[Aston Martin]] |year=2007 |url=http://www.astonmartin.com/thecompany/news?a=14d34f22-1324-4ca5-acbb-764f80c7d7f2 |accessdate=11 December 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523032827/http://www.astonmartin.com/thecompany/news?a=14d34f22-1324-4ca5-acbb-764f80c7d7f2|archivedate=23 May 2009}}</ref> [[Dan Bradley]] was hired as [[second unit]] director because of his work on the second and third [[Bourne (film series)|''Bourne'' films]], so the film would continue the gritty action style begun in ''Casino Royale''.<ref>{{cite news |author=Borys Kit |title=Bradley tapped to aid Bond stunts |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=4 September 2007 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i61cdc71247ef46a7ec4bddbba9463397 |accessdate=10 January 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070913085544/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i61cdc71247ef46a7ec4bddbba9463397 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 13 September 2007}}</ref> He had intended to use [[Ford GT]]s for the opening chase,<ref>{{cite web|title=Dan Bradley interview |publisher=Bourne Stunt Simulator |url=http://www.bournestuntsimulator.com/danbradley/ |accessdate=16 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128143935/http://www.bournestuntsimulator.com/danbradley/ |archivedate=28 January 2008 }}</ref> but it was replaced by the [[Alfa Romeo 159]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1902288/James-Bond-filming-suspended-after-third-accident-leaves-stuntman-in-coma.html|title=James Bond filming suspended after third accident leaves stuntman in coma|accessdate=28 April 2008|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=28 April 2008 | location=London | first=Malcolm | last=Moore}}</ref> After location filming in Italy, further close-ups of Craig, the cars and the truck were shot at Pinewood against a blue screen.<ref name=vfxworld>{{cite news|author=Bill Desowitz|title=A Quantum of VFX for James Bond|publisher=VFX World|date=3 December 2008|url=http://vfxworld.com/?atype=articles&id=3844&page=1#|accessdate=4 December 2008}}</ref> Originally three Alfa Romeos were in the sequence: but Forster felt the scene was running too long and re-edited the scene so it only looked like two Alfas were chasing Bond.<ref name=fxguide/> Ten cars were supplied by Aston Martin. Six 'hero' cars, needed for close-ups and promotional work, all survived filming unharmed with four more cars used for special effects and stunts.<ref>https://astonmartins.com/car/dbs-v12-for-007-q/</ref>\n\nFourteen cameras were used to film the [[Palio di Siena]] footage, which was later edited into the main sequence. Aerial shots using helicopters were banned, and the crew were also forbidden from showing any violence \"involving either people or animals.\"<ref name=paliodisiena/> To shoot the foot chase in [[Siena]] in April 2008 four camera cranes were built in the town, and a [[Skycam|cable camera]] was also used.<ref name=siena/> [[Framestore]] worked on the Siena chase, duplicating the 1,000 extras during principal photography to match shots of the 40,000-strong audience at the real Palio, removing wires that held Craig and the stuntmen in the rooftop segment of the chase, and digital expansion of the floor and skylight in the art gallery Bond and Mitchell fall into.<ref name=vfxworld/> The art gallery fight was intended to be simple, but during filming Craig's stunt double accidentally fell from the construction scaffolding. Forster preferred the idea of Bond hanging from ropes reaching for his gun to kill Mitchell, rather than having both men run out of the building to continue their chase as specified in the script, and the number of effects shots increased.<ref name=vfxworld/>\n\nTo film the aerial dogfight, a \"Snakehead\" camera was built and placed on the nose and tail of a [[Piper Aerostar]] 700. [[SolidWorks]], who provided the software used to design the camera, stated \"pilots for the first time can fly as aggressively as they dare without sacrificing the drama of the shot.\" The camera could turn 360 degrees and was shaped like a [[periscope]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Chris Reidy | title = \"Snakehead\" films James Bond dogfight footage |work=[[The Boston Globe]] | date = 12 May 2008 | url = http://www.boston.com/business/ticker/2008/05/_the_concord_of.html | accessdate=12 May 2008}}</ref> The crew also mounted SpaceCams on helicopters, and placed cameras with 1600mm lenses underground, to cover the action.<ref name=dogfight/> Forster wanted to film the plane fight as a homage to [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[North by Northwest]]'', and chose planes like the [[Douglas DC-3]] to suit that.<ref name=aicnqa>{{cite news|title=Capone talks with James Bond himself, Daniel Craig, and Quantum of Solace director Marc Forster in London!!!|publisher=[[Ain't It Cool News]]|date=21 September 2008|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/38427|accessdate=22 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For Your Eyes Only: RT in Austria with James Bond |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=9 May 2008 |url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1727255/2/for_your_eyes_only_rt_in_austria_with_james_bond |accessdate=16 May 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208092012/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1727255/2/for_your_eyes_only_rt_in_austria_with_james_bond |archivedate= 8 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[free-fall]] scene involved its own set of challenges; Director Marc Forster didn't want to shoot the scene against a green screen.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.budgettravel.com/article/quantum-of-solace-we-interview-the-director-plus-a-video-clip-of-bond-in-action_10236|title=Quantum of Solace--We interview the director--Plus a\u2026|last=Travel|first=Budget|date=3 October 2012|website=Budget Travel|language=en|access-date=31 January 2019}}</ref> The scene was shot in an air tunnel at Bodyflight, which offers the same effects as skydiving.<ref name=\":0\" />  Daniel Craig and Olga Kurylenko did their own stunts for this scene.<ref name=\":0\" /> While a great solution for the actors' performances, the technique presented enormous VFX challenges: relighting shots captured in a tall white tube to match the sky over the Bolivian desert; and the impossibility of filming medium to wide shots of the actors. An array of eight [[Dalsa Origin]] cameras (supported by seven HD cameras and a 35mm hand-held camera, all running in sync) was used to create a [[virtual camera]] with which to shoot the actors floating in the simulator. [[Ged Wright]] and his team at [[Double Negative (VFX)|Double Negative]]<ref name=fxguide/> developed a method to use the data from these cameras that allowed these real performances to be placed in a synthetic environment as seen by a synthetic camera.\nDuring the shooting in the wind tunnel Craig and Kurylenko wore wind-resistant contact lenses that enabled them to open their eyes as they fell. For safety and comfort, they only shot for 30 seconds at a time.<ref name=ugoqa>{{cite news|url=http://movieblog.ugo.com/index.php/movieblog/more/your_quantum_of_solace_questions_answered/ |title=Your Quantum of Solace Questions Answered! |publisher=[[UGO Networks]] |date=21 September 2008 |accessdate=22 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924230111/http://movieblog.ugo.com/index.php/movieblog/more/your_quantum_of_solace_questions_answered/ |archivedate=24 September 2008 }}</ref> Forster wished he had had more time to work on the free-fall scene.<ref name=vfxworld/>\n\nThe [[Moving Picture Company]] created the climactic hotel sequence. The fire effects were supervised by [[Chris Corbould]], and post-production MPC had to enhance the sequence by making the smoke look closer to the actors, so it would look more dangerous.<ref name=vfxworld/> A full-scale replica of the building's exterior was used for the exploding part Bond and Camille escape from.\nThe boat chase was another scene that required very little CGI. Machine FX worked on replacing a few shots of visible stuntmen with a digital version of Craig's head,<ref name=fxguide/> and recreated the boats Bond jumps over on his motorcycle to make it look more dangerous.<ref name=vfxworld/> Crowd creation was done for the ''[[Tosca]]'' scene by Machine FX, to make the performance look like it had sold out.<ref name=fxguide>{{cite news|title=Back into Bondage|date=16 November 2008|author=Bill Dawes|publisher=[[fxguide]]|url=http://www.fxguide.com/featured/back_into_bondage/|accessdate=22 November 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310150233/http://www.fxguide.com/featured/back_into_bondage/|archive-date=10 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Forster edited the opera scene to resemble ''[[The Man Who Knew Too Much (1956 film)|The Man Who Knew Too Much]]''.<ref name=comingsoon/> In total, there are 900+ visual effects shots in ''Quantum of Solace''.<ref name=vfxworld/>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|Quantum of Solace (soundtrack)}}\n[[David Arnold]], who composed the scores for the previous four Bond films, returned for ''Quantum of Solace''. He said that Forster likes to work very closely with his composers and that, in comparison to the accelerated schedule he was tied to on ''Casino Royale'', the intention was to spend a long time scoring the film to \"really work it out.\" He also said he would be \"taking a different approach\" with the score.<ref>{{cite video | people=Tommy Pearson, [[David Arnold]] | date=November 2007 | title=Interview with David Arnold | url=http://www.stageandscreenonline.com/_Media/DavidArnoldPart3.mp3 | format=mp3 | medium=Audio interview | publisher=Stage and Screen Online | accessdate=25 April 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080911055431/http://www.stageandscreenonline.com/_Media/DavidArnoldPart3.mp3 | archivedate=11 September 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Arnold composed the music based on impressions from reading the script, and Forster edited those into the film.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Beaumont|title=The Midas touch of David Arnold and his influence on Bond|work=[[The Times]]|date=18 October 2008|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article4948366.ece|accessdate=18 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref> As with ''Casino Royale'', Arnold kept use of the \"[[James Bond Theme]]\" to a minimum.<ref name=variety/> Arnold collaborated with [[Kieran Hebden]] for \"Crawl, End Crawl,\" a remix of the score played during the end credits.<ref>{{cite news|title='Crawl, End Crawl' track from 'Quantum of Solace' now on iTunes|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=9 December 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=7146&t=mi6&s=news|accessdate=9 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Jack White (musician)|Jack White]] of [[The White Stripes]] and [[Alicia Keys]] collaborated on \"[[Another Way to Die]],\" the first Bond music duet.<ref>{{cite news | title = Alicia Keys, Jack White Team For Bond Theme |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date = 29 July 2008 | url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044639/alicia-keys-jack-white-team-for-bond-theme | accessdate=29 July 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Quantum of Solace \u2013 News \u2013 Alicia Keys, Jack White Team For \"Quantum of Solace\" Theme Song (Press Release) | publisher = [[Columbia Pictures]] | date = 29 July 2008 | url = http://www.007.com/download/ThemeSong_QOS_PressRelease.pdf | accessdate=2 August 2008|format=PDF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327100324/http://www.007.com/download/ThemeSong_QOS_PressRelease.pdf|archivedate=27 March 2009}}</ref> They had wanted to work together for two years beforehand.<ref name=memphishorns/> The song was recorded in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]; White played the drums while Keys performed on the piano.<ref name=newduo>{{cite news|author=Brian Hiatt|title=Jack White and Alicia Keys: Bond's New Duo|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=2 October 2008|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/23064110/jack_white_and_alicia_keys_bonds_new_duo|accessdate=16 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215192816/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/23064110/jack_white_and_alicia_keys_bonds_new_duo|archivedate=15 February 2009}}</ref> [[The Memphis Horns]] also contributed to the track.<ref name=memphishorns>{{cite web|title=Jack White Talks Bond|website=[[IGN]]|date=21 August 2008|url=http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/901/901612p1.html|accessdate=21 August 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005114947/http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/901/901612p1.html|archivedate=5 October 2008}}</ref> White's favourite Bond theme is [[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]]'s instrumental piece for ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (soundtrack)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]'', and he watched various opening credit sequences from the series for inspiration while mixing the track.<ref name=newduo/> [[Mark Ronson]] and [[Amy Winehouse]] had recorded a [[demo (music)|demo]] track for the film,<ref>{{cite news | title = Winehouse working on 'Bond theme' |work=[[BBC News Online]] | date = 28 April 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7371949.stm | accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> but Ronson explained Winehouse's well-publicised legal issues in the preceding weeks made her \"not ready to record any music\" at that time.<ref>{{cite news | title = Troubled Winehouse 'not ready' for Bond theme | publisher = [[CNN]]/[[Associated Press|AP]] | date =3 May 2008 | accessdate=3 May 2008 | url = http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/03/winehouse.bond.ap/index.html |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080506020030/http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Music/05/03/winehouse.bond.ap/index.html |archivedate = 6 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered at the [[Odeon Leicester Square]] on 29 October 2008. Princes [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|William]] and [[Prince Harry|Harry]] attended, and proceeds from the screening were donated to the charities [[Help for Heroes]] and [[the Royal British Legion]].<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Quantum of Solace\" World Premiere Announced|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=5 August 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond_22_premiere_announced.php3?t=qos&s=qos&id=01974|accessdate=6 August 2008}}</ref> The film was originally scheduled to be released in the UK and North America on 7 November; however, Eon pushed forward the British date to 31 October during filming,<ref>{{cite news | author = Olly Richards | title = Quantum of Solace Gets Earlier Release | work = [[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] | date = 19 March 2008 | url = http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=22223 | accessdate=19 March 2008}}</ref> while the American date was pushed back in August to 14 November, after ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' had been moved to 2009, thereby allowing the distributors to market the film over the autumn blockbuster [[Thanksgiving]] holiday weekend.<ref>{{cite news|author=Columbia Pictures|title=Quantum of Solace Moved Back a Week|publisher=ComingSoon.net|date=21 August 2008|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=48142|accessdate=21 August 2008}}</ref> In Australia, the film was moved a week to 19 November, after [[20th Century Fox]] chose to release ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' on ''Quantum of Solace''{{'}}s original date of 26 November.<ref>{{cite news|author=Garry Maddox|title=Bond blinks first in battle of blockbusters|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=6 September 2008|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/film/bond-blinks-first-in-battle-of-the-blockbusters/2008/09/05/1220121520755.html|accessdate=6 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nReturning [[product placement]] partners from ''Casino Royale'' included [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], [[Heineken]], [[Smirnoff]], [[Omega SA]], [[Virgin Atlantic]] and [[Sony Mobile Communications|Sony Ericsson]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Marc Graser|title=Brands line up for Bond sequel|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=14 August 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117990584.html |accessdate=15 August 2008}}</ref> A reported \u00a350&nbsp;million was earned in product placement, which tops the Bond films' record of \u00a344&nbsp;million for ''Die Another Day''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve McGinty|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/Does-this-mean-Bond39s-past.4630875.jp|title=Does this mean Bond's past his sell-by date?|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=27 October 2008|accessdate=15 November 2008}}</ref> The 2009 [[Ford Ka]] is driven by Camille in the film.<ref>\"[http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=6802&catid=106&t=mi6&s=news Bond girl Olga Kurylenko introduces Ford Ka at Paris Motor Show (video)],\" [[MI6-HQ.com]] (10 March 2008). Retrieved 8 November 2008.</ref> [[Avon Products|Avon]] created a fragrance called Bond Girl 007 with [[Gemma Arterton]] as the \"face\" of the product.<ref>{{cite news|title=Avon to introduce Bond Girl 007 fragrance with Gemma Arterton|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=23 May 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=6273|accessdate=12 August 2008}}</ref> [[Coca-Cola]] became a promotional partner, rebranding [[Coke Zero]] as \"Coke Zero Zero 7.\" A tie-in advert featured the orchestral element of \"Another Way to Die.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/video/2008/sep/11/advertising.jamesbond|title=Coca-Cola launches ad featuring Jack White's Quantum of Solace music|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Mark Sweney|date=11 September 2008|accessdate=18 September 2008 | location=London}}</ref> In the film, Coca-Cola was briefly seen being served at Dominic Greene's party. Sony held a competition, \"Mission for a Million,\" enabling registered players to use their products to complete certain tasks. Each completed \"mission\" gave consumers a chance to win $1&nbsp;million and a trip to a top-secret location.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission for a Million|publisher=[[Sony]]|url=http://www.sonymissionmillion.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928070031/http://www.sonymissionmillion.com/|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 September 2008|accessdate=4 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Merchandise====\n[[Corgi International Limited]] made 5-inch action figures and gadgets (such as a voice-activated briefcase), as well as its traditional [[die-cast toy]] vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |title=New 007 Toys & Gadgets 2008 |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=13 February 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_corgi_2008_toyfair3.php3 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Corgi Cars 2008 |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=3 February 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_corgi_2008_toyfair2.php3 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref> It also created 7-inch figures of characters from the previous films.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Corgi Action Figures|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=24 February 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_corgi_2008_toyfair1.php3 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref> [[Scalextric]] released four racing sets to coincide with the film.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scalextric 007 Racing Sets Unveiled |publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]] |date=24 February 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_scalextric_2008_toyfair.php3?t=&s= |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref> [[Activision]] released its first James Bond game, also titled ''[[Quantum of Solace (video game)|Quantum of Solace]]'', which is based on both ''Casino Royale'' and ''Quantum of Solace''. It is the first [[James Bond (games)|Bond game]] to feature Craig's likeness and the first [[History of video game consoles (seventh generation)|seventh-generation console]] game in the series. [[Swatch]] designed a series of wrist watches, each of them inspired by a Bond villain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swatch Launch 007 Villains Watches|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=9 September 2008|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/collecting_swatch_2008_launch.php3?t=&s=&id=02007|accessdate=14 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nThough the screenplay did not get made into a novel despite its original storyline, [[Penguin Books]] published a compilation of Fleming's short stories entitled ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)#Quantum of Solace|Quantum of Solace: The Complete James Bond Short Stories]]'', with a UK release date of 29 May 2008<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/0141189622 Amazon.co.uk listing]. Retrieved 28 June 2008.</ref> and a North American release date of 26 August 2008.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0143114581 Amazon.com listing]. Retrieved 24 May 2008</ref> The book combines the contents of Fleming's two short story collections, ''[[For Your Eyes Only (short story collection)|For Your Eyes Only]]''\u2014including the original \"Quantum of Solace\" short story\u2014and ''[[Octopussy and The Living Daylights]]''.\n\n===Home media===\n''Quantum of Solace'' was released on DVD and [[Blu-ray]] by [[MGM]] via [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] in Australia, the UK and North America from 18 to 24 March 2009. On the DVD sales chart the film opened at No. 3, grossing $21,894,957 from 1.21m DVD units sold.<ref name=\"the-numbers1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2008/JB22-DVD.php |title=Quantum of Solace \u2013 DVD Sales |publisher=The Numbers |accessdate=1 November 2009}}</ref> {{As of|2009|November|1}}, 2,643,250 DVD units were sold, generating $44,110,750 in sales revenue.<ref name=\"the-numbers1\"/> These figures do not include Blu-ray sales or DVD rentals. The DVDs were released in both a standard one-disc set and a deluxe two-disc special edition. There are no audio commentaries or deleted scenes on these editions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quantum of Solace Hits DVD & Blu-ray in March|publisher=ComingSoon.net|date=13 January 2009|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=51899|accessdate=13 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nUpon its opening in the UK, the film grossed \u00a34.9&nbsp;million ($8&nbsp;million), breaking the record for the largest Friday opening (31 October 2008) in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|author=Archie Thomas|title='Solace' makes quantum leap in U.K.|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1 November 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995122.html |accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> The film then broke the UK opening-weekend record, taking \u00a315.5&nbsp;million ($25&nbsp;million) in its first weekend, surpassing the previous record of \u00a314.9&nbsp;million held by ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]''. It earned a further \u00a314&nbsp;million in France and Sweden\u2014where it opened on the same day. The weekend gross of the equivalent of $10.6&nbsp;million in France was a record for the series, surpassing what ''Casino Royale'' made in five days by 16%. The $2.7&nbsp;million gross in Sweden was the fourth-highest opening for a film there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bond film smashes weekend records|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=3 November 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7705631.stm|accessdate=3 November 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Dave McNary|title=James Bond finds overseas 'Solace'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2 November 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995151.html |accessdate=3 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe following week, the film was playing in sixty countries. It grossed the equivalent of $39.3&nbsp;million in the UK, $16.5&nbsp;million in France and $7.7&nbsp;million in Germany on 7 November 2008.<ref>{{cite news|author=Pamela McClintock|title='Quantum' leap in overseas box office|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=8 November 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995539.html |accessdate=9 November 2008}}</ref> The film broke records in Switzerland, Finland, United Arab Emirates, Nigeria, Romania and Slovenia. Its Chinese and Indian openings were the second-largest ever for foreign-language films.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dave McNary|title='Quantum' rules foreign box office|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=9 November 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995548.html |accessdate=10 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe film grossed $27&nbsp;million on its opening day in 3,451 cinemas in Canada and the United States, where it was the number one film for the weekend, with $67.5&nbsp;million and $19,568 average per cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2008&wknd=46&p=.htm | title=Weekend Box Office Results from 11/14 \u2013 11/16 | website=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=14 November 2008}}</ref> It was the highest-grossing opening weekend ''Bond'' film in the US,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=jamesbond.htm | title=James Bond Movies | website=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=14 November 2008}}</ref> and tied with ''[[The Incredibles]]'' for the biggest November opening outside of the ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]'' series. The film earned a B- from [[CinemaScore]]'s audience surveys.<ref>{{cite news|author=Joshua Rich|title='Quantum of Solace' Stirs up a Win|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=16 November 2008|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20240780,00.html|accessdate=17 November 2008}}</ref> From the British opening on 31 October, through to the US opening weekend on 14 November, the film had grossed a total $319,128,882 worldwide. As of 10 February 2010, it had grossed the equivalent of $417,722,300 in countries other than Canada and the US, where it grossed $168,368,427, to give a total of $586,090,727.<ref name=\"bom\" />\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an [[approval rating]] of 65% based on 288 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 6.2/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Brutal and breathless, ''Quantum Of Solace'' delivers tender emotions along with frenetic action, but coming on the heels of ''Casino Royale'', it's still a bit of a disappointment.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/|title=Quantum of Solace (2008)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a weighted average score of 58 out of 100 based on 48 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/quantum-of-solace|title=Quantum of Solace Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> Critics generally preferred ''Casino Royale'', but continued to praise  Daniel Craig's depiction of Bond, and agree that the film is still an enjoyable addition to the series. The action sequences and pacing were praised, but criticism grew over the realism and serious but gritty feel that the film carried over.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Butler |title=UK Tomatometer Preview: Quantum Of Solace \u2013 Is the New Bond Shaken or Stirred? |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=31 October 2008 |url=http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1777726/uk_tomatometer_preview_quantum_of_solace_is_the_new_bond_shaken_or_stirred |accessdate=1 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081106152925/http://uk.rottentomatoes.com/m/quantum_of_solace/news/1777726/uk_tomatometer_preview_quantum_of_solace_is_the_new_bond_shaken_or_stirred |archivedate= 6 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Moore]], the third actor to play Bond in the films, said that Daniel Craig was a \"damn good Bond but the film as a whole, there was a bit too much flash cutting [and] it was just like a commercial of the action. There didn't seem to be any geography and you were wondering what the hell was going on.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Roger Moore weighs in on 'Quantum of Solace'|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=16 March 2009|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=7432&t=mi6&s=news|accessdate=17 March 2009}}</ref> [[Kim Newman]] of ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' gave it 4/5, remarking it was not \"bigger and better than ''Casino Royale'', [which is] perhaps a smart move in that there's still a sense at the finish that Bond's mission has barely begun.\" However, he expressed nostalgia for the more humorous Bond films.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Kim Newman]]|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=134523|title=''Quantum of Solace'' (12A)|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=22 October 2008}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' review noted that \"following ''Casino Royale'' was never going to be easy, but the director Marc Forster has brought the brand's successful relaunch crashing back to earth\u2014with a yawn\"; the screenplay \"is at times incomprehensible\" and the casting \"is a mess.\" The review concludes that \"Bond has been stripped of his iconic status. He no longer represents anything particularly British, or even modern. In place of glamour, we get a spurious grit; instead of style, we get [[product placement]]; in place of fantasy, we get a redundant and silly realism.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Cosmo Landesman]]|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/film_reviews/article5001623.ece|title=Quantum of Solace \u2013 The Sunday Times review|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=26 October 2008|accessdate=28 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave a more positive review, rating it as 4 stars, and was particularly fond of  Daniel Craig's performance, saying he \"made the part his own, every inch the coolly ruthless agent-killer, nursing a broken heart and coldly suppressed rage\" and calling the film \"a crash-bang Bond, high on action, low on quips, long on location glamour, short on product placement\"; it concludes \"''Quantum of Solace'' isn't as good as ''Casino Royale'': the smart elegance off Daniel  Craig's Bond debut has been toned down in favour of conventional action. But the man himself powers this movie; he carries the film: it's an indefinably difficult task for an actor. Craig measures up.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Peter Bradshaw]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/oct/18/jamesbond1|title=Quantum of Solace|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=18 October 2008|accessdate=28 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n''[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]'' says, \"Notices will focus\u2014rightly\u2014on Craig's magnetism as the steely, sexy, murderous MI6 agent, but two other factors weigh in and freshen up proceedings: Forster's new technical team, led by cinematographer Roberto Schaefer and production designer Dennis Gassner. And the ongoing shift of M, as played by Judi Dench, to front and centre: the Bond girls fade into insignificance as she becomes his moral counterpoint and theirs is the only real relationship on screen.\" The review continues, \"Bond is, as has been previously noted, practically the [[Martin Scorsese]] of the [[BAFTA]]s: 22 films later, with grosses probably close to the [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] of one of the small nations it depicts, it's still waiting for that [[BAFTA Award for Best British Film|Alexander Korda award]]. The best ''Casino Royale'' could achieve was a gong for sound. Will this be the year that changes its fortunes?\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Quantum of Solace|publisher=Screen Daily|date=20 October 2008|url=http://www.screendaily.com/ScreenDailyArticle.aspx?intStoryID=41477|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', who praised the previous film, disliked ''Quantum of Solace''. He wrote that the plot was mediocre, characters weak, and that Bond lacked his usual personality, despite his praise for Daniel Craig's interpretation of the role. Throughout his review, he emphasised that \"James Bond is not an action hero.\"<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081111/REVIEWS/811129989 Review] by Roger Ebert, ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', 12 November 2008</ref> [[Kate Muir]] wrote in ''[[The Times]]'' that \"The ''Bond'' franchise is 50 years old this year, and the scriptless mess of ''Quantum of Solace'' may be considered its mid-life crisis\", before she went on to praise the film's successor ''[[Skyfall]]'' as a \"resurrection\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Muir|first=Kate|title=Bond's resurrection is one to die for|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=13 October 2012|authorlink=Kate Muir|location=London|page=4}}</ref> Some writers criticised the choice of ''Quantum of Solace'' as a title. \"Yes, it's a bad title,\" wrote Marni Weisz, the editor of ''Famous'', a Canadian film publication distributed in cinemas in that country, in an editorial entitled \"At least it's not ''[[Octopussy (film)|Octopussy]]''.\"<ref>Marni Weisz, \"At least it's not Octopussy,\" ''Famous'', October 2008, p. 6</ref>\n\nNot all the reviews were as critical. Tim Robey of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', in a reflective review of the film in 2013, was positive. He praised the film's shorter runtime, claiming that many other ''Bond'' films run out of steam before the end, and included ''Casino Royale'' in this category. Describing the film as having a \"rock-solid dramatic idea and the intelligence to run with it\", he gave the film four stars out of five.<ref>{{cite news|last=Robey|first=Tim|title=James Bond: Quantum of Solace, Review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/10540055/James-Bond-Quantum-of-Solace-review.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=30 December 2013|location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe film was nominated for Best Original Score, Best Original Song, Visual Effects, Film and Sound Editing at the 2008 [[Satellite Awards]], winning Best Song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2008.shtml|title=2008 13th Annual SATELLITE Awards|publisher=[[International Press Academy]]|accessdate=15 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209100353/http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2008.shtml <!-- Added by H3llBot -->|archivedate=9 December 2008}}</ref> It was nominated for Best Action Movie at the 2009 [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards|Critics' Choice Awards]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997072.html |author=Dade Hayes|title=Critics Choice favors 'Milk,' 'Button'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=9 December 2008|accessdate=9 December 2008}}</ref> and at the [[Empire Awards]], which is voted for by the public, it was shortlisted for Best Actor, Best Actress, Best Newcomer, Best Thriller and Best Soundtrack.<ref>{{cite news|title=Empire Awards nominate 'Quantum of Solace' five times, vote now online|publisher=[[MI6-HQ.com]]|date=2 March 2009|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=7396&t=mi6&s=news|accessdate=3 March 2009}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Saturn Award]] for Best Action/Adventure/Thriller Film, while Kurylenko and Dench were both nominated for the Best Supporting Actress award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saturnawards.org/nominations.html |title=Nominations for the 35th Annual Saturn Awards |publisher=[[Saturn Award|Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy & Horror Films]] |accessdate=17 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221234527/http://www.saturnawards.org/nominations.html |archivedate=21 February 2012  }}</ref> It was nominated by the [[7th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]] for \"Outstanding Compositing in a Feature Motion Picture.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.visualeffectssociety.com/ayear/7th-annual-ves-awards|title=7th Annual VES Awards|work=visual effects society|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nMovie critic Gilbert Cruz listed the film's pre-titles sequence as the eighth-greatest car chase in film history.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gilbert Cruz|title=The 15 Greatest Movie Car Chases of All Time|work=[[Time (magazine) | Time]]|date=1 May 2011|url=https://entertainment.time.com/2011/05/05/the-15-greatest-movie-car-chases-of-all-time/slide/quantum-of-solace-2008|accessdate=1 February 2020 | location=New York}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n* [[Eco-terrorism in fiction]]\n* [[Outline of James Bond]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* ''Bond on Set: Filming Quantum of Solace'', Greg Williams, DK ADULT (20 October 2008), {{ISBN|0-7566-4120-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Quantum of Solace}}\n{{commons category|Quantum of Solace (film)}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.007.com}}\n*{{IMDb title|0830515}}\n*{{Allmovie title|356351}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|quantum_of_solace}}\n*{{mojo title|jamesbond22}}\n\n{{James Bond films}}\n{{Quantum of Solace}}\n{{Marc Forster}}\n{{Paul Haggis}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Thriller}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:2000s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2000s adventure films]]\n[[Category:2000s spy films]]\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American adventure films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Best Thriller Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British adventure films]]\n[[Category:British sequel films]]\n[[Category:Central Intelligence Agency in fiction]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Eco-terrorism in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Environmental films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by David Arnold]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:British films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Marc Forster]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael G. Wilson]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Barbara Broccoli]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2006]]\n[[Category:Films set in Austria]]\n[[Category:Films set in Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Films set in Haiti]]\n[[Category:Films set in Italy]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in Russia]]\n[[Category:Films set in South America]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Austria]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Chile]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Italy]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Madrid]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Panama]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Wales]]\n[[Category:James Bond films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Pinewood Studios]]\n[[Category:Quantum of Solace]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Paul Haggis]]\n[[Category:Water scarcity in fiction]]\n[[Category:Eon Productions films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]]\n", "name_user": "Percytown", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_of_Solace"}
{"title_page": "Confessions of a Pop Performer", "text_new": "{{short description|1975 film by Norman Cohen}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Confessions of a Pop Performer\n| image          = \"Confessions_of_a_Pop_Performer\"_(1975).jpg\n| image_size     =  \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Norman Cohen]]\n| producer       = [[Greg Smith (film producer)|Greg Smith]]<br>[[Michael Klinger (producer)|Michael Klinger]] (executive producer)\n| writer         = [[Christopher Wood (writer)|Christopher Wood]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Robin Askwith]]<br>[[Antony Booth]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Alan Hume]]\n| editing        = [[Geoffrey Foot (film editor)|Geoffrey Foot]]\n| distributor    = [[Columbia pictures]]\n| released       = July 1975\n| runtime        = 91 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Confessions of a Pop Performer''''' is a 1975 British [[Sex comedy|sex-farce]] film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Confessions of a Pop Performer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/87749/Confessions-of-a-Pop-Performer/overview|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> This second instalment continues the erotic adventures of  Timothy Lea and is based on the novels written under the name by [[Christopher Wood (writer)|Christopher Wood]]. In this case, the original novel was called ''Confessions from the Pop Scene'',<ref>[http://www.trashfiction.co.uk/confessions_of_a_pop_performer_1st_cover.html Trashfiction.co.uk]</ref> but was later re-published under the film's title.<ref>[http://www.trashfiction.co.uk/confessions_of_a_pop_performer_cover.html Trashfiction.co.uk]</ref>\n\n== Premise ==\nSidney overhears a band in his local pub and aspires to be their manager, not so ably assisted by his brother-in-law, Timmy, both still window cleaning for a living. They rename the band Kipper and after a misfortune, Timmy joins the line-up and many sexual encounters follow as a result. Unfortunately, Timmy's natural talent is more mayhem than rock star and disaster ensues of mostly the semi-clothed kind.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Robin Askwith]] .... Timothy Lea \n*[[Tony Booth (actor)|Antony Booth]] .... Sidney Noggett \n*[[Bill Maynard]] .... Mr Lea\n*[[Doris Hare]] .... Mrs Lea \n*[[Sheila White (actress)|Sheila White]] .... Rosie Noggett \n*[[Carol Hawkins]] .... Jill Brown\n*[[Peter Cleall]] .... Nutter Normington\n*[[Bob Todd]] .... Mr Barnwell\n*[[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]] .... Maxy Naus\n*[[Jill Gascoine]] .... Mrs Barnwell\n*[[David Hamilton (broadcasting)|David Hamilton]] .... TV interviewer\n*[[Linda Regan]] .... Brenda Climax\n*[[Diane Langton]] .... Ruby Climax\n*[[Bill Pertwee]] .... Husband with javelin\n*[[Ian Lavender]] .... Rodney\n*[[Robert Dorning]] .... Augustus\n*[[Richard Warwick]]  ....  Petal\n*Sally Harrison .... Patsie\n*Andee Cromarty .... Fanny\n*[[Rita Webb]] .... Fanny's Mother\n*[[Helli Louise]] .... Eva\n*[[Rula Lenska]] .... Receptionist\n*[[David Prowse]] .... Man at Cinema\n\n==Critical Reaction==\n''Confessions of a Pop Performer'' was voted joint \u2018Worst British Film of 1975\u2019 by ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' magazine, tying with ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]''.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nPop Performer was the only film in the series to spawn a soundtrack album on the [[Polydor]] label, with musical numbers produced by [[Ed Welch]], and credited to the film's fictional groups Kipper, and The Climax Sisters (played by Diane Langton and Linda Regan in the film, although Sue Martine provides Regan's singing voice).  The album also includes music from ''[[Confessions of a Window Cleaner]]'' and in-character \u2018Timmy Chat\u2019 from Robin Askwith.\n\n===Soundtrack listing===\n(Original album)\n\nSide 1\n#Confessions of Timmy Tea (Three's a Crowd)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\n#The Clapham (Kipper)\n#Oh Sha La La (Kipper)\n#Accidents will Happen (Kipper)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\n#I Need You (like a hole in the head!) (The Climax Sisters)\n#Kipper (Kipper)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\nSide 2\n#Hell of a Fuss (Teddy Palmer and the Rumble Band)\n#Pop Performer Medley (Fire and Foam, See Though Jazz, The Crash, Timmy Goes Shopping, Theme for Truncheon and Helmet)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\n#This is your Life (Three's a Crowd)\n#Charlie Snowgarden (Sam Sklair)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\n#Confessions of Timmy Tea (reprise) (Three's a Crowd)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0072814}}\n\n{{Confessions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Confessions Of A Pop Performer}}\n[[Category:1975 films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Elstree Studios]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Norman Cohen]]\n[[Category:British sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Christopher Wood (writer)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1975 film by Norman Cohen}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Confessions of a Pop Performer\n| image          = \"Confessions_of_a_Pop_Performer\"_(1975).jpg\n| image_size     =  \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Norman Cohen]]\n| producer       = [[Greg Smith (film producer)|Greg Smith]]<br>[[Michael Klinger (producer)|Michael Klinger]] (executive producer)\n| writer         = [[Christopher Wood (writer)|Christopher Wood]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Robin Askwith]]<br>[[Antony Booth]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Alan Hume]]\n| editing        = [[Geoffrey Foot (film editor)|Geoffrey Foot]]\n| distributor    = [[Columbia pictures]]\n| released       = July 1975\n| runtime        = 91 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Confessions of a Pop Performer''''' is a 1975 British [[Sex comedy|sex-farce]] film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Confessions of a Pop Performer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/87749/Confessions-of-a-Pop-Performer/overview|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> This second instalment continues the erotic adventures of  Timothy Lea and is based on the novels written under the name by [[Christopher Wood (writer)|Christopher Wood]]. In this case, the original novel was called ''Confessions from the Pop Scene'',<ref>[http://www.trashfiction.co.uk/confessions_of_a_pop_performer_1st_cover.html Trashfiction.co.uk]</ref> but was later re-published under the film's title.<ref>[http://www.trashfiction.co.uk/confessions_of_a_pop_performer_cover.html Trashfiction.co.uk]</ref>\n\n== Premise ==\nSidney overhears a band in his local pub and aspires to be their manager, not so ably assisted by his brother-in-law, Timmy, both still window cleaning for a living. They rename the band Kipper and after a misfortune, Timmy joins the line-up and many sexual encounters follow as a result. Unfortunately, Timmy's natural talent is more mayhem than rock star and disaster ensues of mostly the semi-clothed kind.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Robin Askwith]] .... Timothy Lea \n*[[Tony Booth (actor)|Antony Booth]] .... Sidney Noggett \n*[[Bill Maynard]] .... Mr Lea\n*[[Doris Hare]] .... Mrs Lea \n*[[Sheila White (actress)|Sheila White]] .... Rosie Noggett \n*[[Carol Hawkins]] .... Jill Brown\n*[[Peter Cleall]] .... Nutter Normington\n*[[Bob Todd]] .... Mr Barnwell\n*[[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]] .... Maxy Naus\n*[[Jill Gascoine]] .... Mrs Barnwell\n*[[David Hamilton (broadcasting)|David Hamilton]] .... TV interviewer\n*[[Linda Regan]] .... Brenda Climax\n*[[Diane Langton]] .... Ruby Climax\n*[[Bill Pertwee]] .... Husband with javelin\n*[[Ian Lavender]] .... Rodney\n*[[Robert Dorning]] .... Augustus\n*[[Richard Warwick]]  ....  Petal\n*Sally Harrison .... Patsie\n*Andee Cromarty .... Fanny\n*[[Rita Webb]] .... Fanny's Mother\n*[[Helli Louise]] .... Eva\n*[[Rula Lenska]] .... Receptionist\n*[[David Prowse]] .... Man at Cinema\n\n==Critical Reaction==\n''Confessions of a Pop Performer'' was voted joint \u2018Worst British Film of 1975\u2019 by ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' magazine, tying with ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]''.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nPop Performer was the only film in the series to spawn a soundtrack album on the [[Polydor]] label, with musical numbers produced by [[Ed Welch]], and credited to the film\u2019s fictional groups Kipper, and The Climax Sisters (played by Diane Langton and Linda Regan in the film, although Sue Martine provides Regan\u2019s singing voice).  The album also includes music from ''[[Confessions of a Window Cleaner]]'' and in-character \u2018Timmy Chat\u2019 from Robin Askwith.\n\n===Soundtrack listing===\n(Original album)\n\nSide 1\n#Confessions of Timmy Tea (Three\u2019s a Crowd)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\n#The Clapham (Kipper)\n#Oh Sha La La (Kipper)\n#Accidents will Happen (Kipper)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\n#I Need You (like a hole in the head!) (The Climax Sisters)\n#Kipper (Kipper)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\nSide 2\n#Hell of a Fuss (Teddy Palmer and the Rumble Band)\n#Pop Performer Medley (Fire and Foam, See Though Jazz, The Crash, Timmy Goes Shopping, Theme for Truncheon and Helmet)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\n#This is your Life (Three\u2019s a Crowd)\n#Charlie Snowgarden (Sam Sklair)\n#Timmy Chat (Robin Askwith)\n#Confessions of Timmy Tea (reprise) (Three\u2019s a Crowd)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0072814}}\n\n{{Confessions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Confessions Of A Pop Performer}}\n[[Category:1975 films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Elstree Studios]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Norman Cohen]]\n[[Category:British sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Christopher Wood (writer)]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confessions_of_a_Pop_Performer"}
{"title_page": "The Chicken Chronicles", "text_new": "{{short description|1977 film directed by Frank Simon}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Chicken Chronicles\n| image          = The Chicken Chronicles.jpg\n| caption        = film poster\n| director       = [[Frank Simon (director)|Frank Simon]]\n| producer       = [[Walter Shenson]]<br>[[Melvin Simon]] (presenter)\n| writer         = Paul Diamond \n| starring       = [[Phil Silvers]]<br>[[Ed Lauter]]<br>[[Steve Guttenberg]]\n| music          = [[LeRoy Holmes]]<br>[[Ken Lauber]]\n| cinematography = [[Matthew F. Leonetti]]\n| editing        = [[George Folsey Jr.]]    \n| distributor    = [[AVCO Embassy Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1977|10}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''The Chicken Chronicles''''' is a 1977 American [[comedy film]] set in 1969 and starring [[Steve Guttenberg]].<ref>CHICKEN CHRONICLES, The\nMonthly Film Bulletin; London Vol. 48, Iss. 564,  (Jan 1, 1981): 5. </ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nDavid Kessler is a high school student who will go to any lengths to impress a pretty cheerleader and lose his virginity, while juggling his job at a chicken joint and trying not to get thrown out of [[Beverly Hills High]] - a fate that could get him sent to [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]].\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Phil Silvers]] as Max Ober\n*[[Ed Lauter]] as Vice Principal Nastase \n*[[Steve Guttenberg]] as David Kessler \n*[[Lisa Reeves]] as Margaret Shaffer\n*[[Gino Baffa]] as Charlie Kessler\n*[[Meridith Baer]] as Tracy Vogel \n*[[Branscombe Richmond]] as Mark \n*[[Jon Gries]] as Tom \n*[[Raven De La Croix]] as Mrs. Worth\n==Production==\nThe film was based on a novel by Paul Diamond, the 23-year-old son of IAL Diamond. \"It's a very funny very dirty book,\" said Diamond senior.<ref>Diamond in the Rough Screenwriters' World: Diamond in the Rough in Screenwriters' World\nWarga, Wayne. Los Angeles Times 15 Dec 1974: l50. </ref>\n\nFilm rights were sold to Paramount before publication. A screenplay was done by Ned Wynn in 1975 with Paul Monash the producer.<ref>MOVIE CALL SHEET: War to Write, Star in 'Niger'\nMurphy, Mary. Los Angeles Times 16 Aug 1975: b7. </ref> The film was not made. However twoyears later Paul Diamond was working on a script for Avco Embassy.<ref>Case of an intrepid spy-ographer\nLochte, Dick. Los Angeles Times 24 Apr 1977: v2. </ref>\n\nIt was the first lead role for Steve Guttenberg. \"Some actors get embarrassed about their early work,\" Guttenberg said, \"but we all don't start out as 'artistes.' Nobody is going to confuse \"Chicken\" with 'Citizen Kane' but I learned a lot. They took a chance with me. I didn't get rich on it but it was a start.\"<ref>STEVE GUTTENBERG - ACTORS ON EGO TRIPS IRK 'POLICE ACADEMY' STAR\nBlowen, Michael; Boston Globe.7 Apr 1984: 13.</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title.jsp?stid=70781&category=Overview ''The Chicken Chronicles'' at the TCM database.]\n* {{IMDb title|0075836}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the_chicken_chronicles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chicken Chronicles, The}}\n[[Category:1977 films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:Embassy Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about virginity]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Ken Lauber]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1969]]\n[[Category:Films set in Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Teen sex comedy films]]\n\n{{1970s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1977 film directed by Frank Simon}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Chicken Chronicles\n| image          = The Chicken Chronicles.jpg\n| caption        = film poster\n| director       = [[Frank Simon (director)|Frank Simon]]\n| producer       = [[Walter Shenson]]<br>[[Melvin Simon]] (presenter)\n| writer         = Paul Diamond \n| starring       = [[Phil Silvers]]<br>[[Ed Lauter]]<br>[[Steve Guttenberg]]\n| music          = [[LeRoy Holmes]]<br>[[Ken Lauber]]\n| cinematography = [[Matthew F. Leonetti]]\n| editing        = [[George Folsey Jr.]]    \n| distributor    = [[AVCO Embassy Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1977|10}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''The Chicken Chronicles''''' is a 1977 American [[comedy film]] set in 1969 and starring [[Steve Guttenberg]].<ref>CHICKEN CHRONICLES, The\nMonthly Film Bulletin; London Vol. 48, Iss. 564,  (Jan 1, 1981): 5. </ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nDavid Kessler is a high school student who will go to any lengths to impress a pretty cheerleader and lose his virginity, while juggling his job at a chicken joint and trying not to get thrown out of [[Beverly Hills High]] - a fate that could get him sent to [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]].\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Phil Silvers]] as Max Ober\n*[[Ed Lauter]] as Vice Principal Nastase \n*[[Steve Guttenberg]] as David Kessler \n*[[Lisa Reeves]] as Margaret Shaffer\n*[[Gino Baffa]] as Charlie Kessler\n*[[Meridith Baer]] as Tracy Vogel \n*[[Branscombe Richmond]] as Mark \n*[[Jon Gries]] as Tom \n*[[Raven De La Croix]] as Mrs. Worth\n==Production==\nThe film was based on a novel by Paul Diamond, the 23 year old son of IAL Diamond. \"It's a very funny very dirty book,\" said Diamond senior.<ref>Diamond in the Rough Screenwriters' World: Diamond in the Rough in Screenwriters' World\nWarga, Wayne. Los Angeles Times 15 Dec 1974: l50. </ref>\n\nFilm rights were sold to Paramount before publication. A screenplay was done by Ned Wynn in 1975 with Paul Monash the producer.<ref>MOVIE CALL SHEET: War to Write, Star in 'Niger'\nMurphy, Mary. Los Angeles Times 16 Aug 1975: b7. </ref> The film was not made. However twoyears later Paul Diamond was working on a script for Avco Embassy.<ref>Case of an intrepid spy-ographer\nLochte, Dick. Los Angeles Times 24 Apr 1977: v2. </ref>\n\nIt was the first lead role for Steve Guttenberg. \"Some actors get embarrassed about their early work,\" Guttenberg said, \"but we all don't start out as 'artistes.' Nobody is going to confuse \"Chicken\" with 'Citizen Kane' but I learned a lot. They took a chance with me. I didn't get rich on it but it was a start.\"<ref>STEVE GUTTENBERG - ACTORS ON EGO TRIPS IRK 'POLICE ACADEMY' STAR\nBlowen, Michael; Boston Globe.7 Apr 1984: 13.</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title.jsp?stid=70781&category=Overview ''The Chicken Chronicles'' at the TCM database.]\n* {{IMDb title|0075836}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the_chicken_chronicles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chicken Chronicles, The}}\n[[Category:1977 films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:Embassy Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about virginity]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Ken Lauber]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1969]]\n[[Category:Films set in Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Teen sex comedy films]]\n\n{{1970s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 23 year old son \u2192 23-year-old son", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Chicken_Chronicles"}
{"title_page": "Finn B\u00f8", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Finn B\u00f8\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date  |1893|7|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Oslo|Kristiania]], Norway\n| death_date =  {{Death date and age |1962|4|24|1893|7|4|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = Norwegian\n| other_names = \n| education = Chemical engineer\n| alma_mater = [[Norwegian Institute of Technology]]\n| occupation =  Journalist, theatre critic, songwriter, revue writer and playwright \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| home_town = \n| television = \n| religion = \n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| father =  \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n}} \n'''Finn B\u00f8''' (4 July 1893 &ndash; 24 April 1962) was a Norwegian [[songwriter]], [[revue]] writer, playwright, journalist, instructor and [[theatre critic]].\n\n==Career==\nB\u00f8 is particularly remembered for his song \"Norge i r\u00f8dt, hvitt og bl\u00e5tt\", which became extremely popular in 1945. Among his other popular songs are \"N\u00e5 g\u00e5r'n p\u00e5 gummis\u00e5ler\" and \"Bare rundt omkring\", both from 1928. He published the [[anecdote]] collection ''Forbuden frukt'' in 1945, and the song collection ''Jeg tar mig den frihet'' in 1946. Several of his plays were also adapted into film.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Finn Valdemar Johan B\u00f8 |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Finn_Valdemar_Johan_B\u00f8 |language=Norwegian | accessdate=13 July 2010 }}</ref><ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Finn B\u00f8 |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Svend Erik L\u00f8ken |last=Larsen |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Finn_B%C3%B8/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHis parents were Johan Christian Andreas B\u00f8 (1850\u20131924) and Valborg Hansen (1863\u20131910). He married in 1930 to Alfhild Knagenhjelm Poppe.<ref name=\"Store norske leksikon\">{{Cite news|url=https://nbl.snl.no/Finn_B%C3%B8|title=Finn B\u00f8 \u2013 Norsk biografisk leksikon|work=Store norske leksikon|access-date=2017-05-30|language=no}}</ref> He graduated as [[chemical engineer]] from the [[Norwegian Institute of Technology]] in 1916, but from 1920 he mainly worked as writer and journalist.<ref name=nbl/>\n\n==Selected works<ref name=\"Store norske leksikon\"/>==\n\n=== Plays/Revue Comedy ===\n* ''Den enes d\u00f8d'' (sm.m. S. Hoel), 1921\n* ''Du har lovet mig en kone!'', 1934 (filmmanus 1935)\n* ''Hele byen snakker'', 1936 og 1957\n* ''I moralens navn'', 1937\n* ''Det store sp\u00f8rsm\u00e5l'', 1940 (filmmanus ''En herre med bart'', 1942)\n* ''Halmstr\u00e5et'', 1940\n* ''Konge for en natt'', 1940 (filmmanus ''Hansen og Hansen'', 1941)\n* ''Trollfossen'' (filmmanus sm.m. A. Scott-Hansen og S. Hoel), 1948\n* ''To liv'', 1946\n* ''Hele byen flagger'', 1950\n* ''Se deg om i glede'', 1959\n* ''Fordi jeg elsker deg'', 1961\n\n=== Song and Anecdote Collections ===\n* ''Forbuden frukt'', 1945\n* ''Jeg tar meg den frihet'', 1946\n* ''Ondt ord igjen'', 1951\n* ''I Tigerstadens jungel'', 1961\n\n=== Discography(Selection) ===\n* Gamle revyviser (div. artister), 1978\n* Lalla Carlsen, 1989\n* Einar Rose: Landskampen, 1994\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boe, Finn}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Oslo]]\n[[Category:Norwegian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Norwegian journalists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian theatre critics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Norwegian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n\n{{Norway-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Finn B\u00f8\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date  |1893|7|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Oslo|Kristiania]], Norway\n| death_date =  {{Death date and age |1962|4|24|1893|7|4|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = Norwegian\n| other_names = \n| education = Chemical engineer\n| alma_mater = [[Norwegian Institute of Technology]]\n| occupation =  Journalist, theatre critic, songwriter, revue writer and playwright \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| home_town = \n| television = \n| religion = \n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| father =  \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n}} \n'''Finn B\u00f8''' (4 July 1893 &ndash; 24 April 1962) was a Norwegian [[songwriter]], [[revue]] writer, playwright, journalist, instructor and [[theatre critic]].\n\n==Career==\nB\u00f8 is particularly remembered for his song \"Norge i r\u00f8dt, hvitt og bl\u00e5tt\", which became extremely popular in 1945. Among his other popular songs are \"N\u00e5 g\u00e5r'n p\u00e5 gummis\u00e5ler\" and \"Bare rundt omkring\", both from 1928. He published the [[anecdote]] collection ''Forbuden frukt'' in 1945, and the song collection ''Jeg tar mig den frihet'' in 1946. Several of his plays were also adapted into film.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Finn Valdemar Johan B\u00f8 |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Finn_Valdemar_Johan_B\u00f8 |language=Norwegian | accessdate=13 July 2010 }}</ref><ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Finn B\u00f8 |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Svend Erik L\u00f8ken |last=Larsen |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Finn_B%C3%B8/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHis parents were Johan Christian Andreas B\u00f8 (1850\u20131924) and Valborg Hansen (1863\u20131910). He married in 1930 to Alfhild Knagenhjelm Poppe.<ref name=\"Store norske leksikon\">{{Cite news|url=https://nbl.snl.no/Finn_B%C3%B8|title=Finn B\u00f8 \u2013 Norsk biografisk leksikon|work=Store norske leksikon|access-date=2017-05-30|language=no}}</ref> He graduated as [[chemical engineer]] from the [[Norwegian Institute of Technology]] in 1916, but from 1920 he mainly worked as writer and journalist.<ref name=nbl/>\n\n==Selected works<ref name=\"Store norske leksikon\"/>==\n\n=== Plays/Revue Comedy ===\n* ''Den enes d\u00f8d'' (sm.m. S. Hoel), 1921\n* ''Du har lovet mig en kone!'', 1934 (filmmanus 1935)\n* ''Hele byen snakker'', 1936 og 1957\n* ''I moralens navn'', 1937\n* ''Det store sp\u00f8rsm\u00e5l'', 1940 (filmmanus ''En herre med bart'', 1942)\n* ''Halmstr\u00e5et'', 1940\n* ''Konge for en natt'', 1940 (filmmanus ''Hansen og Hansen'', 1941)\n* ''Trollfossen'' (filmmanus sm.m. A. Scott-Hansen og S. Hoel), 1948\n* ''To liv'', 1946\n* ''Hele byen flagger'', 1950\n* ''Se deg om i glede'', 1959\n* ''Fordi jeg elsker deg'', 1961\n\n=== Song and Anecdote Collections ===\n* ''Forbuden frukt'', 1945\n* ''Jeg tar meg den frihet'', 1946\n* ''Ondt ord igjen'', 1951\n* ''I Tigerstadens jungel'', 1961\n\n=== Discography(Selection) ===\n* Gamle revyviser (div. artister), 1978\n* Lalla Carlsen, 1989\n* Einar Rose: Landskampen, 1994\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boe, Finn}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Oslo]]\n[[Category:Norwegian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Norwegian journalists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian theatre critics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n\n\n{{Norway-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRefer